ritish Gangland Saga is Back on Netflix |last=Grey |first=Tobias |date=30 May 2016 |newspaper=Wall Street Journal |issn=0099-9660 |accessdate=31 May 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160530125842/http://www.wsj.com/articles/peaky-blinders-season-3-the-british-gangland-saga-is-back-on-netflix-1464609602 |archive-date=30 May 2016}}</ref> Due to licensing restrictions, however, most of the show's original soundtrack is not available on the Netflix-distributed version of the series.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-blogs/peaky-blinders-10-perfectly-anachronistic-soundtrack-choices |title=10 Perfect Choices on the Peaky Blinders Soundtrack |last=Bartleet |first=Larry |date=10 May 2016 |newspaper=[[NME]] |accessdate=15 July 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160713134400/http://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-blogs/peaky-blinders-10-perfectly-anachronistic-soundtrack-choices |archive-date=13 July 2016}}</ref> In 2018, it was announced ''Peaky Blinders'' would be moved from its original broadcast channel, [[BBC Two]], to [[BBC One]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.express.co.uk/showbiz/tv-radio/879873/Peaky-Blinders-season-5-release-date-cast-plo-When-is-the-series-released-BBC-Netflix |title=Peaky Blinders season 5 release date, cast, plot: When is the new series released? |last=Debnath |first=Neela |date=6 December 2018 |work=Daily Express |language=en |access-date=17 December 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181218102051/https://www.express.co.uk/showbiz/tv-radio/879873/Peaky-Blinders-season-5-release-date-cast-plo-When-is-the-series-released-BBC-Netflix |archive-date=18 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n[https://www.academia.edu/24202294/_Class_Place_and_History_in_the_Imaginative_Landscapes_of_Peaky_Blinders_ Long, Paul (2017) \u2018Class, Place and History in the Imaginative Landscapes of Peaky Blinders\u2019 in Forrest, D. & Johnson, B. (eds.), Social Class and Television Drama in Contemporary Britain, Palgrave]\n\n==External links==\n* {{BBC programme}}\n* {{URL|https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b045fz8r|''Peaky Blinders''}} on [[BBC]]\u2014The official website for the series in the United Kingdom.\n* {{URL|https://www.netflix.com/title/80002479|''Peaky Blinders''}} on [[Netflix]]\u2014The official website for the series in the United States.\n* {{IMDb title|id=2442560|title=Peaky Blinders}}\u2014A user-generated database of information related to the series.\n\n{{Steven Knight}}\n{{BAFTA TV Award for Best Drama Series}}\n\n{{Subject bar|portal1=Television|portal23=United Kingdom|portal2=BBC|commons=yes|commons-search=Category:Peaky Blinders (TV series)|q=yes|d=yes|d-search=Q14944179}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Peaky Blinders (Tv Series)}}\n[[Category:2010s British drama television series]]\n[[Category:2013 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:BBC television dramas]]\n[[Category:British crime drama television series]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Winston Churchill]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Oswald Mosley]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Gangs in fiction]]\n[[Category:Serial drama television series]]\n[[Category:Television series by Endemol]]\n[[Category:Television series by Tiger Aspect Productions]]\n[[Category:Television series set in the 1910s]]\n[[Category:Television series set in the 1920s]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Birmingham, West Midlands]]\n[[Category:Television series about organized crime]]\n[[Category:Television series created by Steven Knight]]\n", "name_user": "Kailash29792", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peaky_Blinders_(TV_series)"}
{"title_page": "Michael McConnell and Jack Baker", "text_new": "{{other people||Jack Baker (disambiguation)}}\n{{Cleanup|reason=odd colors and fonts need to be removed, citations need to be standardized, spurious bold removed, citations checked (too many are primay), general layout and organization: article is laid out as a timeline--of what? the lead doesn't even clarify what the subject is, and the first sentence doesn't comply with MOS|date=March 2020}}\n[[File:MikeMcConnellJackBaker.jpg|thumb|Husbands Mike McConnell (left) and Jack Baker in 2016]]\n'''Michael McConnell''', [[Timeline_of_same-sex_marriage#1970s | librarian]], and '''Jack Baker''', [[Timeline_of_same-sex_marriage#1970s | law student]], were married<ref name=\"Marriage law\"> 1970: \"Minnesota Statutes Annotated\", ''West Publishing&nbsp;Co.''\n* Chapter&nbsp;517.01: '''Marriage a civil contract'''. \"Marriage, so far as its validity in law is concerned, is a civil contract, to which the consent of the parties, capable in law of contracting, is essential.\" \n* Chapter&nbsp;517.03: '''Marriages prohibited'''. [The list does not include parties of the same gender.]</ref> in the U.S. state of [[Minnesota]] on 3&nbsp;September&nbsp;1971.\n\nBoth were activists in Minnesota from 1969 to 1980. They were invited often to appear publicly in the US and Canada at college events, schools, businesses, churches, etc.<ref>See: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;2c and 2d], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> \n\nHistorians insisted that they became the \"first same-sex couple in history to be legally married\".<ref name=Kraemer /> Specifically, the decision of [[Baker_v._Nelson#Facts_and_trial | Minnesota's Supreme Court]] in 1971 [[Baker_v._Nelson | did \"not reach back]] to Baker and McConnell\" since the two obtained their license and were married \"a full six weeks\"<ref name=FLR /> previously. The National Archives came to the same conclusion.<ref name=Archives>Anon., \"Hidden Treasures from the Stacks: pushing for equality\", ''The&nbsp;National Archives at Kansas City'', September&nbsp;2013, 7; [https://www.archives.gov/kansas-city/press/newsletter/2013-september.pdf#page=7 available online]</ref>\n\n==Student activism==\n\nWeeks before the 1969 [[Stonewall riots]], two activists and local friends organize a team called \"Fight Repression of Erotic Expression\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://collections.mnhs.org/cms/display?irn=10262356|title=Twin Cities Gay and Lesbian Community Oral History Project: Interview with Koreen Phelps : Collections Online : mnhs.org|website=collections.mnhs.org|access-date=2019-06-05}}</ref> as part of an outreach program sponsored by MINNESOTA FREE UNIVERSITY.<ref>Program offices were located in the Cedar Riverside Neighborhood of '''Minneapolis''', at 529&nbsp;Cedar&nbsp;Avenue, near the U of Minnesota's expanding campus on the West&nbsp;Bank of the Mississippi.\n* See: K.A.&nbsp;Phelps, \"The Homosexual Revolution\", ''MINNESOTA FREE UNIVERSITY'', 18&nbsp;'''May'''&nbsp;1969; Bulletin&nbsp;No.&nbsp;5, New Courses [final entry].\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;1a&nbsp;-&nbsp;d], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> \n\n* '''May''': Robert Halfhill, a graduate student with interest in their proposal, leaves the neighborhood lectures to form an independent group called \"FREE\" on the [[University of Minnesota|Minneapolis campus]] of the University of Minnesota.<ref name=Halfhill>Bruce Johasen, \"Out of Silence\", Minnesota History, Spring&nbsp;2019:\n* \"Halfhill steered the group through the administrative channels needed to establish FREE as a student group, 189. Lack of interest by women \"was always a bitter disappointment\" for Phelps, 188, who was \"really angry\" with demands for \"the right to get married\", 194;\n* Also: McConnell Files, \"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\" [Binder #7, MEMORANDUM for the record], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''. On page 1:\n* \"Timidity and confusion\" tired Halfhill. \"He left to organize an independent coalition of activists on the East Bank campus.\"</ref> Those attending his meetings elect [[Timeline_of_same-sex_marriage#1970s|Jack Baker, a law student]],<ref>Jack Baker, while a law student, was \n* president of FREE (1969), and\n* later, a student body president on \n* the Minneapolis campuses of \n* the University of Minnesota, \n* [elected 1971, re-elected 1972]</ref> to serve as president.<ref>Neal R. Peirce, \"The Great Plains States of America: People, Politics, and Power in the Nine Great Plains States\", ''George&nbsp;J. McLeod'' (1973), 145; [https://books.google.com/books?id=JyqbTl9fsc4C&pg=PA145& available online], accessed February 7, 2014</ref> \n\n* '''November''': A faculty committee qualifies FREE for all privileges enjoyed by student organizations.<ref name=dynes>Wayne R. Dynes, \"Homosexuality and Government, Politics and Prisons\" (1992), 248; [https://books.google.com/books?id=wegoALly5DEC&pg=PA244& available online], accessed February 7, 2012</ref> As the \"the first student gay organization to gain recognition in the upper mid-west,\"<ref name= FREE>\"Minnesota Hosts First Legally Sanctioned Same-Sex Marriage\"\n* '''For Release''', ''Minnesota Student Association'', 7&nbsp;September&nbsp;1971.\n* also, '''for immediate release''', ''FREE'', 17&nbsp;May&nbsp;1970.\n* and, '''News from''', ''Fight Repression of Erotic Expression'', 1&nbsp;November&nbsp;1969\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;1a&nbsp;-&nbsp;d], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> interest in FREE expands quickly. Its \"leaders believe it to be the first such organization on a Big Ten campus\", the second such organization in the United States, following the [[Student Homophile League]]<ref>Merged later with the [[Columbia Queer Alliance]].</ref> recognized by [[Columbia University]] in 1967.<ref>{{cite news|last=Schumach|first=Murray|title=Columbia Charters Homosexual Group|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1967/05/03/107188654.pdf|accessdate=July 23, 2013|newspaper=New York Times|date=May 3, 1967}}</ref>\n\n'''1970''': Moving openly and aggressively, FREE slowly transforms [[Minneapolis]].<ref name=Coverage>On page&nbsp;13: \"A mecca for gays\", in a story by\n* Lily Hansen, ''GAY'', \"F.R.E.E. At Last\", 11&nbsp;May&nbsp;1970.  \n* also, \"Three big companies say they hire Gays\", ''The&nbsp;Advocate'', 30&nbsp;September&nbsp;1970.\n* and, Ken Bronson, \"A Quest for Full Equality\", 2004; [https://www.lib.umn.edu/sites/default/files/media/Quest%20copy.pdf#page=9 available online] from ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;1a&nbsp;-&nbsp;d], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> \n\n* One member asks five major companies to explain their attitudes toward gay men and women.<ref name=Coverage /> Three large companies respond quickly, insisting that they did not discriminate against homosexuals in their hiring policies.<ref name=Coverage /> [[Honeywell]] objects:<ref name=Honeywell>An inquiry about employment of homosexuals generates a response from Gerry&nbsp;E. Morse, Vice President, ''Honeywell&nbsp;Inc.''. \n* See: letter to '''FREE''', addressed to James&nbsp;W. Chesebro, 29&nbsp;June&nbsp;1970.\n* and: Lars Bjornson, \"A quiet win: Honeywell yields\", ''The Advocate'', 10&nbsp;April&nbsp;1974, 13.\n* Courtesy: Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;1a&nbsp;-&nbsp;d], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> \"We would not employ a known homosexual.\" That member expands his surveys as complaints surface.\n\n* Another member is eager to educate his parents. For credit, he selects a program requested by Dave Moore, then a popular announcer on WCCO-TV. The student is proud of what ultimately airs on Sunday, 30&nbsp;September 1973.<ref>Review the FREE member's course work, including words to his parents.\n* Courtesy: \"Human Relations\", ''University Media Resources''\n* {{YouTube|id=mOwGW-Jie7E&feature=c4-overview&list=UU0ClfyXL_loos5QtXwPhMhQ|title=available online}}\n* Posted by Brandon Wolf </ref> \n\n* Members vote to endorse<ref name=FREE /> [[Timeline_of_same-sex_marriage#1970s|\"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\"]].<ref name=memoir>Memoir of Michael McConnell, as told to Gail Langer Karwoski, \"The Wedding Heard 'Round the World: America's First Gay Marriage,\" ''University of Minnesota Press'', 2016</ref><ref name=Halfhill />\n\n'''1972''': FREE continues working with a faculty committee to craft a new policy that would protect gay students from discrimination.<ref name=policy>See: letter to Jack Baker et al., from\n* Malcolm Moos, President, ''University of Minnesota'', 11&nbsp;February&nbsp;1971.  \"I appreciate your willingness to serve on the Campus Committee on Placement Services\";\n* also: Gary Urban, \"Complaint charges Honeywell discrimination\", ''Minnesota Daily'', 12&nbsp;March&nbsp;1973, 8; \n* Courtesy: Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;1a&nbsp;-&nbsp;d], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> \n\n* '''May''': Central Administration approves a final draft.<ref name=policy /> \n\n* Campus Committee on Placement Services accepts complaints of unequal treatment by employers recruiting on campus. \n\n'''1974''': When faced with a denial of access to students, Honeywell \"quietly reverses its hiring policy\".<ref name=Honeywell /> No longer would it refuse to employ students who were openly gay.\n\n===Gay Pride===\n'''1971''': After the Stonewall Rebellion \u2013 New York City, 1969<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/04/us/stonewall-riots-gay-pride.html|title=50 Years Later, What We Forgot About Stonewall|last=Salam|first=Maya|date=2019-06-04|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-06-05|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/ston/index.htm|title=Stonewall National Monument (U.S. National Park Service)|last=York|first=Mailing Address: 26 Wall Street Federal Hall National Monument c/o Stonewall National Monument New|last2=Us|first2=NY 10005 Phone: 212-668-2577 Contact|website=www.nps.gov|language=en|access-date=2019-06-05}}</ref> \u2013 members of FREE from ''Gay&nbsp;House'' promote self-pride with picnics in Loring Park, near Downtown Minneapolis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://collections.mnhs.org/cms/display?irn=10262356|title=Twin Cities Gay and Lesbian Community Oral History Project: Interview with Koreen Phelps : Collections Online : mnhs.org|website=collections.mnhs.org|access-date=2019-06-05}}</ref> Thom Higgins<ref name=Pride>A monk turned gay activist.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\" [Binder #7, MEMORANDUM for the record], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> crafts \"Gay Pride\" as a chant to discredit the two terms often condemned as \"sins\" by the Catholic archbishop for Minneapolis and Saint Paul. \n\n'''2018''': \"The wrenching bankruptcy that forced a reckoning on the Archdiocese of St. Paul and Minneapolis for decades of clergy sexual abuse has culminated in a $230 million settlement for roughly 450 victims, the largest of its kind nationwide.\"<ref>Victims' attorney Jeff Anderson is overcome with emotion.\n* Staff writers, \"$210 in Atonement\", ''Star&nbsp;Tribune'', 1&nbsp;June&nbsp;2018,&nbsp;A1\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volume&nbsp;8b], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref>\n\n===Student Body President===\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Shoes poster 1971.tif|thumb|right|1971 election poster]]  -->\n'''1971''': Baker campaigned to become president of the Minnesota Student Association<ref name=\"Student Body President\">A student body president known by different names; elected 1971, re-elected 1972. \n* March&nbsp;1942: Richard John Baker, Certificate of Birth \n* September&nbsp;1969: Jack Baker, name adopted to lead activists demanding gay equality \n* August&nbsp;1971: Pat&nbsp;Lyn McConnell, married name; by Decree of Adoption \n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;6a&nbsp;-&nbsp;b], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''\n* also, Kay Tobin and Randy Wicker, \"The&nbsp;Gay Crusaders\", ''Paperback Library'', New&nbsp;York:&nbsp;1972, 136</ref> on the U&nbsp;of&nbsp;M's Minneapolis campus. \"''Student Control over Student Concerns''\",<ref name=Platform>Platform for student body president \n* Jack Baker, \"Policy Statement\", March&nbsp;1971\n* Endorsed by ''Minnesota Daily'', \"Baker for MSA president\", 5&nbsp;April&nbsp;1971,&nbsp;page&nbsp;4. \"He has spoken truth to power because he knows the power of truth.\"\n* After graduation, the Governor signed into law a bill reserving one seat on the Board of Regents for an enrolled student.</ref> urged students \"to search out a new self-respect.\"<ref name=\"Student Body President\" /> Thoughtful posters with a focus on [https://box8661.blogspot.com/2013/06/marriage-equality-was-inevitable.htm self-pride] helped his election,<ref name=election>A total of 6,024 ballots cast topped the previous record of 5,049 in the 1958 election.\n* See: Steve Brandt, \"Baker wins in record vote,\" ''Minnesota Daily'', 8&nbsp;April&nbsp;1971,&nbsp;1\n* and, Gary Dawson, \"Homosexual Credits U Election Victory to a New Sophistication\", ''St.&nbsp;Paul Dispatch'', 8&nbsp;April&nbsp;1971,&nbsp;35\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;6a&nbsp;-&nbsp;b], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> and re-election. <ref name=re-election>It was \"the first time in the 121-year history of the U&nbsp;of&nbsp;M that a student body president has been re-elected.\"\n* See: Vic Stoner, \"Baker, Schwartz win MSA election\", ''Minnesota Daily'', 7&nbsp;April&nbsp;1972,&nbsp;1\n* and, Associated Press, \"Law senior elected U. student president\", ''Austin Daily Herald'', 7&nbsp;April&nbsp;1972,&nbsp;p.&nbsp;?\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;6a&nbsp;-&nbsp;b], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref>\n\n* \"We need a student on the Board of Regents,\" he insisted. No need to wait for a new law.<ref name=Platform /> \"The Regents already have the power to appoint students to all committees of the Board or Regents.\" \n\n* Baker captured 2,766&nbsp;votes;<ref name=election /> two competitors and write-in candidates split the remainder. \n\n* As student body president, Baker continued to question why the Board of Regents ignored students when making its decisions. Soon, one non-voting student was invited to sit with the regents at each committee meeting.<ref name=Platform /> \n\n'''1972''': Re-elected with \"3,035 votes out of a record turnout of 7,441\"<ref name=re-election /> \u2013 41% in a 3-way race.\n\n== Same-sex marriage activism ==\n\n===Lawsuit to obtain a licence===\n{{Main|Baker v. Nelson}}\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:McConnell (l) and Baker (r) apply for marriage license 19700518.png|thumb|right|Michael McConnell (l) and Jack Baker (18&nbsp;May&nbsp;1970) - by R. Bertrand Heine, Minnesota&nbsp;Historical&nbsp;Society]]  -->\n\n'''1970''': Minnesota's statutes do not explicitly forbid marriage between two adult men.<ref name=\"Marriage law\" /> Baker, a law student, argues that \"[[Everything which is not forbidden is allowed|what is not forbidden is permitted]]\"<ref>Jack Baker, as told to Helen Barrett, \"We had America's first gay marriage - in 1971\", ''Financial Times Magazine'', 7&nbsp;August&nbsp;2015; [https://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/9d35d5d8-3ae4-11e5-bbd1-b37bc06f590c.html available online]</ref> when the couple applies for a marriage license in Minneapolis.<ref name=\"Marriage law\" /> The Clerk of District Court<ref>18 May: Fourth Judicial District, in Minneapolis; [[Hennepin County Government Center|Hennepin County]], Minnesota</ref>, Gerald Nelson, denies their request. Refusal by the [[Baker_v._Nelson#Facts_and_trial|lower courts]] to order Nelson to issue a license<ref>All claims were dismissed.\n* See: Associated Press, \"Marriage Is Out\", ''Kansas&nbsp;City Star'', 24&nbsp;May&nbsp;1970,&nbsp;30A\n* and, \"Gay Marriage Plea Is Denied\", ''St.&nbsp;Paul Pioneer Press'', 19&nbsp;November&nbsp;1970,&nbsp;27\n* and, \"Court Won't Let Men Wed\", ''N.Y.&nbsp;Times'', 10&nbsp;Jan.&nbsp;1971, 65\n* also, Appellant's Jurisdictional Statement, ''[[Baker_v._Nelson]]'', Minnesota Supreme Court docket no.&nbsp;71-1027, at 3&nbsp;-&nbsp;4 (statement of the case)</ref> is affirmed by the [[Baker_v._Nelson#Appeal_to_the_Minnesota_Supreme_Court|Minnesota Supreme Court]].<ref>\"The institution of marriage as a union of man and woman, uniquely involving the procreation or rearing of children within a family, is as old as the book of Genesis\".\n* \"Opinion\", by Justice C.&nbsp;Donald Peterson, ''[[Baker v. Nelson]]'', 15&nbsp;Oct&nbsp;1971, 191&nbsp;N.W.2d&nbsp;185 at&nbsp;186.</ref>\n\n* Leadership inside the [[American Civil Liberties Union]] shows \"little or no enthusiasm\" for support.<ref>Letter from Norman Dorsen (General Counsel for ''ACLU'' in 1970),\n* published by Jason Smith, \"Gay Pride Block Party Case\", ''Friends of the Bill of Rights Foundation'', January&nbsp;2012,&nbsp;52 \n* [https://www.lib.umn.edu/pdf/rare/gayprideblockparty.pdf#page=54 available online]\n* Courtesy: ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> Court rules in effect allows the '''''Minnesota Civil Liberties Union''''' to appeal Minnesota's \"opinion\" directly to the [[Baker_v._Nelson#Appeal_to_the_U.S._Supreme_Court|U.S. Supreme Court]].<ref name=NYT051715>{{cite news |last=Eckholm |first=Eric|title=The Same-Sex Couple Who Got a Marriage License in 1971|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/17/us/the-same-sex-couple-who-got-a-marriage-license-in-1971.html|accessdate=May 17, 2015|newspaper=The New York Times|date=May 16, 2015}}</ref>  \n\n* Allan Spear, a U_of_M professor of history, describes them as the \"lunatic fringe\".<ref>David von Drehle, \"Gay Marriage Already Won\", ''TIME'', 8&nbsp;April&nbsp;2013,&nbsp;22</ref>  \n\n* The case receives extensive media attention,<ref name=letters+>See, a matrix of items (late 1960s, 1970s, early 1980),\n* especially, Jack Star, \"The Homosexual Couple,\" ''LOOK'', 26&nbsp;January&nbsp;1971,&nbsp;69&nbsp;-&nbsp;71\n* and, Michael Durham, \"Homosexuals in revolt\", ''LIFE'', 31&nbsp;December&nbsp;1971,&nbsp;68\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Gift&nbsp;#6, the marriage that made history\", Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> including appearances on the ''[[Phil Donahue Show]]'',<ref name=comdon>{{cite news |last=Condon |first=Patrick|title=Minn. gay couple in '71 marriage case still joined|url=http://minnesota.publicradio.org/display/web/2012/12/10/news/jack-baker-michael-mcconnell-same-sex-marriage|accessdate=March 20, 2013|newspaper=Minnesota Public Radio|date=December 10, 2012}}</ref> and Kennedy&nbsp;&amp;&nbsp;Co. (WLS-TV, Chicago&nbsp;IL). On the ''[[David Susskind Show]]''<ref>[http://minnesota.publicradio.org/display/web/2013/05/15/old-video Available online] from Sasha Aslanian, \"Gay rights pioneers Jack Baker and Michael McConnell predicted marriage victory in '70s\", ''Minnesota Public Radio'' (16&nbsp;May&nbsp;2013)</ref> (New&nbsp;York,&nbsp;NY), Baker is blunt.<ref name=Bowes /> \"We're gonna win eventually, not this time but maybe the next time around.\" \n\n'''1972''': The clerk for Justice Harry Blackmun crafts a one-sentence rejection because \"I just [didn't] think the court was ready at the time to take on the issue.\"<ref>Jess Bravin, \"Supreme Court Clerk Remembers First Same-Sex Marriage Case\", ''The Wall Street Journal'', 1&nbsp;May&nbsp;2015; [https://www.wsj.com/articles/supreme-court-clerk-remembers-first-same-sex-marriage-case-1430494015 available online]</ref><ref name=greenhouse /> A quick dismissal of ''[[Baker v. Nelson]]'' is approved unanimously. \n\n'''2015''': The high court allows lower courts to supervise a national debate before deciding that its decision to dismiss demands for marriage equality must be overruled.<ref>\"The Court now holds that same-sex couples may exercise the fundamental right to marry.\"\n* ''Obergefell&nbsp;v. Hodges,'' 26&nbsp;June&nbsp;2015, at&nbsp;22-23 \n* [https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/14pdf/14-556_3204.pdf#page=28 available online]</ref>\n\n* Gay Marriage is \"rejected by early gay activists [in New&nbsp;York City] who were mostly interested in sexual freedom and gay liberation.\"<ref>Thomas Kraemer, \"Jack Baker deserves mainstream press coverage after gay marriage ruling\", ''Tom's&nbsp;OSU'', 7&nbsp;July&nbsp;2012; [http://tomsosu.blogspot.com/2012/07/jack-baker-deserves-mainstream-press.html available online]</ref>\n\n* Gay \"historians\" ignore Minnesota because they \"personally had political objections to gay marriage activism.\"<ref>Minnesotans document gay history:\n* See: Thomas Kraemer [Professor], \"Gay marriage pioneer Jack Baker starts blog\", ''Tom's&nbsp;OSU'', 4&nbsp;April&nbsp;2012; [https://tomsosu.blogspot.com/2012/04/gay-marriage-pioneer-jack-baker-starts.html available online]\n* also, Jack Baker [Attorney], \"A court corrupted\"; [https://box8661.blogspot.com/2015/03/a-court-corrupted.html available online]</ref>\n\n===A civil right===\n'''1970''': [[Timeline_of_same-sex_marriage#1970s|McConnell and Baker]] apply for a license to marry.<ref>18 May: Fourth Judicial District, in Minneapolis; Hennepin County, Minnesota</ref> The Clerk of District Court rejects their request.<ref name=\"517.03\">1970: Minnesota's marriage statute \u2013 Minn.St. c. 517.03 \u2013 did not include parties of the same gender in its list of \"Marriages prohibited\"</ref> \n\n'''1971''': McConnell re-applies in a different county and receives a marriage license.<ref>16 August: Clerk of District Court, Fifth Judicial District, in Mankato \n* 3 September: At a ceremony in Minneapolis, Hennepin County, a United Methodist minister certifies the marriage contract.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\" [binder #7], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> Their wedding is proclaimed to be [[Timeline_of_same-sex_marriage#1970s|\"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\"]].<ref name=memoir /> Skeptics are silenced in '''2018''' when Assistant Chief Judge Gregory Anderson rules that \"The marriage is declared to be in all respects valid.\"<ref name=ruling>McConnells against Blue Earth County, \u201cCONCLUSIONS OF LAW\u201d, Fifth Judicial District, File&nbsp;#07-CV-16-4559, 18&nbsp;September&nbsp;2018. \n* \"The September&nbsp;3,&nbsp;1971 marriage of James&nbsp;Michael McConnell and Pat&nbsp;Lyn McConnell, a/k/a Richard&nbsp;John Baker, has never been dissolved or annulled by judicial decree and no grounds currently exist on which to invalidate the marriage.\" \n* [https://www.lib.umn.edu/sites/default/files/media/McConnellvBlueEarthCounty-17-Sept-2018-ConclusionsofLaw_ORDER.pdf#page=4 Available online] from U of Minnesota Libraries.\n* Courtesy: McConnell&nbsp;Files, \"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\" [binder&nbsp;#4], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref>\n\nBaker is invited to address members of the Ramsey County Bar Association. Same-sex unions are \"not only authorized by the U.S. Constitution\"<ref>Bob Protzman, \"Gay Marriage OK Predicted\", ''St.&nbsp;Paul Pioneer&nbsp;Press'', 22&nbsp;October&nbsp;1971, p&nbsp;?</ref> but are mandatory. \"I&nbsp;am convinced\", he explains, \"that same-sex marriages will be legalized in the United States.\"\n\n'''1972''': Baker speaks to a forum of more than 2,000 at the [[University of Winnipeg]]. \"We maintain,\" he explained, \"that it's a matter of equity and fair play that if a state is going to give childless heterosexual couples rights and benefits under the law, they can't complain when childless same-sex couples ask for the same rights.\"<ref name=\"Canada\">Persistence spread first to Canada, than worldwide.\n* See: Jack Baker, \"The right to be human and gay\", ''Manitoban'', 13&nbsp;March&nbsp;1972,\n* as reprinted by Ken Bronson in \"A Quest for Full Equality\", 2004, 69,  \n* [https://www.lib.umn.edu/sites/default/files/media/Quest%20copy.pdf#page=73 available online] from ''University  of Minnesota Libraries'';\n* also, Mia Rabson, \"Couple helped make history\", ''Winnipeg Free&nbsp;Press'', 17&nbsp;September&nbsp;2004, A4 and \n* letter from Rich North to Jack [Baker] & Mike [McConnell], 20&nbsp;September&nbsp;2004); [http://box8661.blogspot.com/2012/04/letter-from-canada-2.html available online].\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;6a&nbsp;-&nbsp;b], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> The lecture persuades Richard North to begin a \"fight to be married\" to Chris Vogel.<ref name=Canada /> His persistence leads to marriage equality in [[Canada]] during '''2004'''.<ref name= Canada />\n\n'''2012''': Demands for same-sex marriage continue to grow worldwide, becoming \"the civil rights issue of our times\".<ref name=\"never in doubt\">Lecture by NAACP President Benjamin Todd Jealous, during a news conference at the organization's national headquarters.\n* Michael&nbsp;K. Lavers, \"NAACP president: Marriage is '''civil rights issue of our times'''\" ''Washington Blade'', 21&nbsp;May&nbsp;2012; [http://www.washingtonblade.com/2012/05/21/naacp-president-marriage-is-civil-rights-issue-of-our-times/ available online]\n* also, Patrick Condon, \"Gay couple in 1971 marriage ruling reflect on new court challenges\", ''Associated Press,'' as reprinted in the ''St.&nbsp;Paul Pioneer&nbsp;Press'', 11&nbsp;December&nbsp;2012, 3A+.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;7a&nbsp;-&nbsp;e], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> Speaking to the ''Associated Press'', Baker explained that the \"outcome was never in doubt because the conclusion was intuitively obvious to a first-year law student.\"<ref name=\"never in doubt\" />\n\n'''2015''': As Baker predicted, same-sex marriage is [[Baker_v._Nelson|legalized nationwide]].\n\n=== Adoption, name change, marriage ===\n'''1971''': McConnell legally adopts<ref>FINDINGS AND DECREE [File No.&nbsp;AD-19962], 3&nbsp;August&nbsp;1971\n* Order signed by Judge Lindsay&nbsp;G. Arthur, Juvenile Division\n* Fourth Judicial District, in Minneapolis; Hennepin County, Minnesota\n* See: Anon., \"U student head adopted by homosexual friend\", ''Minneapolis Tribune'', 25&nbsp;August&nbsp;1971,&nbsp;1A\n* also, Associated Press, \"Male's adoption by roommate OKd\", ''Rocky Mountain News'', Denver, 26&nbsp;August&nbsp;1971,&nbsp;85\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\" [Binder&nbsp;#3, file&nbsp;#2], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> Baker because \"regardless of popular conception, adoption is not limited to children\". Baker's legal name changes to Pat Lyn McConnell.\n\n* '''August''': Baker and McConnell visit friends in [[Mankato]]. While there, McConnell applies and receives a marriage license.<ref name=\"Free Press\">Issued by the Clerk of District Court, in [[Mankato]], Fifth Judicial District, [[Blue Earth County]] \n* See: \"Daily Record\", ''Mankato&nbsp;Free Press'', 16&nbsp;August&nbsp;1971, p.&nbsp;?\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\" [binder&nbsp;#7], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> \n\n* '''September''': Rev. Roger Lynn, a [[United Methodist]] minister, validates their marriage contract.<ref name=Bowes>\"Pastor Roger Lynn holds up Baker and McConnell's marriage certificate\"\n* Claire Bowes, \"Jack Baker and Michael McConnell: Gay&nbsp;Americans who married in 1971\", ''BBC&nbsp;News Magazine'', 3&nbsp;July&nbsp;2013 \n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-23159390 available online]. \n* A United Methodist minister officiated at a ceremony in Minneapolis, Hennepin County.</ref><ref name=FREE /> \n\n'''1972''': The Hennepin County Attorney convenes a grand jury, which \"studied the legality of the marriage but found the question not worth pursuing.\"<ref>\"Thus the marriage remained in effect.\"\n* See: \"Homosexual Wins Fight to Take Bar Examination in Minnesota\", ''New York Times'', 7&nbsp;January&nbsp;1973, 55. </ref>\n\n'''1974''': ''The&nbsp;Family Law Reporter''<ref name=FLR>Anon., \"Gay married couple frustrated in adoption bid\", ''The&nbsp;Family Law Reporter'', published by The&nbsp;Bureau of National Affairs, 10&nbsp;December&nbsp;1974, page&nbsp;2103</ref> argues that the \"federal constitution prohibition against ex post facto laws .&nbsp;.&nbsp;. forbids the imposition of punishment for past conduct lawful at the time it was engaged\".<ref name=\"Marriage law\" /> Hence, the Minnesota high court's opinion \u2013 ''[[ Baker v. Nelson]]'' \u2013 does not reach back to Baker and McConnell because the two were married \"a full six weeks\" before that decision.\n\n'''2013''': Thomas Kraemer, a retired professor at [[Oregon State University]], concludes that <span style=\"font-size: .93em; color:maroon; font-family: Silom;\">(U&nbsp;of&nbsp;M)</span>&nbsp;FREE hosted \"the first same-sex couple in history to be legally married\".<ref name=Kraemer>Thomas Kraemer [professor, Oregon State University], \"Gay marriage discussion in 1953 vs.&nbsp;1963 and today\", ''Tom's&nbsp;OSU'', posted 16&nbsp;December&nbsp;2013; [http://tomsosu.blogspot.com/2013/12/gay-marriage-discussion-in-1953-vs-1963.html available online]</ref> \n\n* Records at ''The National Archives''<ref name=Archives>Anon., \"Hidden Treasures from the Stacks: pushing for equality\", ''The&nbsp;National Archives at Kansas City'', September&nbsp;2013, 7; [https://www.archives.gov/kansas-city/press/newsletter/2013-september.pdf#page=7 available online]</ref> verify that \"McConnell and Baker's marriage license [from Blue&nbsp;Earth County, MN] was never revoked. They are still married and have been for the last forty two years.\"\n\n=== Federal courts respond ===\n'''1971''': Both state and federal courts rejected the marriage, others approved.<ref>\"What is believed to be the first same-sex marriage in the United States was performed in Minnesota.\"\n* Courtesy: Pat Kessler, \"A Rare Glimpse At Minn.'s 1st Gay Wedding In 1971\", ''WCCO'' [CBS, Minnesota], 31&nbsp;July&nbsp;2013; [http://minnesota.cbslocal.com/2013/07/29/a-rare-glimpse-at-minns-1st-gay-wedding-in-1971/ available online].\n* also, Naomi Pescovitz, \"Pastor Reflects Back on Minn. Gay Marriage\", ''KSTP-TV'' [Minneapolis,&nbsp;MN], 16&nbsp;May&nbsp;2013; {{YouTube|5MdGM9xBIMQ|available online}}.\n* and, Associated Press, \"They're Mr. and Mr.\", ''San Francisco Chronicle'', 8&nbsp;September&nbsp;1971,&nbsp;3</ref> \n\n* Validity of the marriage depended on how Minnesota's [[Baker_v._Nelson#Appeal_to_the_Minnesota_Supreme_Court|marriage law]] was interpreted.<ref name=\"Marriage law\" /> A direct appeal to the United States Supreme Court was [[Baker_v._Nelson#Appeal_to_the_U.S._Supreme_Court|dismissed]].<ref>409 U.S. 810, 93&nbsp;S.Ct.&nbsp;37, 34&nbsp;L.Ed.2d&nbsp;65&nbsp;(1972)</ref> \n\n* While an appeal to the Minnesota Supreme Court was pending, McConnell re-applied and obtained a [[Michael_McConnell_and_Jack_Baker#Adoption,_name_change,_marriage|marriage license]].<ref name=\"Free Press\" /> By Order of Assistant Chief Judge Gregory Anderson, \"The marriage is declared to be in all respects valid.\"<ref name=ruling />\n\n'''1973''': A joint tax return for 1973 was rejected by the Internal Revenue Service.<ref>Anon., \"Homosexual Couple Contest I.R.S. Ban On a Joint Return\", ''The&nbsp;New York Times'', 5&nbsp;Jan.&nbsp;1975,&nbsp;55</ref>\n\n'''1974''': McConnell listed Baker as an [[Michael_McConnell_and_Jack_Baker#Adoption,_name_change,_marriage|adopted \"child\"]] on his tax returns from 1974 through 2004 for which he claimed a deduction as [[head of household]]. That benefit ended when Congress limited the deduction for an adopted child under the age of 19.<ref>Anon., \"Form 1040 Instructions\", ''Internal Revenue Service'' (2005), 19; [https://www.irs.gov/pub/irs-prior/i1040gi--2005.pdf#page=19 available online]</ref>\n\n'''1976''': A claim filed with the Veterans Administration was rejected<ref>''McConnell v. Nooner'':\n* District Court: No.&nbsp;4-75-Civ.&nbsp;566 (D.&nbsp;Minn. 20&nbsp;April&nbsp;1976)\n* and, United States Court of Appeals, Eighth Circuit: 547&nbsp;F.2d&nbsp;54 (8th&nbsp;Cir.&nbsp;1976)</ref> because \"Minnesota law prohibits same sex marriages<ref>[[Baker_v._Nelson]], 291&nbsp;Minn.&nbsp;310, 191&nbsp;N.W.2d&nbsp;185&nbsp;(1971)</ref> .&nbsp;.&nbsp;.\"\n\n==Employment discrimination==\n'''1970''': The <span style=\"font-size: .93em; color:maroon; font-family: Silom;\">(U&nbsp;of&nbsp;M)</span> Librarian offers Michael McConnell the position of Head of the Cataloging Division at the library on the St.&nbsp;Paul campus.<ref name=\"job offer\"> '''1970''': Letter to Michael McConnell,\n* from Ralph&nbsp;H. Hopp, University Librarian, ''University of Minnesota'' [Minneapolis], 27&nbsp;April;\n* also, see Randy Tigue, \"Regent: FREE&nbsp;member case is a matter of public&nbsp;relations\", ''Minnesota Daily'', 16&nbsp;July,&nbsp;1;\n* and, letter from James&nbsp;F. Hogg, Secretary, Board of Regents, ''University of Minnesota'', 10&nbsp;July. \"... your conduct, as represented in the public and University news media, is not consistent with the best interest of the University.\" \n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;5a&nbsp;-&nbsp;e], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> After McConnell applies for a marriage license, regent&nbsp;Daniel Gainey insists that \"homosexuality is about the worst thing there is.\"<ref name=\"job offer\" /> \n\nThe Board of Regents rejects the offer.<ref name=\"job offer\" /> McConnell sues in federal [https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/district-courts/FSupp/316/809/1951718/ <span style=\"color:blue\">District Court</span>] and prevails.<ref>Bob Lundegaard, \"University Ordered to Hire Homosexual\", ''Minneapolis Tribune'', 10&nbsp;September&nbsp;1970,&nbsp;23</ref>\n\n'''1971''': The regents appeal to the [https://openjurist.org/451/f2d/193/mcconnell-v-anderson <span style=\"color:blue\">Eighth Circuit Court of Appeals</span>],<ref>Anon., \"Homosexual Wins a Suit over Hiring\", ''New York Times'', 20&nbsp;September&nbsp;1970; [https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1970/09/20/355908502.pdf available online], accessed February 7, 2012</ref> which concludes that the University did not restrict free speech. Instead, the court rules, it was McConnell who wants \"to pursue an activist role in implementing his controversial ideas concerning the social status to be accorded homosexuals and thereby to foist tacit approval of the socially repugnant concept upon his employer.\"<ref>Michelle Andrea Wolf and Alfred P. Kielwasser, eds., \"Gay People, Sex, and the Media\", ''Haworth Press'' (1991), 237; [https://books.google.com/books?id=Y_Hd0F2J7LEC&pg=PA237& available online], accessed February 7, 2012</ref>\n\n'''1972''': More than 80% of the student body voice disapproval of the regents' action.<ref>\"Do you think the University was justified in firing McConnell because of his open declaration of homosexuality?\"\n* yes&nbsp;=&nbsp;10%, no&nbsp;=&nbsp;81%, no opinion&nbsp;=&nbsp;8%, other&nbsp;=&nbsp;1%\n* See: Office of Student Affairs, \"Research Bulletin\", ''University of Minnesota'', Winter&nbsp;1972  \n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;5a&nbsp;-&nbsp;e], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref>\n\nMcConnell is hired by the [[Hennepin County Library]] <ref>1972: Then, a diverse and growing system of 26&nbsp;facilities; \n* he rises to the level of <span style=\"color:red\">Coordinating Librarian</span> before retiring.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes 6a-b], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> and retires 37&nbsp;years later. The Board of Commissioners commends him for his service.<ref>See: \"Item&nbsp;7A - Commendation of Michael McConnell\", ''Hennepin County Board of Commissioners'', 30&nbsp;November&nbsp;2010; [http://hennepinmn.granicus.com/MediaPlayer.php?view_id=10&amp;clip_id=1134 available online].</ref>\n\n'''2012''': University president [[Eric Kaler]] offers McConnell an apology for the \"<span style=\"color:red\">reprehensible</span>\" treatment he endured from the Board of Regents in 1970.<ref>2012: \"News\", ''University News Service'', 22&nbsp;June\n* 2018: President Kaler affirmed his 2012 News statements. Action taken by our Board in 1970, he said, \"is today worthy of deep criticism - of rebuke and censure.\" See: Email to Logan Chelmo, 27&nbsp;June&nbsp;2018; class of 2018, Shakopee High School, located in Shakopee, Minnesota\n* 2020: McConnell is enrolled as a member of the Heritage Society of the President's Club. See: Letter from xxx, 6&nbsp;June&nbsp;2020  \n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\" [Binder #7, MEMORANDUM for the record], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> He regrets that it occurred and assures that such practices would not be consistent with official actions at this time.\n\nMcConnell accepts the assurance.<ref>Statement from Michael McConnell, on his letterhead, 25&nbsp;July\n* See: Gift&nbsp;#1, accepted by Kristin Lockhart, Associate Vice President for Equity and Diversity.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\" [Binder&nbsp;#8], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> \"Thank you, President Kaler, for offering to remove the cloud that shamed the <span style=\"font-size: .93em; color:maroon; font-family: Silom;\">(U&nbsp;of&nbsp;M)</span>. Your offer is accepted.\"\n\n==Career in law and politics==\n'''June 1972''': Baker led the DFL Gay Rights Caucus<ref>'''For Release Any Time''', \"Gay Machine Startles DFL Regulars\", ''DFL Gay Rights Caucus'', 9&nbsp;June&nbsp;1972.</ref> at the State Convention of the [[Minnesota Democratic\u2013Farmer\u2013Labor Party]]. After the caucus proposed \"legislation defining marriage as a civil contract between any two adults\",<ref>Resolution&nbsp;71.d, \"The 1972 DFL Platform\", ''Minnesota Democratic-Farmer-Labor State Central Committee'', 9&nbsp;-&nbsp;11&nbsp;June&nbsp;1972 at Rochester, MN.</ref> the delegates approved that wording for inclusion in the party platform. This was the first time a major United States political party encouraged support for marriage equality.\n\n'''December''': Baker graduated from the [[University of Minnesota Law School]].<ref>Malcolm Moos, President, ''University of Minnesota'', 13&nbsp;December&nbsp;1972: \"The Degree Of Juris Doctor With All Its Privileges And Obligations\" is conferred</ref> His request to take the bar examination raised questions of fraud surrounding his [[Timeline_of_same-sex_marriage#1970s|1971 marriage license]]. At a hearing, Baker was defended by the Minnesota Civil Liberties Union.<ref>Anon., \"Marriage hurdle cleared, Baker to take bar exams\", ''Minneapolis Star'', 28&nbsp;December 1972,&nbsp;2</ref> The State Board of Law Examiners reviewed the facts and concluded that he was entitled to take the exam.<ref name=bar>{{cite news|title=Homosexual Wins Fights to Take Bar Examination in Minnesota|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1973/01/07/119453382.pdf |accessdate=March 20, 2013|newspaper=New York Times|date=January 7, 1973}}</ref> Later, he was admitted to the bar.<ref> October 2002: In a MEMO for the record, Baker explains why lobbying by the Chief Justice, Oscar Knutson, failed to deny him a license to practice law.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volume&nbsp;7a, section&nbsp;II], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref>\n\nBaker campaigned for Associate Justice of the Minnesota Supreme Court five times. He argued that each opponent violated the Code of Judicial Conduct<ref name=\"Results\">Jack Baker questioned why some judges were allowed to ignore the Code of Judicial Conduct.\n* 1970: Canon&nbsp;5E. '''Arbitration'''. \"A judge should not act as an arbitrator or mediator.\" \n* 1994: Canon&nbsp;4F. '''Service as Arbitrator or Mediator'''. \"A judge shall not act as an arbitrator or mediator or otherwise perform judicial functions in a private capacity unless expressly authorized by law.\"\n* 1978: [http://www.minnesotalegalhistoryproject.org/assets/Election%20Results%201857-2016.pdf#page=72 C. Donald Peterson]\n* 1980: [http://www.minnesotalegalhistoryproject.org/assets/Election%20Results%201857-2016.pdf#page=73 George M. Scott]\n* 1982: [http://www.minnesotalegalhistoryproject.org/assets/Election%20Results%201857-2016.pdf#page=74 John E. Simonett]\n* 1984: [http://www.minnesotalegalhistoryproject.org/assets/Election%20Results%201857-2016.pdf#page=74 Douglas K. Amdahl]\n* 2002: [http://www.minnesotalegalhistoryproject.org/assets/Election%20Results%201857-2016.pdf#page=84 Paul H. Anderson]\n* others\n* Courtesy: Douglas A. Hedrin, \"Results of Elections of Justices to the Minnesota Supreme Court 1857-2016\", ''Minnesota Legal History Project''\n* Details: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volume&nbsp;8c], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> by heading the [[C._Donald_Peterson#Minnesota News Council|Minnesota News Council]] (MNC).<ref name=\"rule_of_law\">Jack Baker, \"2002 Judicial '''Plebiscite'''\", ''Minnesota State Bar Association'', September&nbsp;2002\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volume&nbsp;8c], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> \n\nEthics of C. Donald Peterson<ref name=Results /> were questioned in 1978, George Scott<ref name=Results /> in 1980, John Simonett<ref name=Results /><ref>See: Initial Annual Registration for a Minnesota Non-Profit Corporation, ''Office of the Secretary of State''. \n* \"Effective August 1, 1989, all non-profit corporations are now required to file an annual registration once every calendar year. Please review the information on the label and read all directions before completing this form.\"\n* Corporate Charter Number: L-559 \n* Corporate Name: Minnesota News Council \n* [[Registered Office]] Address: '''230&nbsp;State&nbsp;Capital''', St.&nbsp;Paul, MN [chambers of the Minnesota Supreme Court before moving to a new location] \n* Signature: [Associate Justice] '''John&nbsp;E. Simonett''' \n* Title of Office: Chair \n* Date: 1/22/90\n* Courtesy: ''Minnesota Historical Society''</ref> in 1982, Douglas Amdahl<ref name=Results /> in 1984 and [[Paul H. Anderson]]<ref name=Results /> in 2002. In the ''Plebiscite'' mailed to more than 14,900 attorneys in Minnesota, Baker challenged the bar to end special relationships between Justices of Minnesota's Supreme Court and MNC.<ref name=rule_of_law /> Nevertheless, collusion continued.<ref>The list of \"Supreme Court Justices who chaired the News Council\"\n* 1971-80: C. Donald Peterson\n* [also: George M. Scott]\n* 1980-82: Douglas K. Amdahl\n* 1982-94: John E. Simonett\n* 1995-97: Paul H. Anderson\n* 1998-2006: Edward Stringer\n* See: email from Susan Hansen, <newscncl@mtn.org>, 14 June 2000.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volume 7a], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, University of Minnesota Libraries</ref> \n\nBenefits bestowed on a judge who ignored the Code of Judicial Conduct<ref name=Results /> and who [[C._Donald_Peterson#Minnesota News Council|helped to mediate]] private disputes continued even after the MNC was ejected from court chambers in 1994.<ref>Remaining offices for the Minnesota Supreme Court moved from 230&nbsp;State&nbsp;Capitol in January\n* \u201cEmployees coped. They moved into the newly remodeled space floor-by-floor and coexisted with construction over a period of time from September through '''December''' [1994].\u201d\n* See: Roland C. Amundson, \u201cA Search for Place: The History of the Minnesota Judicial Center\u201d, ''Minnesota Court of Appeals'', 1995,&nbsp;67.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volume&nbsp;8c], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref><ref>Not until James H. Gilbert resigned as Associate Justice and was hired by MNC in 2007 as its \"Hearing Chair\" did MNC stop recruiting judges to mediate its disputes.\n* See: email from Sarah E. Bauer, Interim Director, Minnesota News Council, 11&nbsp;May&nbsp;2007;\n* new address: '''12&nbsp;South Sixth&nbsp;Street''', Suite&nbsp;927, Minneapolis, MN&nbsp;55402.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volume&nbsp;8c], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> MNC ceased to exist in 2011.<ref>Gail Rosenblum, \"News council's demise is bad news for all who value the truth\", ''Star&nbsp;Tribune'', 23&nbsp;February 2011, B1</ref>\n\n==Later years==\n[[File:BakerMcConnell.jpg|thumb|Baker and McConnell in 2016]]\nIn 2003, Baker and McConnell amended their individual tax returns for the year 2000, filing jointly as a couple. They offered proof of a valid marriage license issued in Blue Earth County. The IRS challenged the validity of the marriage license and argued that, even if the license were valid, the [[Defense of Marriage Act]] prohibited the IRS from recognizing it. McConnell brought suit and the [[United States District Court for the District of Minnesota|U.S. District Court for Minnesota]] upheld the IRS ruling in ''McConnell v. United States'' on January 3, 2005,<ref>{{cite web|title=McConnell v. United States, January 3, 2005|url=http://www.lawprofessorblogs.com/taxprof/linkdocs/2005-1056-1.pdf|publisher=US District Court for Minnesota|accessdate=21 March 2013}}</ref> and the Eighth Circuit Court of Appeals affirmed the District Court's ruling on July 17, 2006, saying that McConnell could not relitigate the question decided in ''Baker v. Nelson''.<ref>{{cite web|title=McConnell v. United States|url=http://docs.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/ca8/05-1781/051781u-2011-02-25.pdf?1301253248|publisher=8th Circuit Court of Appeals|accessdate=21 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nBaker and McConnell were still living as a married couple as late as May 2015.<ref name=NYT051715>{{cite news |last=Eckholm |first=Eric|title=The Same-Sex Couple Who Got a Marriage License in 1971|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/17/us/the-same-sex-couple-who-got-a-marriage-license-in-1971.html|accessdate=May 17, 2015|newspaper=The New York Times|date=May 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe U.S. Supreme Court agreed in 2015, \"to decide the issue Jack Baker and Mike McConnell tried to bring before it in 1972: Do same-sex couples have a constitutional right to get married?\"<ref>Roger Parloff, \"12 key moments that led to the Supreme Court's same-sex marriage case\", ''fortune.com'' (posted 16&nbsp;January&nbsp;2015); [http://fortune.com/2015/01/18/same-sex-marriage-supreme-court/ available online]</ref> That case was dismissed \"for want of a substantial federal question.\"<ref name=greenhouse>{{cite news |last=Greenhouse |first=Linda |title=Wedding Bells|url=http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/03/20/wedding-bells/|accessdate=March 21, 2013|newspaper=New York Times|date=March 20, 2013}}</ref> Minnesota's Attorney General argued, in March 2015, as a friend of the court: \"The procreation rationale [used by the Minnesota Supreme Court] does not support the prohibition of same-sex marriage\".<ref name=swanson>Lori Swanson, Attorney General, State of Minnesota; \"Brief of the State of Minnesota as AMICUS CURIAE in support of petitioners\", Obergefell v. Hodges; ''In The Supreme Court of the United States'', March&nbsp;2015, 18; [http://thecolu.mn/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/MNSCOTUSbrief.pdf#page=30 available online]</ref>\n[[File:MikeMcConnell.jpg|thumb|right|upright|McConnell in 2016]]\n\n==Interview==\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.mprnews.org/story/2015/07/16/baker-mcconnell|title=For Mpls. couple, gay marriage ruling is a victory 43 years in the making|author=Tom Crann|date=16 July 2015|publisher=Minnesota Public Radio News}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.pri.org/stories/2015-06-25/meet-two-men-who-managed-get-first-known-same-sex-marriage-license-back-1970|title=Meet the two men who managed to get the first known same-sex marriage license - back in 1970|author=T.J. Raphael|date=25 June 2015|publisher=The Takeaway, Public Radio International}}\n\n==Short documentary==\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cse4s3gmbPE|title=Baker v. Nelson: The Original Case for Gay Marriage|author=Joseph Kase and Jeremiah Smith|date=Feb 2014|publisher=YouTube}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://minnesota.cbslocal.com/2013/07/29/a-rare-glimpse-at-minns-1st-gay-wedding-in-1971/|title=A Rare Glimpse At Minn.'s 1st Gay Wedding In 1971|author=Pat Kessler|date=29 July 2013|publisher=WCCO-TV, Minneapolis}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/17/us/the-same-sex-couple-who-got-a-marriage-license-in-1971.html|title=The Same-Sex Couple Who Got a Marriage License in 1971|author= Erik Eckholm|date=16 May 2015|publisher=www.nytimes.com|newspaper=The New York Times}}\n* {{cite magazine|url=http://time.com/3843579/influential-marriages/|title=The 25 Most Influential Marriages of All Time|author=Lisa Grunwald|date=12 May 2015|magazine=TIME}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.qlibrary.org/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Seeds_for_Gay_Marriage_Equality.pdf#page=2|title=Who defined the gay agenda?|author=Pat Lyn McConnell|date=Jan 2014|publisher=[[Quatrefoil Library]]}}\n* {{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-23159390|title=Jack Baker and Michael McConnell: Gay Americans who married in 1971|author=Claire Bowes|date=4 July 2013|accessdate=4 July 2013|work=BBC News}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.qlibrary.org/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Quatrefolio-2012-Pride.pdf#page=5|title=Minnesota Led the Two Coasts on Marriage Rights, and Should Do So Again: Jack Baker and Michael McConnell|author=Robert Frame|year=2012|publisher=Quatrefoil Library}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.lib.umn.edu/sites/default/files/media/Quest%20copy.pdf|title=A Quest for Full Equality|author=Ken Bronson|year=2004|publisher=University of Minnesota Libraries}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.brumm.com/schools/gaylib/earlybrumm.html#baker|title=My Own Early Gay History|author=Dennis Brumm|year=1971|publisher=www.brumm.com}}\n* Memoir of Michael McConnell (2016) as told to Gail Langer Karwoski, [http://www.worldcat.org/title/wedding-heard-round-the-world-americas-first-gay-marriage/oclc/926312828&referer=brief_results \"The Wedding Heard Heard 'Round the World: America's First Gay Marriage.\"], Minneapolis, MN: ''University of Minnesota Press''.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|25em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baker, Jack}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:LGBT in Minnesota]]\n[[Category:University of Minnesota Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Minnesota]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights activists from the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people||Jack Baker (disambiguation)}}\n{{Cleanup|reason=odd colors and fonts need to be removed, citations need to be standardized, spurious bold removed, citations checked (too many are primay), general layout and organization: article is laid out as a timeline--of what? the lead doesn't even clarify what the subject is, and the first sentence doesn't comply with MOS|date=March 2020}}\n[[File:MikeMcConnellJackBaker.jpg|thumb|Husbands Mike McConnell (left) and Jack Baker in 2016]]\n'''Michael McConnell''', [[Timeline_of_same-sex_marriage#1970s | librarian]], and '''Jack Baker''', [[Timeline_of_same-sex_marriage#1970s | law student]], were married<ref name=\"Marriage law\"> 1970: \"Minnesota Statutes Annotated\", ''West Publishing&nbsp;Co.''\n* Chapter&nbsp;517.01: '''Marriage a civil contract'''. \"Marriage, so far as its validity in law is concerned, is a civil contract, to which the consent of the parties, capable in law of contracting, is essential.\" \n* Chapter&nbsp;517.03: '''Marriages prohibited'''. [The list does not include parties of the same gender.]</ref> in the U.S. state of [[Minnesota]] on 3&nbsp;September&nbsp;1971.\n\nBoth were activists in Minnesota from 1969 to 1980. They were invited often to appear publicly in the US and Canada at college events, schools, businesses, churches, etc.<ref>See: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;2c and 2d], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> \n\nHistorians insisted that they became the \"first same-sex couple in history to be legally married\".<ref name=Kraemer /> Specifically, the decision of [[Baker_v._Nelson#Facts_and_trial | Minnesota's Supreme Court]] in 1971 [[Baker_v._Nelson | did \"not reach back]] to Baker and McConnell\" since the two obtained their license and were married \"a full six weeks\"<ref name=FLR /> previously. The National Archives came to the same conclusion.<ref name=Archives>Anon., \"Hidden Treasures from the Stacks: pushing for equality\", ''The&nbsp;National Archives at Kansas City'', September&nbsp;2013, 7; [https://www.archives.gov/kansas-city/press/newsletter/2013-september.pdf#page=7 available online]</ref>\n\n==Student activism==\n\nWeeks before the 1969 [[Stonewall riots]], two activists and local friends organize a team called \"Fight Repression of Erotic Expression\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://collections.mnhs.org/cms/display?irn=10262356|title=Twin Cities Gay and Lesbian Community Oral History Project: Interview with Koreen Phelps : Collections Online : mnhs.org|website=collections.mnhs.org|access-date=2019-06-05}}</ref> as part of an outreach program sponsored by MINNESOTA FREE UNIVERSITY.<ref>Program offices were located in the Cedar Riverside Neighborhood of '''Minneapolis''', at 529&nbsp;Cedar&nbsp;Avenue, near the U of Minnesota's expanding campus on the West&nbsp;Bank of the Mississippi.\n* See: K.A.&nbsp;Phelps, \"The Homosexual Revolution\", ''MINNESOTA FREE UNIVERSITY'', 18&nbsp;'''May'''&nbsp;1969; Bulletin&nbsp;No.&nbsp;5, New Courses [final entry].\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;1a&nbsp;-&nbsp;d], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> \n\n* '''May''': Robert Halfhill, a graduate student with interest in their proposal, leaves the neighborhood lectures to form an independent group called \"FREE\" on the [[University of Minnesota|Minneapolis campus]] of the University of Minnesota.<ref name=Halfhill>Bruce Johasen, \"Out of Silence\", Minnesota History, Spring&nbsp;2019:\n* \"Halfhill steered the group through the administrative channels needed to establish FREE as a student group, 189. Lack of interest by women \"was always a bitter disappointment\" for Phelps, 188, who was \"really angry\" with demands for \"the right to get married\", 194;\n* Also: McConnell Files, \"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\" [Binder #7, MEMORANDUM for the record], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''. On page 1:\n* \"Timidity and confusion\" tired Halfhill. \"He left to organize an independent coalition of activists on the East Bank campus.\"</ref> Those attending his meetings elect [[Timeline_of_same-sex_marriage#1970s|Jack Baker, a law student]],<ref>Jack Baker, while a law student, was \n* president of FREE (1969), and\n* later, a student body president on \n* the Minneapolis campuses of \n* the University of Minnesota, \n* [elected 1971, re-elected 1972]</ref> to serve as president.<ref>Neal R. Peirce, \"The Great Plains States of America: People, Politics, and Power in the Nine Great Plains States\", ''George&nbsp;J. McLeod'' (1973), 145; [https://books.google.com/books?id=JyqbTl9fsc4C&pg=PA145& available online], accessed February 7, 2014</ref> \n\n* '''November''': A faculty committee qualifies FREE for all privileges enjoyed by student organizations.<ref name=dynes>Wayne R. Dynes, \"Homosexuality and Government, Politics and Prisons\" (1992), 248; [https://books.google.com/books?id=wegoALly5DEC&pg=PA244& available online], accessed February 7, 2012</ref> As the \"the first student gay organization to gain recognition in the upper mid-west,\"<ref name= FREE>\"Minnesota Hosts First Legally Sanctioned Same-Sex Marriage\"\n* '''For Release''', ''Minnesota Student Association'', 7&nbsp;September&nbsp;1971.\n* also, '''for immediate release''', ''FREE'', 17&nbsp;May&nbsp;1970.\n* and, '''News from''', ''Fight Repression of Erotic Expression'', 1&nbsp;November&nbsp;1969\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;1a&nbsp;-&nbsp;d], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> interest in FREE expands quickly. Its \"leaders believe it to be the first such organization on a Big Ten campus\", the second such organization in the United States, following the [[Student Homophile League]]<ref>Merged later with the [[Columbia Queer Alliance]].</ref> recognized by [[Columbia University]] in 1967.<ref>{{cite news|last=Schumach|first=Murray|title=Columbia Charters Homosexual Group|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1967/05/03/107188654.pdf|accessdate=July 23, 2013|newspaper=New York Times|date=May 3, 1967}}</ref>\n\n'''1970''': Moving openly and aggressively, FREE slowly transforms [[Minneapolis]].<ref name=Coverage>On page&nbsp;13: \"A mecca for gays\", in a story by\n* Lily Hansen, ''GAY'', \"F.R.E.E. At Last\", 11&nbsp;May&nbsp;1970.  \n* also, \"Three big companies say they hire Gays\", ''The&nbsp;Advocate'', 30&nbsp;September&nbsp;1970.\n* and, Ken Bronson, \"A Quest for Full Equality\", 2004; [https://www.lib.umn.edu/sites/default/files/media/Quest%20copy.pdf#page=9 available online] from ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;1a&nbsp;-&nbsp;d], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> \n\n* One member asks five major companies to explain their attitudes toward gay men and women.<ref name=Coverage /> Three large companies respond quickly, insisting that they did not discriminate against homosexuals in their hiring policies.<ref name=Coverage /> [[Honeywell]] objects:<ref name=Honeywell>An inquiry about employment of homosexuals generates a response from Gerry&nbsp;E. Morse, Vice President, ''Honeywell&nbsp;Inc.''. \n* See: letter to '''FREE''', addressed to James&nbsp;W. Chesebro, 29&nbsp;June&nbsp;1970.\n* and: Lars Bjornson, \"A quiet win: Honeywell yields\", ''The Advocate'', 10&nbsp;April&nbsp;1974, 13.\n* Courtesy: Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;1a&nbsp;-&nbsp;d], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> \"We would not employ a known homosexual.\" That member expands his surveys as complaints surface.\n\n* Another member is eager to educate his parents. For credit, he selects a program requested by Dave Moore, then a popular announcer on WCCO-TV. The student is proud of what ultimately airs on Sunday, 30&nbsp;September 1973.<ref>Review the FREE member's course work, including words to his parents.\n* Courtesy: \"Human Relations\", ''University Media Resources''\n* {{YouTube|id=mOwGW-Jie7E&feature=c4-overview&list=UU0ClfyXL_loos5QtXwPhMhQ|title=available online}}\n* Posted by Brandon Wolf </ref> \n\n* Members vote to endorse<ref name=FREE /> [[Timeline_of_same-sex_marriage#1970s|\"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\"]].<ref name=memoir>Memoir of Michael McConnell, as told to Gail Langer Karwoski, \"The Wedding Heard 'Round the World: America's First Gay Marriage,\" ''University of Minnesota Press'', 2016</ref><ref name=Halfhill />\n\n'''1972''': FREE continues working with a faculty committee to craft a new policy that would protect gay students from discrimination.<ref name=policy>See: letter to Jack Baker et al., from\n* Malcolm Moos, President, ''University of Minnesota'', 11&nbsp;February&nbsp;1971.  \"I appreciate your willingness to serve on the Campus Committee on Placement Services\";\n* also: Gary Urban, \"Complaint charges Honeywell discrimination\", ''Minnesota Daily'', 12&nbsp;March&nbsp;1973, 8; \n* Courtesy: Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;1a&nbsp;-&nbsp;d], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> \n\n* '''May''': Central Administration approves a final draft.<ref name=policy /> \n\n* Campus Committee on Placement Services accepts complaints of unequal treatment by employers recruiting on campus. \n\n'''1974''': When faced with a denial of access to students, Honeywell \"quietly reverses its hiring policy\".<ref name=Honeywell /> No longer would it refuse to employ students who were openly gay.\n\n===Gay Pride===\n'''1971''': After the Stonewall Rebellion \u2013 New York City, 1969<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/04/us/stonewall-riots-gay-pride.html|title=50 Years Later, What We Forgot About Stonewall|last=Salam|first=Maya|date=2019-06-04|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-06-05|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/ston/index.htm|title=Stonewall National Monument (U.S. National Park Service)|last=York|first=Mailing Address: 26 Wall Street Federal Hall National Monument c/o Stonewall National Monument New|last2=Us|first2=NY 10005 Phone: 212-668-2577 Contact|website=www.nps.gov|language=en|access-date=2019-06-05}}</ref> \u2013 members of FREE from ''Gay&nbsp;House'' promote self-pride with picnics in Loring Park, near Downtown Minneapolis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://collections.mnhs.org/cms/display?irn=10262356|title=Twin Cities Gay and Lesbian Community Oral History Project: Interview with Koreen Phelps : Collections Online : mnhs.org|website=collections.mnhs.org|access-date=2019-06-05}}</ref> Thom Higgins<ref name=Pride>A monk turned gay activist.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\" [Binder #7, MEMORANDUM for the record], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> crafts \"Gay Pride\" as a chant to discredit the two terms often condemned as \"sins\" by the Catholic archbishop for Minneapolis and Saint Paul. \n\n'''2018''': \"The wrenching bankruptcy that forced a reckoning on the Archdiocese of St. Paul and Minneapolis for decades of clergy sexual abuse has culminated in a $230 million settlement for roughly 450 victims, the largest of its kind nationwide.\"<ref>Victims' attorney Jeff Anderson is overcome with emotion.\n* Staff writers, \"$210 in Atonement\", ''Star&nbsp;Tribune'', 1&nbsp;June&nbsp;2018,&nbsp;A1\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volume&nbsp;8b], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref>\n\n===Student Body President===\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Shoes poster 1971.tif|thumb|right|1971 election poster]]  -->\n'''1971''': Baker campaigned to become president of the Minnesota Student Association<ref name=\"Student Body President\">A student body president known by different names; elected 1971, re-elected 1972. \n* March&nbsp;1942: Richard John Baker, Certificate of Birth \n* September&nbsp;1969: Jack Baker, name adopted to lead activists demanding gay equality \n* August&nbsp;1971: Pat&nbsp;Lyn McConnell, married name; by Decree of Adoption \n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;6a&nbsp;-&nbsp;b], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''\n* also, Kay Tobin and Randy Wicker, \"The&nbsp;Gay Crusaders\", ''Paperback Library'', New&nbsp;York:&nbsp;1972, 136</ref> on the U_of_M's Minneapolis campus. \"''Student Control over Student Concerns''\",<ref name=Platform>Platform for student body president \n* Jack Baker, \"Policy Statement\", March&nbsp;1971\n* Endorsed by ''Minnesota Daily'', \"Baker for MSA president\", 5&nbsp;April&nbsp;1971,&nbsp;page&nbsp;4. \"He has spoken truth to power because he knows the power of truth.\"\n* After graduation, the Governor signed into law a bill reserving one seat on the Board of Regents for an enrolled student.</ref> urged students \"to search out a new self-respect.\"<ref name=\"Student Body President\" /> Thoughtful posters with a focus on [https://box8661.blogspot.com/2013/06/marriage-equality-was-inevitable.htm self-pride]<ref name=Pride /> helped his election,<ref name=election>A total of 6,024 ballots cast topped the previous record of 5,049 in the 1958 election.\n* See: Steve Brandt, \"Baker wins in record vote,\" ''Minnesota Daily'', 8&nbsp;April&nbsp;1971,&nbsp;1\n* and, Gary Dawson, \"Homosexual Credits U Election Victory to a New Sophistication\", ''St.&nbsp;Paul Dispatch'', 8&nbsp;April&nbsp;1971,&nbsp;35\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;6a&nbsp;-&nbsp;b], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> and re-election. <ref name=re-election>It was \"the first time in the 121-year history of the U_of_M that a student body president has been re-elected.\"\n* See: Vic Stoner, \"Baker, Schwartz win MSA election\", ''Minnesota Daily'', 7&nbsp;April&nbsp;1972,&nbsp;1\n* and, Associated Press, \"Law senior elected U. student president\", ''Austin Daily Herald'', 7&nbsp;April&nbsp;1972,&nbsp;p.&nbsp;?\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;6a&nbsp;-&nbsp;b], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref>\n\n* \"We need a student on the Board of Regents,\" he insisted. No need to wait for a new law.<ref name=Platform /> \"The Regents already have the power to appoint students to all committees of the Board or Regents.\" \n\n* Baker captured 2,766&nbsp;votes;<ref name=election /> two competitors and write-in candidates split the remainder. \n\n* As student body president, Baker continued to question why the Board of Regents ignored students when making its decisions. Soon, one non-voting student was invited to sit with the regents at each committee meeting.<ref name=Platform /> \n\n'''1972''': Re-elected with \"3,035 votes out of a record turnout of 7,441\"<ref name=re-election /> \u2013 41% in a 3-way race.\n\n== Same-sex marriage activism ==\n\n===Lawsuit to obtain a licence===\n{{Main|Baker v. Nelson}}\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:McConnell (l) and Baker (r) apply for marriage license 19700518.png|thumb|right|Michael McConnell (l) and Jack Baker (18&nbsp;May&nbsp;1970) - by R. Bertrand Heine, Minnesota&nbsp;Historical&nbsp;Society]]  -->\n\n'''1970''': Minnesota's statutes do not explicitly forbid marriage between two adult men.<ref name=\"Marriage law\" /> Baker, a law student, argues that \"[[Everything which is not forbidden is allowed|what is not forbidden is permitted]]\"<ref>Jack Baker, as told to Helen Barrett, \"We had America's first gay marriage - in 1971\", ''Financial Times Magazine'', 7&nbsp;August&nbsp;2015; [https://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/9d35d5d8-3ae4-11e5-bbd1-b37bc06f590c.html available online]</ref> when the couple applies for a marriage license in Minneapolis.<ref name=\"Marriage law\" /> The Clerk of District Court<ref>18 May: Fourth Judicial District, in Minneapolis; [[Hennepin County Government Center|Hennepin County]], Minnesota</ref>, Gerald Nelson, denies their request. Refusal by the [[Baker_v._Nelson#Facts_and_trial|lower courts]] to order Nelson to issue a license<ref>All claims were dismissed.\n* See: Associated Press, \"Marriage Is Out\", ''Kansas&nbsp;City Star'', 24&nbsp;May&nbsp;1970,&nbsp;30A\n* and, \"Gay Marriage Plea Is Denied\", ''St.&nbsp;Paul Pioneer Press'', 19&nbsp;November&nbsp;1970,&nbsp;27\n* and, \"Court Won't Let Men Wed\", ''N.Y.&nbsp;Times'', 10&nbsp;Jan.&nbsp;1971, 65\n* also, Appellant's Jurisdictional Statement, ''[[Baker_v._Nelson]]'', Minnesota Supreme Court docket no.&nbsp;71-1027, at 3&nbsp;-&nbsp;4 (statement of the case)</ref> is affirmed by the [[Baker_v._Nelson#Appeal_to_the_Minnesota_Supreme_Court|Minnesota Supreme Court]].<ref>\"The institution of marriage as a union of man and woman, uniquely involving the procreation or rearing of children within a family, is as old as the book of Genesis\".\n* \"Opinion\", by Justice C.&nbsp;Donald Peterson, ''[[Baker v. Nelson]]'', 15&nbsp;Oct&nbsp;1971, 191&nbsp;N.W.2d&nbsp;185 at&nbsp;186.</ref>\n\n* Leadership inside the [[American Civil Liberties Union]] shows \"little or no enthusiasm\" for support.<ref>Letter from Norman Dorsen (General Counsel for ''ACLU'' in 1970),\n* published by Jason Smith, \"Gay Pride Block Party Case\", ''Friends of the Bill of Rights Foundation'', January&nbsp;2012,&nbsp;52 \n* [https://www.lib.umn.edu/pdf/rare/gayprideblockparty.pdf#page=54 available online]\n* Courtesy: ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> Court rules in effect allows the '''''Minnesota Civil Liberties Union''''' to appeal Minnesota's \"opinion\" directly to the [[Baker_v._Nelson#Appeal_to_the_U.S._Supreme_Court|U.S. Supreme Court]].<ref name=NYT051715>{{cite news |last=Eckholm |first=Eric|title=The Same-Sex Couple Who Got a Marriage License in 1971|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/17/us/the-same-sex-couple-who-got-a-marriage-license-in-1971.html|accessdate=May 17, 2015|newspaper=The New York Times|date=May 16, 2015}}</ref>  \n\n* Allan Spear, a U_of_M professor of history, describes them as the \"lunatic fringe\".<ref>David von Drehle, \"Gay Marriage Already Won\", ''TIME'', 8&nbsp;April&nbsp;2013,&nbsp;22</ref>  \n\n* The case receives extensive media attention,<ref name=letters+>See, a matrix of items (late 1960s, 1970s, early 1980),\n* especially, Jack Star, \"The Homosexual Couple,\" ''LOOK'', 26&nbsp;January&nbsp;1971,&nbsp;69&nbsp;-&nbsp;71\n* and, Michael Durham, \"Homosexuals in revolt\", ''LIFE'', 31&nbsp;December&nbsp;1971,&nbsp;68\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Gift&nbsp;#6, the marriage that made history\", Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> including appearances on the ''[[Phil Donahue Show]]'',<ref name=comdon>{{cite news |last=Condon |first=Patrick|title=Minn. gay couple in '71 marriage case still joined|url=http://minnesota.publicradio.org/display/web/2012/12/10/news/jack-baker-michael-mcconnell-same-sex-marriage|accessdate=March 20, 2013|newspaper=Minnesota Public Radio|date=December 10, 2012}}</ref> and Kennedy&nbsp;&amp;&nbsp;Co. (WLS-TV, Chicago&nbsp;IL). On the ''[[David Susskind Show]]''<ref>[http://minnesota.publicradio.org/display/web/2013/05/15/old-video Available online] from Sasha Aslanian, \"Gay rights pioneers Jack Baker and Michael McConnell predicted marriage victory in '70s\", ''Minnesota Public Radio'' (16&nbsp;May&nbsp;2013)</ref> (New&nbsp;York,&nbsp;NY), Baker is blunt.<ref name=Bowes /> \"We're gonna win eventually, not this time but maybe the next time around.\" \n\n'''1972''': The clerk for Justice Harry Blackmun crafts a one-sentence rejection because \"I just [didn't] think the court was ready at the time to take on the issue.\"<ref>Jess Bravin, \"Supreme Court Clerk Remembers First Same-Sex Marriage Case\", ''The Wall Street Journal'', 1&nbsp;May&nbsp;2015; [https://www.wsj.com/articles/supreme-court-clerk-remembers-first-same-sex-marriage-case-1430494015 available online]</ref><ref name=greenhouse /> A quick dismissal of ''[[Baker v. Nelson]]'' is approved unanimously. \n\n'''2015''': The high court allows lower courts to supervise a national debate before deciding that its decision to dismiss demands for marriage equality must be overruled.<ref>\"The Court now holds that same-sex couples may exercise the fundamental right to marry.\"\n* ''Obergefell&nbsp;v. Hodges,'' 26&nbsp;June&nbsp;2015, at&nbsp;22-23 \n* [https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/14pdf/14-556_3204.pdf#page=28 available online]</ref>\n\n* Gay Marriage is \"rejected by early gay activists [in New&nbsp;York City] who were mostly interested in sexual freedom and gay liberation.\"<ref>Thomas Kraemer, \"Jack Baker deserves mainstream press coverage after gay marriage ruling\", ''Tom's&nbsp;OSU'', 7&nbsp;July&nbsp;2012; [http://tomsosu.blogspot.com/2012/07/jack-baker-deserves-mainstream-press.html available online]</ref>\n\n* Gay \"historians\" ignore Minnesota because they \"personally had political objections to gay marriage activism.\"<ref>Minnesotans document gay history:\n* See: Thomas Kraemer [Professor], \"Gay marriage pioneer Jack Baker starts blog\", ''Tom's&nbsp;OSU'', 4&nbsp;April&nbsp;2012; [https://tomsosu.blogspot.com/2012/04/gay-marriage-pioneer-jack-baker-starts.html available online]\n* also, Jack Baker [Attorney], \"A court corrupted\"; [https://box8661.blogspot.com/2015/03/a-court-corrupted.html available online]</ref>\n\n===A civil right===\n'''1970''': [[Timeline_of_same-sex_marriage#1970s|McConnell and Baker]] apply for a license to marry.<ref>18 May: Fourth Judicial District, in Minneapolis; Hennepin County, Minnesota</ref> The Clerk of District Court rejects their request.<ref name=\"517.03\">1970: Minnesota's marriage statute \u2013 Minn.St. c. 517.03 \u2013 did not include parties of the same gender in its list of \"Marriages prohibited\"</ref> \n\n'''1971''': McConnell re-applies in a different county and receives a marriage license.<ref>16 August: Clerk of District Court, Fifth Judicial District, in Mankato \n* 3 September: At a ceremony in Minneapolis, Hennepin County, a United Methodist minister certifies the marriage contract.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\" [binder #7], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> Their wedding is proclaimed to be [[Timeline_of_same-sex_marriage#1970s|\"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\"]].<ref name=memoir /> Skeptics are silenced in '''2018''' when Assistant Chief Judge Gregory Anderson rules that \"The marriage is declared to be in all respects valid.\"<ref name=ruling>McConnells against Blue Earth County, \u201cCONCLUSIONS OF LAW\u201d, Fifth Judicial District, File&nbsp;#07-CV-16-4559, 18&nbsp;September&nbsp;2018. \n* \"The September&nbsp;3,&nbsp;1971 marriage of James&nbsp;Michael McConnell and Pat&nbsp;Lyn McConnell, a/k/a Richard&nbsp;John Baker, has never been dissolved or annulled by judicial decree and no grounds currently exist on which to invalidate the marriage.\" \n* [https://www.lib.umn.edu/sites/default/files/media/McConnellvBlueEarthCounty-17-Sept-2018-ConclusionsofLaw_ORDER.pdf#page=4 Available online] from U of Minnesota Libraries.\n* Courtesy: McConnell&nbsp;Files, \"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\" [binder&nbsp;#4], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref>\n\nBaker is invited to address members of the Ramsey County Bar Association. Same-sex unions are \"not only authorized by the U.S. Constitution\"<ref>Bob Protzman, \"Gay Marriage OK Predicted\", ''St.&nbsp;Paul Pioneer&nbsp;Press'', 22&nbsp;October&nbsp;1971, p&nbsp;?</ref> but are mandatory. \"I&nbsp;am convinced\", he explains, \"that same-sex marriages will be legalized in the United States.\"\n\n'''1972''': Baker speaks to a forum of more than 2,000 at the [[University of Winnipeg]]. \"We maintain,\" he explained, \"that it's a matter of equity and fair play that if a state is going to give childless heterosexual couples rights and benefits under the law, they can't complain when childless same-sex couples ask for the same rights.\"<ref name=\"Canada\">Persistence spread first to Canada, than worldwide.\n* See: Jack Baker, \"The right to be human and gay\", ''Manitoban'', 13&nbsp;March&nbsp;1972,\n* as reprinted by Ken Bronson in \"A Quest for Full Equality\", 2004, 69,  \n* [https://www.lib.umn.edu/sites/default/files/media/Quest%20copy.pdf#page=73 available online] from ''University  of Minnesota Libraries'';\n* also, Mia Rabson, \"Couple helped make history\", ''Winnipeg Free&nbsp;Press'', 17&nbsp;September&nbsp;2004, A4 and \n* letter from Rich North to Jack [Baker] & Mike [McConnell], 20&nbsp;September&nbsp;2004); [http://box8661.blogspot.com/2012/04/letter-from-canada-2.html available online].\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;6a&nbsp;-&nbsp;b], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> The lecture persuades Richard North to begin a \"fight to be married\" to Chris Vogel.<ref name=Canada /> His persistence leads to marriage equality in [[Canada]] during '''2004'''.<ref name= Canada />\n\n'''2012''': Demands for same-sex marriage continue to grow worldwide, becoming \"the civil rights issue of our times\".<ref name=\"never in doubt\">Lecture by NAACP President Benjamin Todd Jealous, during a news conference at the organization's national headquarters.\n* Michael&nbsp;K. Lavers, \"NAACP president: Marriage is '''civil rights issue of our times'''\" ''Washington Blade'', 21&nbsp;May&nbsp;2012; [http://www.washingtonblade.com/2012/05/21/naacp-president-marriage-is-civil-rights-issue-of-our-times/ available online]\n* also, Patrick Condon, \"Gay couple in 1971 marriage ruling reflect on new court challenges\", ''Associated Press,'' as reprinted in the ''St.&nbsp;Paul Pioneer&nbsp;Press'', 11&nbsp;December&nbsp;2012, 3A+.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;7a&nbsp;-&nbsp;e], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> Speaking to the ''Associated Press'', Baker explained that the \"outcome was never in doubt because the conclusion was intuitively obvious to a first-year law student.\"<ref name=\"never in doubt\" />\n\n'''2015''': As Baker predicted, same-sex marriage is [[Baker_v._Nelson|legalized nationwide]].\n\n=== Adoption, name change, marriage ===\n'''1971''': McConnell legally adopts<ref>FINDINGS AND DECREE [File No.&nbsp;AD-19962], 3&nbsp;August&nbsp;1971\n* Order signed by Judge Lindsay&nbsp;G. Arthur, Juvenile Division\n* Fourth Judicial District, in Minneapolis; Hennepin County, Minnesota\n* See: Anon., \"U student head adopted by homosexual friend\", ''Minneapolis Tribune'', 25&nbsp;August&nbsp;1971,&nbsp;1A\n* also, Associated Press, \"Male's adoption by roommate OKd\", ''Rocky Mountain News'', Denver, 26&nbsp;August&nbsp;1971,&nbsp;85\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\" [Binder&nbsp;#3, file&nbsp;#2], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> Baker because \"regardless of popular conception, adoption is not limited to children\". Baker's legal name changes to Pat Lyn McConnell.\n\n* '''August''': Baker and McConnell visit friends in [[Mankato]]. While there, McConnell applies and receives a marriage license.<ref name=\"Free Press\">Issued by the Clerk of District Court, in [[Mankato]], Fifth Judicial District, [[Blue Earth County]] \n* See: \"Daily Record\", ''Mankato&nbsp;Free Press'', 16&nbsp;August&nbsp;1971, p.&nbsp;?\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\" [binder&nbsp;#7], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> \n\n* '''September''': Rev. Roger Lynn, a [[United Methodist]] minister, validates their marriage contract.<ref name=Bowes>\"Pastor Roger Lynn holds up Baker and McConnell's marriage certificate\"\n* Claire Bowes, \"Jack Baker and Michael McConnell: Gay&nbsp;Americans who married in 1971\", ''BBC&nbsp;News Magazine'', 3&nbsp;July&nbsp;2013 \n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-23159390 available online]. \n* A United Methodist minister officiated at a ceremony in Minneapolis, Hennepin County.</ref><ref name=FREE /> \n\n'''1972''': The Hennepin County Attorney convenes a grand jury, which \"studied the legality of the marriage but found the question not worth pursuing.\"<ref>\"Thus the marriage remained in effect.\"\n* See: \"Homosexual Wins Fight to Take Bar Examination in Minnesota\", ''New York Times'', 7&nbsp;January&nbsp;1973, 55. </ref>\n\n'''1974''': ''The&nbsp;Family Law Reporter''<ref name=FLR>Anon., \"Gay married couple frustrated in adoption bid\", ''The&nbsp;Family Law Reporter'', published by The&nbsp;Bureau of National Affairs, 10&nbsp;December&nbsp;1974, page&nbsp;2103</ref> argues that the \"federal constitution prohibition against ex post facto laws .&nbsp;.&nbsp;. forbids the imposition of punishment for past conduct lawful at the time it was engaged\".<ref name=\"Marriage law\" /> Hence, the Minnesota high court's opinion \u2013 ''[[ Baker v. Nelson]]'' \u2013 does not reach back to Baker and McConnell because the two were married \"a full six weeks\" before that decision.\n\n'''2013''': Thomas Kraemer, a retired professor at [[Oregon State University]], concludes that <span style=\"font-size: .93em; color:maroon; font-family: Silom;\">(U&nbsp;of&nbsp;M)</span>&nbsp;FREE hosted \"the first same-sex couple in history to be legally married\".<ref name=Kraemer>Thomas Kraemer [professor, Oregon State University], \"Gay marriage discussion in 1953 vs.&nbsp;1963 and today\", ''Tom's&nbsp;OSU'', posted 16&nbsp;December&nbsp;2013; [http://tomsosu.blogspot.com/2013/12/gay-marriage-discussion-in-1953-vs-1963.html available online]</ref> \n\n* Records at ''The National Archives''<ref name=Archives>Anon., \"Hidden Treasures from the Stacks: pushing for equality\", ''The&nbsp;National Archives at Kansas City'', September&nbsp;2013, 7; [https://www.archives.gov/kansas-city/press/newsletter/2013-september.pdf#page=7 available online]</ref> verify that \"McConnell and Baker's marriage license [from Blue&nbsp;Earth County, MN] was never revoked. They are still married and have been for the last forty two years.\"\n\n=== Federal courts respond ===\n'''1971''': Both state and federal courts rejected the marriage, others approved.<ref>\"What is believed to be the first same-sex marriage in the United States was performed in Minnesota.\"\n* Courtesy: Pat Kessler, \"A Rare Glimpse At Minn.'s 1st Gay Wedding In 1971\", ''WCCO'' [CBS, Minnesota], 31&nbsp;July&nbsp;2013; [http://minnesota.cbslocal.com/2013/07/29/a-rare-glimpse-at-minns-1st-gay-wedding-in-1971/ available online].\n* also, Naomi Pescovitz, \"Pastor Reflects Back on Minn. Gay Marriage\", ''KSTP-TV'' [Minneapolis,&nbsp;MN], 16&nbsp;May&nbsp;2013; {{YouTube|5MdGM9xBIMQ|available online}}.\n* and, Associated Press, \"They're Mr. and Mr.\", ''San Francisco Chronicle'', 8&nbsp;September&nbsp;1971,&nbsp;3</ref> \n\n* Validity of the marriage depended on how Minnesota's [[Baker_v._Nelson#Appeal_to_the_Minnesota_Supreme_Court|marriage law]] was interpreted.<ref name=\"Marriage law\" /> A direct appeal to the United States Supreme Court was [[Baker_v._Nelson#Appeal_to_the_U.S._Supreme_Court|dismissed]].<ref>409 U.S. 810, 93&nbsp;S.Ct.&nbsp;37, 34&nbsp;L.Ed.2d&nbsp;65&nbsp;(1972)</ref> \n\n* While an appeal to the Minnesota Supreme Court was pending, McConnell re-applied and obtained a [[Michael_McConnell_and_Jack_Baker#Adoption,_name_change,_marriage|marriage license]].<ref name=\"Free Press\" /> By Order of Assistant Chief Judge Gregory Anderson, \"The marriage is declared to be in all respects valid.\"<ref name=ruling />\n\n'''1973''': A joint tax return for 1973 was rejected by the Internal Revenue Service.<ref>Anon., \"Homosexual Couple Contest I.R.S. Ban On a Joint Return\", ''The&nbsp;New York Times'', 5&nbsp;Jan.&nbsp;1975,&nbsp;55</ref>\n\n'''1974''': McConnell listed Baker as an [[Michael_McConnell_and_Jack_Baker#Adoption,_name_change,_marriage|adopted \"child\"]] on his tax returns from 1974 through 2004 for which he claimed a deduction as [[head of household]]. That benefit ended when Congress limited the deduction for an adopted child under the age of 19.<ref>Anon., \"Form 1040 Instructions\", ''Internal Revenue Service'' (2005), 19; [https://www.irs.gov/pub/irs-prior/i1040gi--2005.pdf#page=19 available online]</ref>\n\n'''1976''': A claim filed with the Veterans Administration was rejected<ref>''McConnell v. Nooner'':\n* District Court: No.&nbsp;4-75-Civ.&nbsp;566 (D.&nbsp;Minn. 20&nbsp;April&nbsp;1976)\n* and, United States Court of Appeals, Eighth Circuit: 547&nbsp;F.2d&nbsp;54 (8th&nbsp;Cir.&nbsp;1976)</ref> because \"Minnesota law prohibits same sex marriages<ref>[[Baker_v._Nelson]], 291&nbsp;Minn.&nbsp;310, 191&nbsp;N.W.2d&nbsp;185&nbsp;(1971)</ref> .&nbsp;.&nbsp;.\"\n\n==Employment discrimination==\n'''1970''': The <span style=\"font-size: .93em; color:maroon; font-family: Silom;\">(U&nbsp;of&nbsp;M)</span> Librarian offers Michael McConnell the position of Head of the Cataloging Division at the library on the St.&nbsp;Paul campus.<ref name=\"job offer\"> '''1970''': Letter to Michael McConnell,\n* from Ralph&nbsp;H. Hopp, University Librarian, ''University of Minnesota'' [Minneapolis], 27&nbsp;April;\n* also, see Randy Tigue, \"Regent: FREE&nbsp;member case is a matter of public&nbsp;relations\", ''Minnesota Daily'', 16&nbsp;July,&nbsp;1;\n* and, letter from James&nbsp;F. Hogg, Secretary, Board of Regents, ''University of Minnesota'', 10&nbsp;July. \"... your conduct, as represented in the public and University news media, is not consistent with the best interest of the University.\" \n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;5a&nbsp;-&nbsp;e], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> After McConnell applies for a marriage license, regent&nbsp;Daniel Gainey insists that \"homosexuality is about the worst thing there is.\"<ref name=\"job offer\" /> \n\nThe Board of Regents rejects the offer.<ref name=\"job offer\" /> McConnell sues in federal [https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/district-courts/FSupp/316/809/1951718/ <span style=\"color:blue\">District Court</span>] and prevails.<ref>Bob Lundegaard, \"University Ordered to Hire Homosexual\", ''Minneapolis Tribune'', 10&nbsp;September&nbsp;1970,&nbsp;23</ref>\n\n'''1971''': The regents appeal to the [https://openjurist.org/451/f2d/193/mcconnell-v-anderson <span style=\"color:blue\">Eighth Circuit Court of Appeals</span>],<ref>Anon., \"Homosexual Wins a Suit over Hiring\", ''New York Times'', 20&nbsp;September&nbsp;1970; [https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1970/09/20/355908502.pdf available online], accessed February 7, 2012</ref> which concludes that the University did not restrict free speech. Instead, the court rules, it was McConnell who wants \"to pursue an activist role in implementing his controversial ideas concerning the social status to be accorded homosexuals and thereby to foist tacit approval of the socially repugnant concept upon his employer.\"<ref>Michelle Andrea Wolf and Alfred P. Kielwasser, eds., \"Gay People, Sex, and the Media\", ''Haworth Press'' (1991), 237; [https://books.google.com/books?id=Y_Hd0F2J7LEC&pg=PA237& available online], accessed February 7, 2012</ref>\n\n'''1972''': More than 80% of the student body voice disapproval of the regents' action.<ref>\"Do you think the University was justified in firing McConnell because of his open declaration of homosexuality?\"\n* yes&nbsp;=&nbsp;10%, no&nbsp;=&nbsp;81%, no opinion&nbsp;=&nbsp;8%, other&nbsp;=&nbsp;1%\n* See: Office of Student Affairs, \"Research Bulletin\", ''University of Minnesota'', Winter&nbsp;1972  \n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;5a&nbsp;-&nbsp;e], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref>\n\nMcConnell is hired by the [[Hennepin County Library]] <ref>1972: Then, a diverse and growing system of 26&nbsp;facilities; \n* he rises to the level of <span style=\"color:red\">Coordinating Librarian</span> before retiring.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes 6a-b], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> and retires 37&nbsp;years later. The Board of Commissioners commends him for his service.<ref>See: \"Item&nbsp;7A - Commendation of Michael McConnell\", ''Hennepin County Board of Commissioners'', 30&nbsp;November&nbsp;2010; [http://hennepinmn.granicus.com/MediaPlayer.php?view_id=10&amp;clip_id=1134 available online].</ref>\n\n'''2012''': University president [[Eric Kaler]] offers McConnell an apology for the \"<span style=\"color:red\">reprehensible</span>\" treatment he endured from the Board of Regents in 1970.<ref>2012: \"News\", ''University News Service'', 22&nbsp;June\n* 2018: President Kaler affirmed his 2012 News statements. Action taken by our Board in 1970, he said, \"is today worthy of deep criticism - of rebuke and censure.\" See: Email to Logan Chelmo, 27&nbsp;June&nbsp;2018; class of 2018, Shakopee High School, located in Shakopee, Minnesota\n* 2020: McConnell is enrolled as a member of the Heritage Society of the President's Club. See: Letter from xxx, 6&nbsp;June&nbsp;2020  \n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\" [Binder #7, MEMORANDUM for the record], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> He regrets that it occurred and assures that such practices would not be consistent with official actions at this time.\n\nMcConnell accepts the assurance.<ref>Statement from Michael McConnell, on his letterhead, 25&nbsp;July\n* See: Gift&nbsp;#1, accepted by Kristin Lockhart, Associate Vice President for Equity and Diversity.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\" [Binder&nbsp;#8], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> \"Thank you, President Kaler, for offering to remove the cloud that shamed the <span style=\"font-size: .93em; color:maroon; font-family: Silom;\">(U&nbsp;of&nbsp;M)</span>. Your offer is accepted.\"\n\n==Career in law and politics==\n'''June 1972''': Baker led the DFL Gay Rights Caucus<ref>'''For Release Any Time''', \"Gay Machine Startles DFL Regulars\", ''DFL Gay Rights Caucus'', 9&nbsp;June&nbsp;1972.</ref> at the State Convention of the [[Minnesota Democratic\u2013Farmer\u2013Labor Party]]. After the caucus proposed \"legislation defining marriage as a civil contract between any two adults\",<ref>Resolution&nbsp;71.d, \"The 1972 DFL Platform\", ''Minnesota Democratic-Farmer-Labor State Central Committee'', 9&nbsp;-&nbsp;11&nbsp;June&nbsp;1972 at Rochester, MN.</ref> the delegates approved that wording for inclusion in the party platform. This was the first time a major United States political party encouraged support for marriage equality.\n\n'''December''': Baker graduated from the [[University of Minnesota Law School]].<ref>Malcolm Moos, President, ''University of Minnesota'', 13&nbsp;December&nbsp;1972: \"The Degree Of Juris Doctor With All Its Privileges And Obligations\" is conferred</ref> His request to take the bar examination raised questions of fraud surrounding his [[Timeline_of_same-sex_marriage#1970s|1971 marriage license]]. At a hearing, Baker was defended by the Minnesota Civil Liberties Union.<ref>Anon., \"Marriage hurdle cleared, Baker to take bar exams\", ''Minneapolis Star'', 28&nbsp;December 1972,&nbsp;2</ref> The State Board of Law Examiners reviewed the facts and concluded that he was entitled to take the exam.<ref name=bar>{{cite news|title=Homosexual Wins Fights to Take Bar Examination in Minnesota|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1973/01/07/119453382.pdf |accessdate=March 20, 2013|newspaper=New York Times|date=January 7, 1973}}</ref> Later, he was admitted to the bar.<ref> October 2002: In a MEMO for the record, Baker explains why lobbying by the Chief Justice, Oscar Knutson, failed to deny him a license to practice law.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volume&nbsp;7a, section&nbsp;II], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref>\n\nBaker campaigned for Associate Justice of the Minnesota Supreme Court five times. He argued that each opponent violated the Code of Judicial Conduct<ref name=\"Results\">Jack Baker questioned why some judges were allowed to ignore the Code of Judicial Conduct.\n* 1970: Canon&nbsp;5E. '''Arbitration'''. \"A judge should not act as an arbitrator or mediator.\" \n* 1994: Canon&nbsp;4F. '''Service as Arbitrator or Mediator'''. \"A judge shall not act as an arbitrator or mediator or otherwise perform judicial functions in a private capacity unless expressly authorized by law.\"\n* 1978: [http://www.minnesotalegalhistoryproject.org/assets/Election%20Results%201857-2016.pdf#page=72 C. Donald Peterson]\n* 1980: [http://www.minnesotalegalhistoryproject.org/assets/Election%20Results%201857-2016.pdf#page=73 George M. Scott]\n* 1982: [http://www.minnesotalegalhistoryproject.org/assets/Election%20Results%201857-2016.pdf#page=74 John E. Simonett]\n* 1984: [http://www.minnesotalegalhistoryproject.org/assets/Election%20Results%201857-2016.pdf#page=74 Douglas K. Amdahl]\n* 2002: [http://www.minnesotalegalhistoryproject.org/assets/Election%20Results%201857-2016.pdf#page=84 Paul H. Anderson]\n* others\n* Courtesy: Douglas A. Hedrin, \"Results of Elections of Justices to the Minnesota Supreme Court 1857-2016\", ''Minnesota Legal History Project''\n* Details: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volume&nbsp;8c], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> by heading the [[C._Donald_Peterson#Minnesota News Council|Minnesota News Council]] (MNC).<ref name=\"rule_of_law\">Jack Baker, \"2002 Judicial '''Plebiscite'''\", ''Minnesota State Bar Association'', September&nbsp;2002\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volume&nbsp;8c], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> \n\nEthics of C. Donald Peterson<ref name=Results /> were questioned in 1978, George Scott<ref name=Results /> in 1980, John Simonett<ref name=Results /><ref>See: Initial Annual Registration for a Minnesota Non-Profit Corporation, ''Office of the Secretary of State''. \n* \"Effective August 1, 1989, all non-profit corporations are now required to file an annual registration once every calendar year. Please review the information on the label and read all directions before completing this form.\"\n* Corporate Charter Number: L-559 \n* Corporate Name: Minnesota News Council \n* [[Registered Office]] Address: '''230&nbsp;State&nbsp;Capital''', St.&nbsp;Paul, MN [chambers of the Minnesota Supreme Court before moving to a new location] \n* Signature: [Associate Justice] '''John&nbsp;E. Simonett''' \n* Title of Office: Chair \n* Date: 1/22/90\n* Courtesy: ''Minnesota Historical Society''</ref> in 1982, Douglas Amdahl<ref name=Results /> in 1984 and [[Paul H. Anderson]]<ref name=Results /> in 2002. In the ''Plebiscite'' mailed to more than 14,900 attorneys in Minnesota, Baker challenged the bar to end special relationships between Justices of Minnesota's Supreme Court and MNC.<ref name=rule_of_law /> Nevertheless, collusion continued.<ref>The list of \"Supreme Court Justices who chaired the News Council\"\n* 1971-80: C. Donald Peterson\n* [also: George M. Scott]\n* 1980-82: Douglas K. Amdahl\n* 1982-94: John E. Simonett\n* 1995-97: Paul H. Anderson\n* 1998-2006: Edward Stringer\n* See: email from Susan Hansen, <newscncl@mtn.org>, 14 June 2000.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volume 7a], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, University of Minnesota Libraries</ref> \n\nBenefits bestowed on a judge who ignored the Code of Judicial Conduct<ref name=Results /> and who [[C._Donald_Peterson#Minnesota News Council|helped to mediate]] private disputes continued even after the MNC was ejected from court chambers in 1994.<ref>Remaining offices for the Minnesota Supreme Court moved from 230&nbsp;State&nbsp;Capitol in January\n* \u201cEmployees coped. They moved into the newly remodeled space floor-by-floor and coexisted with construction over a period of time from September through '''December''' [1994].\u201d\n* See: Roland C. Amundson, \u201cA Search for Place: The History of the Minnesota Judicial Center\u201d, ''Minnesota Court of Appeals'', 1995,&nbsp;67.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volume&nbsp;8c], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref><ref>Not until James H. Gilbert resigned as Associate Justice and was hired by MNC in 2007 as its \"Hearing Chair\" did MNC stop recruiting judges to mediate its disputes.\n* See: email from Sarah E. Bauer, Interim Director, Minnesota News Council, 11&nbsp;May&nbsp;2007;\n* new address: '''12&nbsp;South Sixth&nbsp;Street''', Suite&nbsp;927, Minneapolis, MN&nbsp;55402.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volume&nbsp;8c], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> MNC ceased to exist in 2011.<ref>Gail Rosenblum, \"News council's demise is bad news for all who value the truth\", ''Star&nbsp;Tribune'', 23&nbsp;February 2011, B1</ref>\n\n==Later years==\n[[File:BakerMcConnell.jpg|thumb|Baker and McConnell in 2016]]\nIn 2003, Baker and McConnell amended their individual tax returns for the year 2000, filing jointly as a couple. They offered proof of a valid marriage license issued in Blue Earth County. The IRS challenged the validity of the marriage license and argued that, even if the license were valid, the [[Defense of Marriage Act]] prohibited the IRS from recognizing it. McConnell brought suit and the [[United States District Court for the District of Minnesota|U.S. District Court for Minnesota]] upheld the IRS ruling in ''McConnell v. United States'' on January 3, 2005,<ref>{{cite web|title=McConnell v. United States, January 3, 2005|url=http://www.lawprofessorblogs.com/taxprof/linkdocs/2005-1056-1.pdf|publisher=US District Court for Minnesota|accessdate=21 March 2013}}</ref> and the Eighth Circuit Court of Appeals affirmed the District Court's ruling on July 17, 2006, saying that McConnell could not relitigate the question decided in ''Baker v. Nelson''.<ref>{{cite web|title=McConnell v. United States|url=http://docs.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/ca8/05-1781/051781u-2011-02-25.pdf?1301253248|publisher=8th Circuit Court of Appeals|accessdate=21 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nBaker and McConnell were still living as a married couple as late as May 2015.<ref name=NYT051715>{{cite news |last=Eckholm |first=Eric|title=The Same-Sex Couple Who Got a Marriage License in 1971|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/17/us/the-same-sex-couple-who-got-a-marriage-license-in-1971.html|accessdate=May 17, 2015|newspaper=The New York Times|date=May 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe U.S. Supreme Court agreed in 2015, \"to decide the issue Jack Baker and Mike McConnell tried to bring before it in 1972: Do same-sex couples have a constitutional right to get married?\"<ref>Roger Parloff, \"12 key moments that led to the Supreme Court's same-sex marriage case\", ''fortune.com'' (posted 16&nbsp;January&nbsp;2015); [http://fortune.com/2015/01/18/same-sex-marriage-supreme-court/ available online]</ref> That case was dismissed \"for want of a substantial federal question.\"<ref name=greenhouse>{{cite news |last=Greenhouse |first=Linda |title=Wedding Bells|url=http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/03/20/wedding-bells/|accessdate=March 21, 2013|newspaper=New York Times|date=March 20, 2013}}</ref> Minnesota's Attorney General argued, in March 2015, as a friend of the court: \"The procreation rationale [used by the Minnesota Supreme Court] does not support the prohibition of same-sex marriage\".<ref name=swanson>Lori Swanson, Attorney General, State of Minnesota; \"Brief of the State of Minnesota as AMICUS CURIAE in support of petitioners\", Obergefell v. Hodges; ''In The Supreme Court of the United States'', March&nbsp;2015, 18; [http://thecolu.mn/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/MNSCOTUSbrief.pdf#page=30 available online]</ref>\n[[File:MikeMcConnell.jpg|thumb|right|upright|McConnell in 2016]]\n\n==Interview==\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.mprnews.org/story/2015/07/16/baker-mcconnell|title=For Mpls. couple, gay marriage ruling is a victory 43 years in the making|author=Tom Crann|date=16 July 2015|publisher=Minnesota Public Radio News}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.pri.org/stories/2015-06-25/meet-two-men-who-managed-get-first-known-same-sex-marriage-license-back-1970|title=Meet the two men who managed to get the first known same-sex marriage license - back in 1970|author=T.J. Raphael|date=25 June 2015|publisher=The Takeaway, Public Radio International}}\n\n==Short documentary==\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cse4s3gmbPE|title=Baker v. Nelson: The Original Case for Gay Marriage|author=Joseph Kase and Jeremiah Smith|date=Feb 2014|publisher=YouTube}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://minnesota.cbslocal.com/2013/07/29/a-rare-glimpse-at-minns-1st-gay-wedding-in-1971/|title=A Rare Glimpse At Minn.'s 1st Gay Wedding In 1971|author=Pat Kessler|date=29 July 2013|publisher=WCCO-TV, Minneapolis}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/17/us/the-same-sex-couple-who-got-a-marriage-license-in-1971.html|title=The Same-Sex Couple Who Got a Marriage License in 1971|author= Erik Eckholm|date=16 May 2015|publisher=www.nytimes.com|newspaper=The New York Times}}\n* {{cite magazine|url=http://time.com/3843579/influential-marriages/|title=The 25 Most Influential Marriages of All Time|author=Lisa Grunwald|date=12 May 2015|magazine=TIME}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.qlibrary.org/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Seeds_for_Gay_Marriage_Equality.pdf#page=2|title=Who defined the gay agenda?|author=Pat Lyn McConnell|date=Jan 2014|publisher=[[Quatrefoil Library]]}}\n* {{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-23159390|title=Jack Baker and Michael McConnell: Gay Americans who married in 1971|author=Claire Bowes|date=4 July 2013|accessdate=4 July 2013|work=BBC News}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.qlibrary.org/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Quatrefolio-2012-Pride.pdf#page=5|title=Minnesota Led the Two Coasts on Marriage Rights, and Should Do So Again: Jack Baker and Michael McConnell|author=Robert Frame|year=2012|publisher=Quatrefoil Library}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.lib.umn.edu/sites/default/files/media/Quest%20copy.pdf|title=A Quest for Full Equality|author=Ken Bronson|year=2004|publisher=University of Minnesota Libraries}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.brumm.com/schools/gaylib/earlybrumm.html#baker|title=My Own Early Gay History|author=Dennis Brumm|year=1971|publisher=www.brumm.com}}\n* Memoir of Michael McConnell (2016) as told to Gail Langer Karwoski, [http://www.worldcat.org/title/wedding-heard-round-the-world-americas-first-gay-marriage/oclc/926312828&referer=brief_results \"The Wedding Heard Heard 'Round the World: America's First Gay Marriage.\"], Minneapolis, MN: ''University of Minnesota Press''.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|25em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baker, Jack}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:LGBT in Minnesota]]\n[[Category:University of Minnesota Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Minnesota]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights activists from the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Y6f&tP4z", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eStudent Body President:edit for accuracy", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_McConnell_and_Jack_Baker"}
{"title_page": "Veronica Clare", "text_new": "{{infobox television |\n | show_name = Veronica Clare\n| genre  = [[Crime drama]]\n | image = VeronicaClareTitleCard.jpg\n | caption = Title card\n|alt=A black-and-white image of a woman against a postcard-style image of a cityscape. There is text saying Veronica Clare.\n | runtime = 60 minutes\n | creator= [[Jeffrey Bloom]]\n | producer = \n | camera = \n | starring = {{plain list|\n*Laura Robinson\n*[[Robert Beltran]]\n*[[Tony Plana]]\n*[[Christina Pickles]]\n*Robert Ruth\n*Robert Sutton\n*Wayne Chou\n}}\n| theme_music_composer = [[Gil Mell\u00e9]]\n| location = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]\n| company = Hearst Entertainment, Inc\n | country = United States\n | language = English\n | network = [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]]\n | first_aired = July 23\n | last_aired = September 17, 1991\n| picture_format = [[480i]]/[[576i]] ([[4:3]] [[Standard-definition television|SDTV]])\n| audio_format = [[Stereophonic sound|Stereo]]\n | num_seasons = 1\n | num_episodes = 9\n | list_episodes = Veronica Clare#Episodes\n| executive_producer = Jeffrey Bloom\n}}\n\n'''''Veronica Clare''''' is an American [[crime drama]], created by [[Jeffrey Bloom]], which originally aired for one season on [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]] beginning on July 23, 1991, to September 17, 1991. Played by Laura Robinson, the eponymous Clare is a [[private investigator]] and part-owner of a [[Chinatown, Los Angeles|Chinatown]] [[jazz club]], who uses intelligence rather than physical strength to solve cases. The supporting cast includes [[Robert Beltran]], [[Tony Plana]], [[Christina Pickles]], Robert Ruth, Robert Sutton, and Wayne Chou. [[Gil Mell\u00e9]] composed the show's soundtrack. The show was developed as one of three television programs ordered by Lifetime in 1991. It was one of the network's first scripted programs following its successful acquisition of ''[[The Days and Nights of Molly Dodd]]'' from [[NBC]].\n\nAfter nine episodes had aired, the network placed the show on hiatus before it was eventually canceled. It has never been released on DVD or Blu-ray, or made available on online-streaming services. The episodes were rebroadcast as four [[television movie]]s in 1991 and 1992. Critical response to ''Veronica Clare'' was mixed, with [[Television criticism|commentators]] divided over its style. The series attracted feminist analysis, with a focus on Clare's identity as a female private investigator. Critics have compared Robinson to other actresses including [[Kathleen Turner]] and [[Lauren Bacall]], and Clare to other fictional female detectives like [[V.I. Warshawski]].\n\n==Premise and characters==\nDescribed as a \"moody [[Film noir|noir]] [[Detective fiction|detective drama]]\" by the ''[[Sun-Sentinel]]'',<ref name=\"Source1\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1991-09-01/entertainment/9102030267_1_veronica-clare-lifetime-narrowcast|title=`Veronica Clare` Being Pulled From Lifetime|date=September 1, 1991|work=[[Sun-Sentinel]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171022200911/http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1991-09-01/entertainment/9102030267_1_veronica-clare-lifetime-narrowcast|archivedate=October 22, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Veronica Clare'' revolves around the titular character (Laura Robinson) and her work as a [[private investigator]] and a partial owner of a [[Chinatown, Los Angeles|Chinatown]] [[jazz club]].<ref name=\"Source3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/tv/1991/07/21/lifetime-premieres-three-original-series-tuesday/b320b374-21cd-4dfa-9750-11639daaa427/|title=Lifetime Premieres Three Original Series Tuesday|last=Brennan|first=Patricia|date=July 21, 1991|work=[[The Washington Post]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171022200911/https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/tv/1991/07/21/lifetime-premieres-three-original-series-tuesday/b320b374-21cd-4dfa-9750-11639daaa427/?utm_term=.7c725e81e0b8|archivedate=October 22, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Source4\">{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1980&dat=19910721&id=I34iAAAAIBAJ&sjid=DK8FAAAAIBAJ&pg=1296,4084300&hl=en|title='Veronica Clare' premieres tonight on Lifetime|date=July 21, 1991|work=[[The Item]]|accessdate=October 22, 2017}}</ref> [[Mass communication]] professor Eileen R. Meehan and [[media studies]] professor Jackie Byars identified the show as an example of a [[Cozy mystery|soft-boiled detective series]].<ref name=\"Book22\">[[#MeehanByarsl2004|Meehan & Byars (2004)]]: p. 95</ref> Told from Clare's perspective,<ref name=\"Book4\">[[#Green1998|Green (1998)]]: pp. 164-165</ref><ref name=\"Book3\">[[#Green1998|Green (1998)]]: p. 164</ref> the mysteries showcase how she uses her intelligence to solve cases.<ref name=\"Book4\" /> Characterized as \"not physically tough, but merely determined\",<ref name=\"Book6\">[[#Green1998|Green (1998)]]: p. 240</ref> Clare avoids using guns, and engaging in hand-to-hand combat, instead relying on her intellect to solve cases.<ref name=\"Book4\" /> She has no interest in being paid for her investigations,<ref name=\"Source6\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1991-07-23/entertainment/ca-48_1_tv-reviews|title=A Crime Package That Doesn't Pay Off|last=Rosenberg|first=Howard|date=July 23, 1991|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171022200911/http://articles.latimes.com/1991-07-23/entertainment/ca-48_1_tv-reviews|archivedate=October 22, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and instead only takes on cases that interest her.<ref name=\"Books122\">[[Veronica Clare#brooksmarsh2009|Brooks & Marsh (2009)]]: p. 794</ref> Clare serves as the narrator for each episode.<ref name=\"Book4\" />\n\nHer business partner Duke Rado ([[Robert Beltran]]), and [[Los Angeles Police Department]] officer Nikki Swarcek ([[Tony Plana]]) assist Clare.<ref name=\"Source3\" /> Rado, the show's male lead, is not presented as Clare's [[love interest]] or as a \"source of wisdom and authorization for her\".<ref name=\"Book4\" /> Swarcek, an [[expatriate]] from Poland, carries an [[unrequited love]] for Clare.<ref name=\"Source3\" /><ref name=\"Source4\" /> In several episodes, Clare is shown writing letters to an unidentified lover whose gender is never revealed.<ref name=\"Book4\" /> Had the show had continued, the audience would have learned more about Clare's past.<ref name=\"Books122\"/> While absent from the pilot episode, Clare's friend Kelsey Horne ([[Christina Pickles]]) features in its later storylines.<ref name=\"Source3\" /> She works for a [[Book collecting|rare bookstore]].<ref name=\"Source4\" /> Other cast members include Sergeant Swede (Robert Ruth), Rocko the [[bartender]] (Robert Sutton), and Jimmy (Wayne Chou).<ref name=\"Books122\"/><ref name=\"Book112\">[[Veronica Clare#Terrace2008|Terrace (2008)]]: pp. 1139-1140</ref>\n\n== Production ==\nFollowing the successful acquisition of ''[[The Days and Nights of Molly Dodd]]'' from [[NBC]], [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]] went through an \"emergent period\" in which it began to develop original television dramas.<ref name=\"Book22\"/> ''Veronica Clare'' was created by [[Jeffrey Bloom]],<ref name=\"SourceCreator\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RxHbPxbBM1AC&pg=PP160&lpg=PP160&dq=%22Veronica+Clare%22+%22Jeffrey+Bloom%22&source=bl&ots=AWS0Fi34CZ&sig=mptPLiMBIo6sNH6BggXiQLCWhZ8&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjyg_m87bXYAhXIQCYKHeSXAMw4ChDoAQgzMAI#v=onepage&q=%22Veronica%20Clare%22%20%22Jeffrey%20Bloom%22&f=false|title=Veronica Clare|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=July 29, 1991|accessdate=December 31, 2017}}</ref> and produced by Hearst Entertainment, Inc.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://catalog.loc.gov/vwebv/holdingsInfo?searchId=23544&recCount=25&recPointer=0&bibId=11672923|title=Veronica Clare. Affairs with death|date=1992|publisher=[[Library of Congress]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171023043734/https://catalog.loc.gov/vwebv/holdingsInfo?searchId=23544&recCount=25&recPointer=0&bibId=11672923|archivedate=October 23, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> It was one of three scripted programs ordered by Lifetime in 1991; the other two were ''[[The Hidden Room (TV series)|The Hidden Room]]'' and ''[[Confessions of Crime]]''.<ref name=\"Source2\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1991-07-23/features/1991204100_1_veronica-clare-laura-robinson-hidden-room|title='Veronica Clare' stands out among new Lifetime series|last=Zurawik|first=David|date=July 23, 1991|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171022200911/http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1991-07-23/features/1991204100_1_veronica-clare-laura-robinson-hidden-room|archivedate=October 22, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Each of the shows feature elements of [[Mystery fiction|mystery]] or [[suspense]].<ref name=\"Book1\">[[Veronica Clare#NewmanWitsell2016|Newman & Witsell (2016)]]: p. 10</ref>\n\nWriting for the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', [[Howard Rosenberg]] described the programs' development as Lifetime's \"most ambitious effort to date\".<ref name=\"Source6\" /> After picking up ''Veronica Clare'' for 13 episodes,<ref name=\"SourceReRuns\" /> Lifetime marketed the show toward women.<ref name=\"Source1\" /><ref name=\"Source2\" /> This followed the network's tradition of acquiring shows depicting female characters in traditionally male occupations; other examples include a female police officer in [[Lady Blue (TV series)|''Lady Blue'']], a female physician in ''[[Kay O'Brien]]'', and a female private detective in [[Partners in Crime (U.S. TV series)|''Partners in Crime'']].<ref name=\"Book10\">[[#DinesHumez2003|Dines & Humez (2003)]]: p. 620</ref>\n\nEven though the series is set in a contemporary period in Los Angeles,<ref name=\"Source4\" /><ref name=\"Book112\"/> a writer for ''[[The Item]]'' felt that it had a \"[[historical drama|period]] feel\" reminiscent of the 1940s and the 1980s.<ref name=\"Source4\" /> Shay Austin contributed to the series as its [[production designer]].<ref name=\"SourceCreator\" /> Each episode features camera techniques similar to those used in [[film noir]], and has a score composed by American jazz musician [[Gil Mell\u00e9]].<ref name=\"Source4\" />\n\n==Episodes==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%; background:#fff;\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#39f;\"| No.\n! style=\"background:#39f;\"| Title\n! style=\"background:#39f;\"| Directed by\n! style=\"background:#39f;\"| Written by\n! style=\"background:#39f;\"| Original air date\n{{Episode list\n |Title=Veronica's Aunt\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1991|7|23}}\n |EpisodeNumber=1\n |DirectedBy= [[Jeffrey Bloom]]\n |WrittenBy= Jeffrey Bloom\n |ShortSummary= Veronica is hired to help her aunt who has been threatened by her recently deceased husband's mob employers.\n |LineColor=3399ff\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |Title=Reed\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1991|7|30}}\n |EpisodeNumber=2\n |DirectedBy= Mark Cullingham\n |WrittenBy= Jeffrey Bloom\n |ShortSummary= Veronica tries to solve a mystery involving one of Duke's close friends.\n |LineColor=3399ff\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |Title=Anonymous\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1991|8|6}}\n |EpisodeNumber=3\n |DirectedBy= [[Rafal Zielinski]]\n |WrittenBy= Jeffrey Bloom\n |ShortSummary= When an amnesiac Romanian woman is found severely beaten, Veronica tries to help her remember her past to locate the attacker.\n |LineColor=3399ff\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |Title=The Boxing Story\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1991|8|13}}\n |EpisodeNumber=4\n |DirectedBy= [[Leon Ichaso]]\n |WrittenBy= Jeffrey Bloom and Frank Megna\n |ShortSummary= Veronica is approached by a female boxing manager to determine why her most popular boxer decided to abandon his career.\n |LineColor=3399ff\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |Title=Phoebe\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1991|8|20}}\n |EpisodeNumber=5\n |DirectedBy= [[Frederick King Keller|Fred Keller]]\n |WrittenBy= Jeffrey Bloom\n |ShortSummary= A woman hires Veronica to find her missing husband.\n |LineColor=3399ff\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |Title=Slow Violence\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1991|8|27}}\n |EpisodeNumber=6\n |DirectedBy= Deborah Dalton\n |WrittenBy= Nancy Bond\n |ShortSummary= A singer at the club pushes Veronica to babysit her child, and then suddenly disappears.\n |LineColor=3399ff\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |Title=Mr. Duvall\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1991|9|3}}\n |EpisodeNumber=7\n |DirectedBy= Fred Keller\n |WrittenBy= [[Jane Atkins]]\n |ShortSummary=Veronica is tasked to locate a wealthy man's missing wife. \n |LineColor=3399ff\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |Title=Love, Amanda\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1991|9|10}}\n |EpisodeNumber=8\n |DirectedBy= [[Amy Goldstein]]\n |WrittenBy= Nina Shengold\n |ShortSummary= Veronica tries to discover what is behind a young girl's murder by piecing together clues from her diary.\n |LineColor=3399ff\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |Title=Pilot\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1991|9|17}}\n |EpisodeNumber=9\n |DirectedBy= [[Donna Deitch]]\n |WrittenBy= Jeffrey Bloom\n |ShortSummary= Veronica is assigned to find a man's brooch, which is believed to have been stolen by his son.\n |LineColor=3399ff\n}}\n|}\n\n==Broadcast history==\n''Veronica Clare'' was broadcast initially on Tuesday nights at 10:00&nbsp;pm&nbsp;[[Eastern Time Zone|EST]],<ref name=\"Source1\" /> and aired directly after ''The Hidden Room'' and ''Confessions of a Crime''.<ref name=\"Source2\" /> [[Rerun]]s aired on Saturdays at 11:00&nbsp;pm&nbsp;EST.<ref name=\"SourceReRuns\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.courant.com/1991-07-19/features/0000213980_1_pat-fili-production-for-lifetime-television-victims|title=`Confessions Of Crime' Opens Lineup|last=Endrst|first=James|work=[[Hartford Courant]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171023050500/http://articles.courant.com/1991-07-19/features/0000213980_1_pat-fili-production-for-lifetime-television-victims|archivedate=October 23, 2017}}</ref> Despite delivering \"pretty respectable\" ratings, the show was placed on hiatus on September 24, 1991,<ref name=\"Source1\" /> after nine episodes had aired.<ref name=\"Source1\" /><ref name=\"Book8\">[[#Mizejewski2004|Mizejewski (2004)]]: p. 208</ref> ''Veronica Clare'', along with ''The Hidden Room'' and ''Confessions of a Crime'', had lower ratings than original films produced by the network.<ref name=\"Book7\">[[#Lotz2010|Lotz (2010)]]: p. 188</ref>\n\nNetwork spokesperson Alex Wagner attributed the decision to pull the series from air to issues with its production; he explained: \"We`re shutting down to address creative concerns, with the idea of rewriting.\" A writer from the ''Sun-Sentinel'' found this surprising given that television shows aimed at a [[niche market]] were often not required to deliver immediate high ratings in comparison to [[network television]].<ref name=\"Source1\" /> Lifetime canceled the series during its hiatus.<ref name=\"Book1\" /> Media studies scholar Eithne Johnson claimed that the network reached this decision due to its \"ambivalence about its 'feminine identity' during prime time\".<ref name=\"Book1\" /> The series has never been made available on DVD or Blu-ray, nor released on an online-streaming service.<ref name=\"SourceHomeRelease\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/shows/Veronica-Clare/4489 |title=Veronica Clare (1991) |publisher=[[TVShowsOnDVD.com]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130304183308/http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/shows/Veronica-Clare/4489 |archivedate=March 4, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1991 and 1992, the nine episodes were converted into four [[television movie]]s and aired on television. The titles of the films were ''Affairs with Death'', ''Deadly Minds'', ''Naked Hearts'', and ''Slow Violence''; they can be requested through the [[Library of Congress]] as [[Video Reel|video reel]]s.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":01\">{{cite web|url=https://catalog.loc.gov/vwebv/holdingsInfo?searchId=23818&recCount=25&recPointer=1&bibId=11635943|title=Veronica Clare. Deadly minds|date=1992|publisher=[[Library of Congress]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171023044515/https://catalog.loc.gov/vwebv/holdingsInfo?searchId=23818&recCount=25&recPointer=1&bibId=11635943|archivedate=October 23, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":012\">{{cite web|url=https://catalog.loc.gov/vwebv/holdingsInfo?searchId=23823&recCount=25&recPointer=2&bibId=11635933|title=Veronica Clare. Veronica Clare|date=1991|publisher=[[Library of Congress]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171023044515/https://catalog.loc.gov/vwebv/holdingsInfo?searchId=23823&recCount=25&recPointer=2&bibId=11635933|archivedate=October 23, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":0123\">{{cite web|url=https://catalog.loc.gov/vwebv/holdingsInfo?searchId=23835&recCount=25&recPointer=3&bibId=11635914|title=Veronica Clare. Slow violence|date=1991|publisher=[[Library of Congress]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171023044515/https://catalog.loc.gov/vwebv/holdingsInfo?searchId=23835&recCount=25&recPointer=3&bibId=11635914|archivedate=October 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Critical reception===\n''Veronica Clare'' has received mixed critical feedback. [[David Zurawik]] of ''[[The Baltimore Sun]]'' praised it as the network's only successful scripted program. Reviewing the first episode, he described the series as having a \"contemporary sensibility with plenty of retro-classic-P.I. atmosphere\".<ref name=\"Source2\" /> ''[[The Washington Post]]'''s Patricia Brennan called the show a stylish one-hour mystery series.<ref name=\"Source3\" /> Ginny Holbert of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' praised the show's style and its actors' performances.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4064749.html|title=Lifetime goes crime-time // Cable programs explore violence, lust and romance|last=Holbert|first=Ginny|date=July 23, 1991|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171023043734/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4064749.html|archivedate=October 23, 2017}} {{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nOther [[Television criticism|critics]] were more negative. Giving the series a C-, David Hiltbrand of [[People (magazine)|''People'']] was critical of the storylines' believability, describing the show's style as \"murky and contrived\". He also criticized Robinson's performance for its \"vacuity\".<ref name=\"Source5\">{{cite web|url=http://people.com/archive/picks-and-pans-review-veronica-clare-vol-36-no-4/|title=Picks and Pans Review: Veronica Clare|last=Hiltbrand|first=David|date=August 5, 1991|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171022200911/http://people.com/archive/picks-and-pans-review-veronica-clare-vol-36-no-4/|archivedate=October 22, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Howard Rosenberg initially praised the pilot as an indication of a \"stylishly mounted, [[Raymond Chandler|Chandleresque]]-style series\", but panned subsequent episodes. He felt that the storylines bordered on a [[parody]] in the style of the 1991 film ''[[The Naked Gun 2\u00bd: The Smell of Fear]]'', and did not match the \"subtlety and a charming playfulness\" of the series' premiere.<ref name=\"Source6\" /> The ''[[Orlando Sentinel]]'''s Nancy Pete criticized ''Veronica Clare'' as \"well-intentioned but ludicrous\",<ref name=\"Source11111\" /> and a reviewer from [[Variety (magazine)|''Variety'']] responded negatively to the pilot's script, writing that \"atmosphere goes only so far\".<ref name=\"SourceCreator\" />\n\n===Critical analysis===\n[[File:Lauren Bacall 1945 (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|right|Clare was compared to [[Lauren Bacall]] (''pictured in 1945'') by critics.<ref name=\"Source4\" /><ref name=\"Books122\"/><ref name=\"SourceCreator\" />|alt=A black-and-white image of a woman with long hair staring towards the camera.]]\n\nFollowing its premiere, ''Veronica Clare'' was described as an example of the rise of lead female characters in mysteries and crime dramas in film and television.<ref name=\"Source6\" /><ref name=\"Source2\" /><ref name=\"Source11111\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1991-08-11/entertainment/9108090275_1_agatha-christie-millhone-ngaio-marsh|title=This Summer, Women Sleuths Are On The Case|date=August 11, 1991|last=Pate|first=Nancy|work=[[Orlando Sentinel]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171023115812/http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1991-08-11/entertainment/9108090275_1_agatha-christie-millhone-ngaio-marsh|archivedate=October 23, 2017}}</ref> Zurawik felt the show's success and impact \"could be a culturally important one\", identifying its focus on a female private investigator as fitting with the \"boom of women writing and starring in mystery fiction\".<ref name=\"Source2\" /> Expressing a similar sentiment, Hiltbrand found the series to be a continuation of \"the season for female private eyes\".<ref name=\"Source5\" /> Rosenberg felt that \"beyond male biases among network programmers\", there was no reason for female detectives to be treated as a \"TV curiosity\".<ref name=\"Source6\" />\n\nClare has been compared to other fictional female detectives, and Robinson to noted actresses. Hiltbrand likened Clare to [[Kathleen Turner]]'s leading role in the 1991 film [[V.I. Warshawski (film)|''V.I. Warshawski'']], and felt that Robinson was attempting a \"mysterious [[Sam Spade|Samantha Spade]] style\".<ref name=\"Source5\" /> A writer for ''The Item'' called the character a \"cross between the [[Lauren Bacall]] of the '40s and the Kathleen Turner of the '80's\", noting intelligence and sexuality as her primary characteristics.<ref name=\"Source4\" /> Television historians [[Tim Brooks (television historian)|Tim Brooks]] and Earle F. Marsh pointed to Clare's \"long flowing hair and reserved demeanor\" as her notable character traits, which recalled Bacall and [[the Andrews Sisters]].<ref name=\"Books122\"/> In a negative review of the character, Rosenberg wrote that Clare was \"a poached egg compared to the [[Hardboiled|hard-boiled]] gumshoe of [[Sara Paretsky]]'s detective stories\" featuring V. I. Warshawski.<ref name=\"Source6\" />\n\nCritics have analyzed Clare's identity as a female detective. Political theorist [[Philip Green (author)|Philip Green]] argued the show portrayed Clare as beautiful to accentuate her \"masculine toughness\" and avoid presenting her as a \"fetishized male in disguise\".<ref name=\"Book4\" /><ref name=\"Book5\">[[#Green1998|Green (1998)]]: p. 241</ref> Green wrote that Clare's appearance was kept separate from \"pure feminized sexuality\" and her skills differed from \"hypermasculine aggression\". He interpreted Clare's role as the narrator as allowing her to never become the object of [[voyeurism]] or the [[male gaze]].<ref name=\"Book4\" /> [[Gender and women's studies]] scholar Susan White noted that ''Veronica Clare''<nowiki/>'s fashion and scenic design played a major role in its identity as a female-driven detective show. White argued that the \"postmodern surplus of feminine details works in tension with the codes of the hardboiled narrative and style\".<ref name=\"Book9\">[[#Mizejewski2004|Mizejewski (2004)]]: p. 199</ref>\n\n== References ==\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Book sources===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last1 = Brooks |first1 = Tim |last2 = Marsh |first2 = Earle F. |title =The Complete Directory to Prime Time Network and Cable TV Shows, 1946-Present|year = 2009 |publisher =Random House Publishing Group |location = New York |isbn = 978-0-345-49773-4 |ref =brooksmarsh2009 }}\n* {{cite book |last1 = Dines |first1 = Gail |last2 = Humez |first2 = Jean M. |title = Gender, Race, and Class in Media: A Text-Reader |year = 2003 |publisher = Sage |location = Thousand Oaks |isbn = 0-7619-2260-1 |ref = DinesHumez2003 |url-access = registration |url = https://archive.org/details/genderraceclassi0000unse }}\n* {{cite book |last1 = Green |first1 = Phillip|title =Cracks in the Pedestal: Ideology and Gender in Hollywood|year = 1998 |publisher =University of Massachusetts Press |location = Amherst |isbn = 1-55849-119-8 |ref =Green1998 }}\n* {{cite book |last1 = Lotz |first1 = Amanda D.|title =Redesigning Women: Television after the Network Era|year = 2010 |publisher =University of Illinois Press|location = Chicago |isbn = 978-0-252-03067-3 |ref =Lotz2010 }}\n* {{cite book |last1 = Meehan|first1 = Eileen R. |last2 = Byars |first2 = Jackie|chapter=Telefeminism: How Lifetime got It's Groove, 1984-1997|pages= 92\u2013104 |editor-last=Allen|editor-first1=Robert Clyde|editor-last2=Hill|editor-first2=Annette|title =The Television Studies Reader|year = 2004 |publisher =Psychology Press |location = New York|isbn = 0-415-28323-X |ref =MeehanByarsl2004 }}\n* {{cite book |last1 = Mizejewski|first1 = Linda|title =Hardboiled and High Heeled: The Woman Detective in Popular Culture|year = 2004 |publisher =Routledge|location = New York |isbn = 0-415-96970-0 |ref =Mizejewski2004 }}\n* {{cite book |last1 = Newman |first1 = Emily L. |last2 = Witsell |first2 = Emily|chapter=Introduction|pages= 1\u201320 |title =The Lifetime Network: Essays on \"Television for Women\" in the 21st Century|year = 2016 |publisher =McFarland |location = Jefferson |isbn = 978-0-7864-9830-7 |ref =NewmanWitsell2016 }}\n* {{cite book |last = Terrace |first = Vincent|title = Encyclopedia of Television Shows, 1925 through 2010 |year = 2008 |publisher = McFarland |location = Jefferson |isbn =978-0-7864-6477-7|ref = Terrace2008}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|101232}}\n*{{Tv.com show|veronica-clare}}\n\n{{Lifetime Shows}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1991 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1991 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:1990s American crime drama television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Lifetime (TV network) original programming]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Los Angeles]]\n", "text_old": "{{infobox television |\n | show_name = Veronica Clare\n| genre  = [[Crime drama]]\n | image = VeronicaClareTitleCard.jpg\n | caption = Title card\n|alt=A black-and-white image of a woman against a postcard-style image of a cityscape. There is text saying Veronica Clare.\n | runtime = 60 minutes\n | creator= [[Jeffrey Bloom]]\n | producer = \n | camera = \n | starring = {{plain list|\n*Laura Robinson\n*[[Robert Beltran]]\n*[[Tony Plana]]\n*[[Christina Pickles]]\n*Robert Ruth\n*Robert Sutton\n*Wayne Chou\n}}\n| theme_music_composer = [[Gil Mell\u00e9]]\n| location = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]\n| company = Hearst Entertainment, Inc\n | country = United States\n | language = English\n | network = [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]]\n | first_aired = July 23\n | last_aired = September 17, 1991\n| picture_format = [[480i]]/[[576i]] ([[4:3]] [[Standard-definition television|SDTV]])\n| audio_format = [[Stereophonic sound|Stereo]]\n | num_seasons = 1\n | num_episodes = 9\n | list_episodes = Veronica Clare#Episodes\n| executive_producer = Jeffrey Bloom\n}}\n\n'''''Veronica Clare''''' is an American [[crime drama]], created by [[Jeffrey Bloom]], which originally aired for one season on [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]] beginning on July 23, 1991, to September 17, 1991. Played by Laura Robinson, the eponymous Clare is a [[private investigator]] and part-owner of a [[Chinatown, Los Angeles|Chinatown]] [[jazz club]], who uses intelligence rather than physical strength to solve cases. The supporting cast includes [[Robert Beltran]], [[Tony Plana]], [[Christina Pickles]], Robert Ruth, Robert Sutton, and Wayne Chou. [[Gil Mell\u00e9]] composed the show's soundtrack. The show was developed as one of three television programs ordered by Lifetime in 1991. It was one of the network's first scripted programs following its successful acquisition of ''[[The Days and Nights of Molly Dodd]]'' from [[NBC]].\n\nAfter nine episodes had aired, the network placed the show on hiatus before it was eventually canceled. It has never been released on DVD or Blu-ray, or made available on online-streaming services. The episodes were rebroadcast as four [[television movie]]s in 1991 and 1992. Critical response to ''Veronica Clare'' was mixed, with [[Television criticism|commentators]] divided over its style. The series attracted feminist analysis, with a focus on Clare's identity as a female private investigator. Critics have compared Robinson to other actresses including [[Kathleen Turner]] and [[Lauren Bacall]], and Clare to other fictional female detectives like [[V.I. Warshawski]].\n\n==Premise and characters==\nDescribed as a \"moody [[Film noir|noir]] [[Detective fiction|detective drama]]\" by the ''[[Sun-Sentinel]]'',<ref name=\"Source1\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1991-09-01/entertainment/9102030267_1_veronica-clare-lifetime-narrowcast|title=`Veronica Clare` Being Pulled From Lifetime|date=September 1, 1991|work=[[Sun-Sentinel]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171022200911/http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1991-09-01/entertainment/9102030267_1_veronica-clare-lifetime-narrowcast|archivedate=October 22, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Veronica Clare'' revolves around the titular character (Laura Robinson) and her work as a [[private investigator]] and a partial owner of a [[Chinatown, Los Angeles|Chinatown]] [[jazz club]].<ref name=\"Source3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/tv/1991/07/21/lifetime-premieres-three-original-series-tuesday/b320b374-21cd-4dfa-9750-11639daaa427/|title=Lifetime Premieres Three Original Series Tuesday|last=Brennan|first=Patricia|date=July 21, 1991|work=[[The Washington Post]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171022200911/https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/tv/1991/07/21/lifetime-premieres-three-original-series-tuesday/b320b374-21cd-4dfa-9750-11639daaa427/?utm_term=.7c725e81e0b8|archivedate=October 22, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Source4\">{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1980&dat=19910721&id=I34iAAAAIBAJ&sjid=DK8FAAAAIBAJ&pg=1296,4084300&hl=en|title='Veronica Clare' premieres tonight on Lifetime|date=July 21, 1991|work=[[The Item]]|accessdate=October 22, 2017}}</ref> [[Mass communication]] professor Eileen R. Meehan and [[media studies]] professor Jackie Byars identified the show as an example of a [[Cozy mystery|soft-boiled detective series]].<ref name=\"Book22\">[[#MeehanByarsl2004|Meehan & Byars (2004)]]: p. 95</ref> Told from Clare's perspective,<ref name=\"Book4\">[[#Green1998|Green (1998)]]: pp. 164-165</ref><ref name=\"Book3\">[[#Green1998|Green (1998)]]: p. 164</ref> the mysteries showcase how she uses her intelligence to solve cases.<ref name=\"Book4\" /> Characterized as \"not physically tough, but merely determined\",<ref name=\"Book6\">[[#Green1998|Green (1998)]]: p. 240</ref> Clare avoids using guns, and engaging in hand-to-hand combat, instead relying on her intellect to solve cases.<ref name=\"Book4\" /> She has no interest in being paid for her investigations,<ref name=\"Source6\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1991-07-23/entertainment/ca-48_1_tv-reviews|title=A Crime Package That Doesn't Pay Off|last=Rosenberg|first=Howard|date=July 23, 1991|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171022200911/http://articles.latimes.com/1991-07-23/entertainment/ca-48_1_tv-reviews|archivedate=October 22, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and instead only takes on cases that interest her.<ref name=\"Books122\">[[Veronica Clare#brooksmarsh2009|Brooks & Marsh (2009)]]: p. 794</ref> Clare serves as the narrator for each episode.<ref name=\"Book4\" />\n\nHer business partner Duke Rado ([[Robert Beltran]]), and [[Los Angeles Police Department]] officer Nikki Swarcek ([[Tony Plana]]) assist Clare.<ref name=\"Source3\" /> Rado, the show's male lead, is not presented as Clare's [[love interest]] or as a \"source of wisdom and authorization for her\".<ref name=\"Book4\" /> Swarcek, an [[expatriate]] from Poland, carries an [[unrequited love]] for Clare.<ref name=\"Source3\" /><ref name=\"Source4\" /> In several episodes, Clare is shown writing letters to an unidentified lover whose gender is never revealed.<ref name=\"Book4\" /> Had the show had continued, the audience would have learned more about Clare's past.<ref name=\"Books122\"/> While absent from the pilot episode, Clare's friend Kelsey Horne ([[Christina Pickles]]) features in its later storylines.<ref name=\"Source3\" /> She works for a [[Book collecting|rare bookstore]].<ref name=\"Source4\" /> Other cast members include Sergeant Swede (Robert Ruth), Rocko the [[bartender]] (Robert Sutton), and Jimmy (Wayne Chou).<ref name=\"Books122\"/><ref name=\"Book112\">[[Veronica Clare#Terrace2008|Terrace (2008)]]: pp. 1139-1140</ref>\n\n== Production ==\nFollowing the successful acquisition of ''[[The Days and Nights of Molly Dodd]]'' from [[NBC]], [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]] went through an \"emergent period\" in which it began to develop original television dramas.<ref name=\"Book22\"/> ''Veronica Clare'' was created by [[Jeffrey Bloom]],<ref name=\"SourceCreator\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RxHbPxbBM1AC&pg=PP160&lpg=PP160&dq=%22Veronica+Clare%22+%22Jeffrey+Bloom%22&source=bl&ots=AWS0Fi34CZ&sig=mptPLiMBIo6sNH6BggXiQLCWhZ8&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjyg_m87bXYAhXIQCYKHeSXAMw4ChDoAQgzMAI#v=onepage&q=%22Veronica%20Clare%22%20%22Jeffrey%20Bloom%22&f=false|title=Veronica Clare|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=July 29, 1991|accessdate=December 31, 2017}}</ref> and produced by Hearst Entertainment, Inc.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://catalog.loc.gov/vwebv/holdingsInfo?searchId=23544&recCount=25&recPointer=0&bibId=11672923|title=Veronica Clare. Affairs with death|date=1992|publisher=[[Library of Congress]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171023043734/https://catalog.loc.gov/vwebv/holdingsInfo?searchId=23544&recCount=25&recPointer=0&bibId=11672923|archivedate=October 23, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> It was one of three scripted programs ordered by Lifetime in 1991; the other two were ''[[The Hidden Room (TV series)|The Hidden Room]]'' and ''[[Confessions of Crime]]''.<ref name=\"Source2\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1991-07-23/features/1991204100_1_veronica-clare-laura-robinson-hidden-room|title='Veronica Clare' stands out among new Lifetime series|last=Zurawik|first=David|date=July 23, 1991|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171022200911/http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1991-07-23/features/1991204100_1_veronica-clare-laura-robinson-hidden-room|archivedate=October 22, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Each of the shows feature elements of [[Mystery fiction|mystery]] or [[suspense]].<ref name=\"Book1\">[[Veronica Clare#NewmanWitsell2016|Newman & Witsell (2016)]]: p. 10</ref>\n\nWriting for the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', [[Howard Rosenberg]] described the programs' development as Lifetime's \"most ambitious effort to date\".<ref name=\"Source6\" /> After picking up ''Veronica Clare'' for 13 episodes,<ref name=\"SourceReRuns\" /> Lifetime marketed the show toward women.<ref name=\"Source1\" /><ref name=\"Source2\" /> This followed the network's tradition of acquiring shows depicting female characters in traditionally male occupations; other examples include a female police officer in [[Lady Blue (TV series)|''Lady Blue'']], a female physician in ''[[Kay O'Brien]]'', and a female private detective in [[Partners in Crime (U.S. TV series)|''Partners in Crime'']].<ref name=\"Book10\">[[#DinesHumez2003|Dines & Humez (2003)]]: p. 620</ref>\n\nEven though the series is set in a contemporary period in Los Angeles,<ref name=\"Source4\" /><ref name=\"Book112\"/> a writer for ''[[The Item]]'' felt that it had a \"[[Historical period drama|period]] feel\" reminiscent of the 1940s and the 1980s.<ref name=\"Source4\" /> Shay Austin contributed to the series as its [[production designer]].<ref name=\"SourceCreator\" /> Each episode features camera techniques similar to those used in [[film noir]], and has a score composed by American jazz musician [[Gil Mell\u00e9]].<ref name=\"Source4\" />\n\n==Episodes==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%; background:#fff;\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#39f;\"| No.\n! style=\"background:#39f;\"| Title\n! style=\"background:#39f;\"| Directed by\n! style=\"background:#39f;\"| Written by\n! style=\"background:#39f;\"| Original air date\n{{Episode list\n |Title=Veronica's Aunt\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1991|7|23}}\n |EpisodeNumber=1\n |DirectedBy= [[Jeffrey Bloom]]\n |WrittenBy= Jeffrey Bloom\n |ShortSummary= Veronica is hired to help her aunt who has been threatened by her recently deceased husband's mob employers.\n |LineColor=3399ff\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |Title=Reed\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1991|7|30}}\n |EpisodeNumber=2\n |DirectedBy= Mark Cullingham\n |WrittenBy= Jeffrey Bloom\n |ShortSummary= Veronica tries to solve a mystery involving one of Duke's close friends.\n |LineColor=3399ff\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |Title=Anonymous\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1991|8|6}}\n |EpisodeNumber=3\n |DirectedBy= [[Rafal Zielinski]]\n |WrittenBy= Jeffrey Bloom\n |ShortSummary= When an amnesiac Romanian woman is found severely beaten, Veronica tries to help her remember her past to locate the attacker.\n |LineColor=3399ff\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |Title=The Boxing Story\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1991|8|13}}\n |EpisodeNumber=4\n |DirectedBy= [[Leon Ichaso]]\n |WrittenBy= Jeffrey Bloom and Frank Megna\n |ShortSummary= Veronica is approached by a female boxing manager to determine why her most popular boxer decided to abandon his career.\n |LineColor=3399ff\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |Title=Phoebe\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1991|8|20}}\n |EpisodeNumber=5\n |DirectedBy= [[Frederick King Keller|Fred Keller]]\n |WrittenBy= Jeffrey Bloom\n |ShortSummary= A woman hires Veronica to find her missing husband.\n |LineColor=3399ff\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |Title=Slow Violence\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1991|8|27}}\n |EpisodeNumber=6\n |DirectedBy= Deborah Dalton\n |WrittenBy= Nancy Bond\n |ShortSummary= A singer at the club pushes Veronica to babysit her child, and then suddenly disappears.\n |LineColor=3399ff\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |Title=Mr. Duvall\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1991|9|3}}\n |EpisodeNumber=7\n |DirectedBy= Fred Keller\n |WrittenBy= [[Jane Atkins]]\n |ShortSummary=Veronica is tasked to locate a wealthy man's missing wife. \n |LineColor=3399ff\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |Title=Love, Amanda\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1991|9|10}}\n |EpisodeNumber=8\n |DirectedBy= [[Amy Goldstein]]\n |WrittenBy= Nina Shengold\n |ShortSummary= Veronica tries to discover what is behind a young girl's murder by piecing together clues from her diary.\n |LineColor=3399ff\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |Title=Pilot\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1991|9|17}}\n |EpisodeNumber=9\n |DirectedBy= [[Donna Deitch]]\n |WrittenBy= Jeffrey Bloom\n |ShortSummary= Veronica is assigned to find a man's brooch, which is believed to have been stolen by his son.\n |LineColor=3399ff\n}}\n|}\n\n==Broadcast history==\n''Veronica Clare'' was broadcast initially on Tuesday nights at 10:00&nbsp;pm&nbsp;[[Eastern Time Zone|EST]],<ref name=\"Source1\" /> and aired directly after ''The Hidden Room'' and ''Confessions of a Crime''.<ref name=\"Source2\" /> [[Rerun]]s aired on Saturdays at 11:00&nbsp;pm&nbsp;EST.<ref name=\"SourceReRuns\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.courant.com/1991-07-19/features/0000213980_1_pat-fili-production-for-lifetime-television-victims|title=`Confessions Of Crime' Opens Lineup|last=Endrst|first=James|work=[[Hartford Courant]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171023050500/http://articles.courant.com/1991-07-19/features/0000213980_1_pat-fili-production-for-lifetime-television-victims|archivedate=October 23, 2017}}</ref> Despite delivering \"pretty respectable\" ratings, the show was placed on hiatus on September 24, 1991,<ref name=\"Source1\" /> after nine episodes had aired.<ref name=\"Source1\" /><ref name=\"Book8\">[[#Mizejewski2004|Mizejewski (2004)]]: p. 208</ref> ''Veronica Clare'', along with ''The Hidden Room'' and ''Confessions of a Crime'', had lower ratings than original films produced by the network.<ref name=\"Book7\">[[#Lotz2010|Lotz (2010)]]: p. 188</ref>\n\nNetwork spokesperson Alex Wagner attributed the decision to pull the series from air to issues with its production; he explained: \"We`re shutting down to address creative concerns, with the idea of rewriting.\" A writer from the ''Sun-Sentinel'' found this surprising given that television shows aimed at a [[niche market]] were often not required to deliver immediate high ratings in comparison to [[network television]].<ref name=\"Source1\" /> Lifetime canceled the series during its hiatus.<ref name=\"Book1\" /> Media studies scholar Eithne Johnson claimed that the network reached this decision due to its \"ambivalence about its 'feminine identity' during prime time\".<ref name=\"Book1\" /> The series has never been made available on DVD or Blu-ray, nor released on an online-streaming service.<ref name=\"SourceHomeRelease\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/shows/Veronica-Clare/4489 |title=Veronica Clare (1991) |publisher=[[TVShowsOnDVD.com]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130304183308/http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/shows/Veronica-Clare/4489 |archivedate=March 4, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1991 and 1992, the nine episodes were converted into four [[television movie]]s and aired on television. The titles of the films were ''Affairs with Death'', ''Deadly Minds'', ''Naked Hearts'', and ''Slow Violence''; they can be requested through the [[Library of Congress]] as [[Video Reel|video reel]]s.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":01\">{{cite web|url=https://catalog.loc.gov/vwebv/holdingsInfo?searchId=23818&recCount=25&recPointer=1&bibId=11635943|title=Veronica Clare. Deadly minds|date=1992|publisher=[[Library of Congress]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171023044515/https://catalog.loc.gov/vwebv/holdingsInfo?searchId=23818&recCount=25&recPointer=1&bibId=11635943|archivedate=October 23, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":012\">{{cite web|url=https://catalog.loc.gov/vwebv/holdingsInfo?searchId=23823&recCount=25&recPointer=2&bibId=11635933|title=Veronica Clare. Veronica Clare|date=1991|publisher=[[Library of Congress]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171023044515/https://catalog.loc.gov/vwebv/holdingsInfo?searchId=23823&recCount=25&recPointer=2&bibId=11635933|archivedate=October 23, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":0123\">{{cite web|url=https://catalog.loc.gov/vwebv/holdingsInfo?searchId=23835&recCount=25&recPointer=3&bibId=11635914|title=Veronica Clare. Slow violence|date=1991|publisher=[[Library of Congress]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171023044515/https://catalog.loc.gov/vwebv/holdingsInfo?searchId=23835&recCount=25&recPointer=3&bibId=11635914|archivedate=October 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Critical reception===\n''Veronica Clare'' has received mixed critical feedback. [[David Zurawik]] of ''[[The Baltimore Sun]]'' praised it as the network's only successful scripted program. Reviewing the first episode, he described the series as having a \"contemporary sensibility with plenty of retro-classic-P.I. atmosphere\".<ref name=\"Source2\" /> ''[[The Washington Post]]'''s Patricia Brennan called the show a stylish one-hour mystery series.<ref name=\"Source3\" /> Ginny Holbert of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' praised the show's style and its actors' performances.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4064749.html|title=Lifetime goes crime-time // Cable programs explore violence, lust and romance|last=Holbert|first=Ginny|date=July 23, 1991|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171023043734/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4064749.html|archivedate=October 23, 2017}} {{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nOther [[Television criticism|critics]] were more negative. Giving the series a C-, David Hiltbrand of [[People (magazine)|''People'']] was critical of the storylines' believability, describing the show's style as \"murky and contrived\". He also criticized Robinson's performance for its \"vacuity\".<ref name=\"Source5\">{{cite web|url=http://people.com/archive/picks-and-pans-review-veronica-clare-vol-36-no-4/|title=Picks and Pans Review: Veronica Clare|last=Hiltbrand|first=David|date=August 5, 1991|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171022200911/http://people.com/archive/picks-and-pans-review-veronica-clare-vol-36-no-4/|archivedate=October 22, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Howard Rosenberg initially praised the pilot as an indication of a \"stylishly mounted, [[Raymond Chandler|Chandleresque]]-style series\", but panned subsequent episodes. He felt that the storylines bordered on a [[parody]] in the style of the 1991 film ''[[The Naked Gun 2\u00bd: The Smell of Fear]]'', and did not match the \"subtlety and a charming playfulness\" of the series' premiere.<ref name=\"Source6\" /> The ''[[Orlando Sentinel]]'''s Nancy Pete criticized ''Veronica Clare'' as \"well-intentioned but ludicrous\",<ref name=\"Source11111\" /> and a reviewer from [[Variety (magazine)|''Variety'']] responded negatively to the pilot's script, writing that \"atmosphere goes only so far\".<ref name=\"SourceCreator\" />\n\n===Critical analysis===\n[[File:Lauren Bacall 1945 (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|right|Clare was compared to [[Lauren Bacall]] (''pictured in 1945'') by critics.<ref name=\"Source4\" /><ref name=\"Books122\"/><ref name=\"SourceCreator\" />|alt=A black-and-white image of a woman with long hair staring towards the camera.]]\n\nFollowing its premiere, ''Veronica Clare'' was described as an example of the rise of lead female characters in mysteries and crime dramas in film and television.<ref name=\"Source6\" /><ref name=\"Source2\" /><ref name=\"Source11111\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1991-08-11/entertainment/9108090275_1_agatha-christie-millhone-ngaio-marsh|title=This Summer, Women Sleuths Are On The Case|date=August 11, 1991|last=Pate|first=Nancy|work=[[Orlando Sentinel]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171023115812/http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1991-08-11/entertainment/9108090275_1_agatha-christie-millhone-ngaio-marsh|archivedate=October 23, 2017}}</ref> Zurawik felt the show's success and impact \"could be a culturally important one\", identifying its focus on a female private investigator as fitting with the \"boom of women writing and starring in mystery fiction\".<ref name=\"Source2\" /> Expressing a similar sentiment, Hiltbrand found the series to be a continuation of \"the season for female private eyes\".<ref name=\"Source5\" /> Rosenberg felt that \"beyond male biases among network programmers\", there was no reason for female detectives to be treated as a \"TV curiosity\".<ref name=\"Source6\" />\n\nClare has been compared to other fictional female detectives, and Robinson to noted actresses. Hiltbrand likened Clare to [[Kathleen Turner]]'s leading role in the 1991 film [[V.I. Warshawski (film)|''V.I. Warshawski'']], and felt that Robinson was attempting a \"mysterious [[Sam Spade|Samantha Spade]] style\".<ref name=\"Source5\" /> A writer for ''The Item'' called the character a \"cross between the [[Lauren Bacall]] of the '40s and the Kathleen Turner of the '80's\", noting intelligence and sexuality as her primary characteristics.<ref name=\"Source4\" /> Television historians [[Tim Brooks (television historian)|Tim Brooks]] and Earle F. Marsh pointed to Clare's \"long flowing hair and reserved demeanor\" as her notable character traits, which recalled Bacall and [[the Andrews Sisters]].<ref name=\"Books122\"/> In a negative review of the character, Rosenberg wrote that Clare was \"a poached egg compared to the [[Hardboiled|hard-boiled]] gumshoe of [[Sara Paretsky]]'s detective stories\" featuring V. I. Warshawski.<ref name=\"Source6\" />\n\nCritics have analyzed Clare's identity as a female detective. Political theorist [[Philip Green (author)|Philip Green]] argued the show portrayed Clare as beautiful to accentuate her \"masculine toughness\" and avoid presenting her as a \"fetishized male in disguise\".<ref name=\"Book4\" /><ref name=\"Book5\">[[#Green1998|Green (1998)]]: p. 241</ref> Green wrote that Clare's appearance was kept separate from \"pure feminized sexuality\" and her skills differed from \"hypermasculine aggression\". He interpreted Clare's role as the narrator as allowing her to never become the object of [[voyeurism]] or the [[male gaze]].<ref name=\"Book4\" /> [[Gender and women's studies]] scholar Susan White noted that ''Veronica Clare''<nowiki/>'s fashion and scenic design played a major role in its identity as a female-driven detective show. White argued that the \"postmodern surplus of feminine details works in tension with the codes of the hardboiled narrative and style\".<ref name=\"Book9\">[[#Mizejewski2004|Mizejewski (2004)]]: p. 199</ref>\n\n== References ==\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Book sources===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last1 = Brooks |first1 = Tim |last2 = Marsh |first2 = Earle F. |title =The Complete Directory to Prime Time Network and Cable TV Shows, 1946-Present|year = 2009 |publisher =Random House Publishing Group |location = New York |isbn = 978-0-345-49773-4 |ref =brooksmarsh2009 }}\n* {{cite book |last1 = Dines |first1 = Gail |last2 = Humez |first2 = Jean M. |title = Gender, Race, and Class in Media: A Text-Reader |year = 2003 |publisher = Sage |location = Thousand Oaks |isbn = 0-7619-2260-1 |ref = DinesHumez2003 |url-access = registration |url = https://archive.org/details/genderraceclassi0000unse }}\n* {{cite book |last1 = Green |first1 = Phillip|title =Cracks in the Pedestal: Ideology and Gender in Hollywood|year = 1998 |publisher =University of Massachusetts Press |location = Amherst |isbn = 1-55849-119-8 |ref =Green1998 }}\n* {{cite book |last1 = Lotz |first1 = Amanda D.|title =Redesigning Women: Television after the Network Era|year = 2010 |publisher =University of Illinois Press|location = Chicago |isbn = 978-0-252-03067-3 |ref =Lotz2010 }}\n* {{cite book |last1 = Meehan|first1 = Eileen R. |last2 = Byars |first2 = Jackie|chapter=Telefeminism: How Lifetime got It's Groove, 1984-1997|pages= 92\u2013104 |editor-last=Allen|editor-first1=Robert Clyde|editor-last2=Hill|editor-first2=Annette|title =The Television Studies Reader|year = 2004 |publisher =Psychology Press |location = New York|isbn = 0-415-28323-X |ref =MeehanByarsl2004 }}\n* {{cite book |last1 = Mizejewski|first1 = Linda|title =Hardboiled and High Heeled: The Woman Detective in Popular Culture|year = 2004 |publisher =Routledge|location = New York |isbn = 0-415-96970-0 |ref =Mizejewski2004 }}\n* {{cite book |last1 = Newman |first1 = Emily L. |last2 = Witsell |first2 = Emily|chapter=Introduction|pages= 1\u201320 |title =The Lifetime Network: Essays on \"Television for Women\" in the 21st Century|year = 2016 |publisher =McFarland |location = Jefferson |isbn = 978-0-7864-9830-7 |ref =NewmanWitsell2016 }}\n* {{cite book |last = Terrace |first = Vincent|title = Encyclopedia of Television Shows, 1925 through 2010 |year = 2008 |publisher = McFarland |location = Jefferson |isbn =978-0-7864-6477-7|ref = Terrace2008}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|101232}}\n*{{Tv.com show|veronica-clare}}\n\n{{Lifetime Shows}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1991 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1991 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:1990s American crime drama television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Lifetime (TV network) original programming]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Los Angeles]]\n", "name_user": "Kailash29792", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eProduction:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Veronica_Clare"}
{"title_page": "Mingma Gyabu Sherpa", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n|image = [[File:Mingma-gyabu.jpg|thumb]]\n|name = Mingma Gyabu Sherpa \n|other_names = Mingma David Sherpa \n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1989|05|16}}\n|birth_place = [[Taplejung, Nepal]]\n|nationality = [[Nepal]]ese\n|known_for = [[Mountaineering]]\n}}\n\n'''Mingma Gyabu Sherpa''' aka Mingma David (b. 16 May 1989)is a Nepalese mountaineer and renowned rescue crew. Mingma Gyabu is the youngest person to climb the all 14 main 8000m peaks.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sherpa |first1=Mingma G. |title=14 Peak climber |url=https://english.khabarhub.com/2019/06/11244/ |website=https://english.khabarhub.com/ |publisher=Khabarhub}}</ref> He also holds the Guinness World Record for the title of \"Fastest time to climb Everest and K2\", he climbed first and second highest peak in the world with in 61 day.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sherpa |first1=Mingma Gyabu |title=Fastest Everest and K2 |url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/mingma-gyabu-sets-world-record-for-fastest-ascents-of-everest-k2/ |website=https://thehimalayantimes.com/ |publisher=The Himalayan Times |accessdate=18/10/2019}}</ref>\n\n\n\n'''Name of the Mountains climbed by Mingma Gyabu:'''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! S.No.!! Peak (Height) !! Year (Season)\n|-\n|1.||Everest (8848).    || 2010 (Spring)\n|-\n|2.||K2 (8611 m).    || 2012 (Summer), 2018 (Summer)\n|-\n|3.||Kangchenjunga (8586 m).    ||2019 (Spring)\n|-\n|4.||Lhotse (8516 m).    ||2018 (Spring)\n|-\n|5.||Makalu (8485 m).    ||2014 (Spring)\n|-\n|6.||Cho Oyu (8201 m).    ||2011 (Autumn)\n|-\n|7.||Dhaulagiri (8167 m).    ||2019 (Spring)\n|-\n|8.||Manaslu (8163 m).    ||2012 (Autumn), 2019 (Autumn)\n|-\n|9.||Nanga Parbat (8125 m).    ||2019 (Summer)\n|-\n|10.||Annapurna I (8091 m).    ||2019 (Spring)\n|-\n|11.||Gasherbrum I (8068 m).    ||2019 (Summer)\n|-\n|12.||Broad Peak (8047 m).    ||2019 (Summer)\n|-\n|13.||Gasherbrum II (8035 m).    ||2019 (Summer)\n|-\n|14.||Shisha Pangma (8027 m).    ||2019 (Autumn)\n|}\n\n\n==References==\n<ref>https://english.khabarhub.com/2019/28/64746/<ref>\n<ref>https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/mingma-gyabu-sets-world-record-for-fastest-ascents-of-everest-k2/<ref>\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n|image = [[File:Mingma-gyabu.jpg|thumb]]\n|name = Mingma Gyabu Sherpa \n|other_names = Mingma David Sherpa \n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1989|05|16}}\n|birth_place = [[Taplejung, Nepal]]\n|nationality = [[Nepal]]ese\n|known_for = [[Mountaineering]]\n}}\n\n'''Mingma Gyabu Sherpa''' aka Mingma David (b. 16 May 1989)is a Nepalese mountaineer and renowned rescue crew. Mingma Gyabu is the youngest person to climb the all 14 main 8000m peaks.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sherpa |first1=Mingma G. |title=14 Peak climber |url=https://english.khabarhub.com/2019/06/11244/ |website=https://english.khabarhub.com/ |publisher=Khabarhub}}</ref> He also holds the Guinness World Record for the title of \"Fastest time to climb Everest and K2\", he climbed first and second highest peak in the world with in 61 day. <ref>https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/mingma-gyabu-sets-world-record-for-fastest-ascents-of-everest-k2/<ref>.\n\n\n\n'''Name of the Mountains climbed by Mingma Gyabu:'''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! S.No.!! Peak (Height) !! Year (Season)\n|-\n|1.||Everest (8848).    || 2010 (Spring)\n|-\n|2.||K2 (8611 m).    || 2012 (Summer), 2018 (Summer)\n|-\n|3.||Kangchenjunga (8586 m).    ||2019 (Spring)\n|-\n|4.||Lhotse (8516 m).    ||2018 (Spring)\n|-\n|5.||Makalu (8485 m).    ||2014 (Spring)\n|-\n|6.||Cho Oyu (8201 m).    ||2011 (Autumn)\n|-\n|7.||Dhaulagiri (8167 m).    ||2019 (Spring)\n|-\n|8.||Manaslu (8163 m).    ||2012 (Autumn), 2019 (Autumn)\n|-\n|9.||Nanga Parbat (8125 m).    ||2019 (Summer)\n|-\n|10.||Annapurna I (8091 m).    ||2019 (Spring)\n|-\n|11.||Gasherbrum I (8068 m).    ||2019 (Summer)\n|-\n|12.||Broad Peak (8047 m).    ||2019 (Summer)\n|-\n|13.||Gasherbrum II (8035 m).    ||2019 (Summer)\n|-\n|14.||Shisha Pangma (8027 