ist filmmakers]]\n[[Category:Science fiction fans]]\n", "name_user": "Errantius", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFuture projects", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Terry_Gilliam"}
{"title_page": "Masters of Sex", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n | show_name = Masters of Sex\n | image = Masters of Sex title.png\n | image_size = 250px\n | image_alt =\n | genre = {{Plainlist|\n* [[historical drama|Period drama]]\n}}\n | developer = [[Michelle Ashford]]\n | caption = \n | based_on = {{Based on|''[[Masters of Sex (book)|Masters of Sex]]''|[[Thomas Maier]]}}\n | starring = {{Plainlist |\n* [[Michael Sheen]]\n* [[Lizzy Caplan]]\n* [[Caitlin FitzGerald]]\n* [[Teddy Sears]]\n* [[Nicholas D'Agosto]]\n* [[Annaleigh Ashford]]\n}}\n | theme_music_composer = \n | opentheme = \n | endtheme = \n | composer = [[Michael Penn]]\n | country = United States\n | language = English\n | num_seasons = 4\n | num_episodes = 46\n | list_episodes = List of Masters of Sex episodes\n | executive_producer = {{Plainlist |\n* Michelle Ashford\n* Sarah Timberman\n* Carl Beverly\n* [[Amy Lippman]]\n* Judith Verno\n}}\n | producer = Michael Sheen<br />Lizzy Caplan <br />Thomas Maier\n | location = {{Plainlist|\n* [[New York City]]\n* [[Los Angeles]]\n}}\n | cinematography = [[Ben Davis (cinematographer)|Ben Davis]]\n | camera = \n | runtime = 55\u201360 minutes\n | company = {{Plainlist|\n* Round Two Productions\n* Timberman/Beverly Productions\n* [[Sony Pictures Television]]\n* [[Showtime Networks]]\n}}\n | distributor = [[CBS Television Distribution]]\n | channel = [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]]\n | picture_format = \n | audio_format = \n | first_aired = {{Start date|2013|9|29}}\n | last_aired = {{End date|2016|11|13}}\n | preceded_by = \n | followed_by = \n | related = \n | website = \n | website_title = Official website\n | production_website = \n}}\n\n'''''Masters of Sex''''' is an American [[period drama]] television series that premiered on September 29, 2013, on [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]].<ref name=\"premiere\">{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/01/12/showtime-announces-premiere-dates-for-nurse-jackie-dexter-returning-early-ray-donovan-homeland-masters-of-sex-more/165132/|title=Showtime Announces Premiere Dates for 'Nurse Jackie,' 'Dexter' (Returning Early) 'Ray Donovan,' 'Homeland,' 'Masters of Sex' & More|last=Seidman|first=Robert|work=TV by the Numbers|date=January 12, 2013|accessdate=January 12, 2013}}</ref> It was developed by [[Michelle Ashford]] and loosely based on [[Thomas Maier]]'s biography ''[[Masters of Sex (book)|Masters of Sex]]''.<ref name=\"lat2013\"/> Set in the 1950s through the late 1960s, the series tells the story of [[Masters and Johnson]] ([[William Masters|Dr. William Masters]] and [[Virginia E. Johnson|Virginia Johnson]]) who are portrayed by [[Michael Sheen]] and [[Lizzy Caplan]]. The series has received critical acclaim. It was nominated for a [[Golden Globe Award]] for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Television Series \u2013 Drama|Best Drama Series]] in 2013. The series was canceled by Showtime on November 30, 2016, after four seasons.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2016/11/30/masters-of-sex-cancelled-showtime-season-5/ |title=Masters of Sex Is Done at Showtime |publisher=TVLine |first=Vlada |last=Gelman |date=November 30, 2016 |accessdate=November 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Premise==\nThe series explores the research and the relationship between [[William Masters]] ([[Michael Sheen]]) and [[Virginia E. Johnson|Virginia Johnson]] ([[Lizzy Caplan]]), two pioneering researchers of human sexuality at [[Washington University in St. Louis|Washington University]] in [[St. Louis, Missouri]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Maier |first=Thomas |title= Masters Of Sex: The Life and Times of William Masters and Virginia Johnson, The Couple Who Taught America How To Love|year=2009 |publisher= Basic Books |location=New York|isbn=9780465003075|pages=400|asin=B001Y35IZO}}</ref> The series begins in October 1956 and ends in August 1969 with the fourth season.\n\nAs noted by the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' television critic, the series \"hangs on bones of fact\"; \"it's more useful for the viewer to think of it as all made up. Because, mostly, it is, and because to the extent it tells the story of two real people, it also adorns the telling with dramatic practicalities, invented characters and narrative detours. Indeed, it's down these side streets, casting a brief light on a passing character (patients, prostitutes, a provost's wife), that the show finds many of its best moments.\"<ref name=\"lat2013\"/>\n\nOther than principal characters, which are partly fictionalized, adults are significantly fictionalized; however, children are entirely fictionalized. In real life, Masters and Johnson each have two children, however, in the series they have three children each. Episodes featuring the children include a disclaimer where it states that their storylines are \"entirely fictitious\". Series creator Michelle Ashford explained, \"We are telling a non-fiction story and one where there are people who are still alive out there, and those people need to be protected. We were advised to add [the baby] to protect the people that are still alive. It wasn't a storytelling prerogative. It had to do with protecting living people.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/masters-of-sex-fake-baby/ |title=The Kids Aren't Alright: Behind Masters of Sex's Controversial Children's Stories |website=TV Guide |first=Hanh |last=Nguyen |date=August 11, 2015 |accessdate=January 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Cast and characters==\n[[File:Cast of Masters of Sex at PaleyFest 2014.jpg|thumb|The cast and crew at [[PaleyFest]] 2014. From left: [[Michelle Ashford]], [[Michael Sheen]], [[Lizzy Caplan]], Sarah Timberman (executive producer), [[Caitlin FitzGerald]], [[Teddy Sears]] and [[Annaleigh Ashford]]]]\n\n===Main cast===\n* [[Michael Sheen]] as [[William Masters|Dr. William Masters]]\n* [[Lizzy Caplan]] as [[Virginia E. Johnson|Virginia Johnson]]\n* [[Caitlin FitzGerald]] as Libby Masters\n* [[Teddy Sears]] as Dr. Austin Langham (seasons 1\u20132, recurring seasons 3\u20134)\n* [[Nicholas D'Agosto]] as Dr. Ethan Haas (season 1, guest season 2)\n* [[Annaleigh Ashford]] as Betty Dimello (seasons 2\u20134, recurring season 1)\n\n===Recurring cast===\n* [[Beau Bridges]] as Barton Scully, medical school provost and longtime friend of William Masters\n* [[Allison Janney]] as Margaret Scully, Barton's wife (seasons 1\u20133)\n* [[Rose McIver]] as Vivian Scully, Barton and Margaret's daughter<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/showtimes-masters-sex-adds-lovely-419826 |title=Showtime's 'Masters of Sex' Adds 'Lovely Bones' Actress |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=February 8, 2013 |accessdate=February 11, 2013 |first=Lesley |last=Goldberg}}</ref> (seasons 1\u20132)\n* [[Hel\u00e9ne Yorke]] as Jane Martin, a hospital secretary and participant in the sex study\n* Kevin Christy as Lester Linden, the archivist of Masters and Johnson's work\n* [[Julianne Nicholson]] as Dr. Lillian DePaul, a doctor working in the Obstetrics Department of Washington University Hospital (seasons 1\u20132)\n* [[Ann Dowd]] as Estabrooks 'Essie' Masters, William's mother<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/02/linda-lavin-to-co-star-in-nbcs-sean-hayes-pilot-ann-dowd-recurs-on-masters-of-sex/ |title=Linda Lavin To Co-Star In NBC\u2019s Sean Hayes Pilot, Ann Dowd Recurs On \u2018Masters Of Sex\u2019 |publisher=Deadline.com |first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |date=February 4, 2013 |accessdate=September 28, 2013}}</ref> (seasons 1\u20132)\n* [[Mather Zickel]] as George Johnson, Virginia's ex-husband and father of her children\n* [[Cole Sand]] (seasons 1\u20132) and [[Noah Robbins]] (season 3) as Henry Johnson, Virginia's son\n* Kayla Madison (seasons 1\u20132) and [[Isabelle Fuhrman]] (seasons 3\u20134) as Tessa Johnson, Virginia's daughter\n* [[Greg Grunberg]] as Gene Moretti, Betty's husband (seasons 1\u20132)\n* [[Finn Wittrock]] as Dale, a male [[Male prostitution|prostitute]] whom Barton Scully patronizes (season 1)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thebacklot.com/masters-of-sex-gay-story/11/2013/ |title=The Compelling Gay Story in \"Masters Of Sex\" |publisher=The Backlot |date=November 19, 2013 |accessdate=November 19, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Betsy Brandt]] as Barbara Sanderson, Masters' new secretary, and later a patient of his clinic (season 2)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/breaking-bads-betsy-brandt-joins-689335 |title=Breaking Bad's' Betsy Brandt Joins Showtime's 'Masters of Sex' |work=The Hollywood Reporter |first=Lesley |last=Goldberg |date=March 18, 2014 |accessdate=May 28, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Christian Borle]] as Francis 'Frank' Masters, Jr., the younger brother of William Masters (season 2)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.ca/ustv/news/a573109/masters-of-sex-casts-smash-actor-christian-borle.html#~oFzDp7PqIGbiu8 |title=Masters of Sex casts Smash actor Christian Borle |publisher=Digital Spy |first=Tom |last=Eames |date=May 23, 2014 |accessdate=May 28, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Keke Palmer]] as Coral, the Masters' African-American nanny (season 2)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/keke-palmer-joins-showtimes-masters-of-sex-1201130050/# |title=Keke Palmer Joins Showtime\u2019s \u2018Masters of Sex' |work=Variety |first=Francesca |last=Bacardi |date=March 12, 2014 |accessdate=May 28, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Jocko Sims]] as Robert Franklin, Coral's brother and a civil rights activist (season 2)\n* [[Sarah Silverman]] as Helen, Betty's lover (seasons 2\u20134)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/sarah-silverman-masters-of-sex-1201165873/ |title=Sarah Silverman Joins \u2018Masters of Sex\u2019 Cast |work=Variety |first=Whitney |last=Friedlander |date=April 28, 2014 |accessdate=May 28, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Courtney B. Vance]] as Dr. Charles Hendricks, the head of an African-American St. Louis hospital who seeks integration (season 2)<ref name=\"Auberjonois and Vance\">{{cite web |url=http://www.deadline.com/2014/05/courtney-b-vance-rene-auberjonois-set-for-season-2-of-masters-of-sex/ |title=Courtney B. Vance & Rene Auberjonois Set For Season 2 Of \u2018Masters Of Sex\u2019 |publisher=Deadline.com |first=Erik |last=Pedersen |date=May 19, 2014 |accessdate=May 28, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Danny Huston]] as Dr. Douglas Greathouse, the head of a hospital's Obstetrics Department (season 2)\n* [[Artemis Pebdani]] as Flo Packer, the owner of a diet pill company (season 2)\n* [[Adam Arkin]] as Shep Tally, a [[Public relations|PR]] expert hired by Masters and Johnson to help them present their work (season 2)\n* [[Josh Charles]] as Dan Logan (season 3)\n* [[Emily Kinney]] as Nora Everett, a woman fascinated with Bill and Virginia's work who later becomes part of Bill's surrogacy program (season 3)\n* [[Ben Koldyke]] as Paul Edley (season 3)\n* Colin Woodell as Ronald Sturgis (season 3)\n* [[Jaeden Lieberher]] as Johnny Masters, Bill and Libby's son (seasons 3\u20134)\n* [[Jeremy Strong (actor)|Jeremy Strong]] as Dr. Art Dreesen, a psychologist who is brought in to help lessen Bill and Virginia's workload (season 4)\n* [[Betty Gilpin]] as Dr. Nancy Leveau, Art's wife and a doctor who is brought in to help lessen Bill and Virginia's workload (season 4)\n* [[Niecy Nash]] as Louise Bell, the head of Alcoholics Anonymous (season 4)\n* [[Kelli O'Hara]] as Dody Oliver, Bill's first love who did not answer his marriage proposal (season 4)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Development and production==\nShowtime ordered the pilot for ''Masters of Sex'' in August 2011,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.deadline.com/2011/08/showtime-picks-up-pilots-from-andrew-gurland-michelle-ashford-ann-biderman/ |title=Showtime Picks Up Pilots From Andrew Gurland, Michelle Ashford & Ann Biderman |publisher=Deadline.com |first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |date=August 21, 2011 |accessdate=September 30, 2013}}</ref> and greenlit it for series in June 2012, with the first season consisting of twelve episodes.<ref name=\"variety\">{{cite news |url=https://variety.com/2012/tv/news/showtime-gives-series-orders-to-donovan-sex-1118055335/ |title=Showtime gives series orders to 'Donovan,' 'Sex' |last=Littleton |first=Cynthia |date=June 11, 2012 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=July 15, 2012}}</ref>\n\nWriter/producer [[Michelle Ashford]] serves as [[showrunner]] for ''Masters of Sex''. She assembled a majority-female writing staff, although she says this was unintentional.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nymag.com/thecut/2013/09/dirty-talk-with-the-woman-behind-masters-of-sex.html |title=Q&A: Dirty Talk With the Woman Behind ''Masters of Sex'' |work=New York Magazine |first=Allison P. |last=Davis |date=September 30, 2013 |accessdate=September 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAshford created the character of Barton Scully out of a combination of several men whom Masters knew. One of them was gay, but was not the man serving as provost during Masters' initial study.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thebacklot.com/masters-of-sex-creator-on-the-shows-gay-storyline/11/2013/ |title=\"Masters Of Sex\" Creator On The Show\u2019s \"Exciting\" Gay Storyline |publisher=The Backlot |first=Jim |last=Halterman |date=November 25, 2013 |accessdate=November 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\nProp master Jeffrey Johnson noted the difficulty of obtaining accurate information about [[sex toy|sexual devices]] from the time period. \"They were so taboo it was hard to find research drawings. People didn\u2019t even put them in writing.\" He obtained some vintage vibrators and [[dildo]]s for use in the series along with acquiring [[condom]]s manufactured in the era (which did not have the reservoir tips of modern condoms). He designed \"Ulysses\", a transparent dildo with attached camera first seen in the pilot episode, from scratch, along with a diaphragm sizing kit seen in later episodes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vulture.com/2013/09/masters-of-sex-prop-master-glass-dildos.html |title=Talking to ''Masters of Sex''{{'}}s Prop Master About Glass Dildos and Old Condoms |work=Vulture |first=Molly |last=Langmuir |date=September 30, 2013 |accessdate=September 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[Annaleigh Ashford]], who has a recurring role in the first season as Betty Dimello, was promoted to series regular in season two.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/12/annaleigh-ashford-regular-on-masters-of-sex-departs-kinky-boots/ |title=Annaleigh Ashford Upped To Regular On \u2018Masters Of Sex\u2019, Will Depart \u2018Kinky Boots\u2019 |publisher=Deadline.com |first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |date=December 3, 2013 |accessdate=December 8, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe [[opening credits]] sequence was created by design studio Elastic. The sequence, which includes suggestive, tongue-in-cheek sex metaphors and symbols, received a mixed response from critics; it placed on both best and worst lists for opening credit sequences. It was also nominated for the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Main Title Design]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://time.com/2980158/masters-of-sex-season-2-premier-opening-credits/ |title=Behind the Unusual Opening Credits to Masters of Sex |work=Time |first=Feeney |last=Nolan |date=July 14, 2014 |accessdate=February 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Series overview ==\n{{Main|List of Masters of Sex episodes}}\n{{:List of Masters of Sex episodes}}\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Critical response===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"float: right;text-align:center; width:%70;margin:10px\"\n|-\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" | Season\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" colspan=\"2\" | Critical response\n|-\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | [[Rotten Tomatoes]]\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | [[Metacritic]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#BDD6D3;\"|\n| 1\n| 90% (58 reviews)\n| 86 (32 reviews)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#B30027;\"|\n| 2\n| 98% (43 reviews)\n| 89 (17 reviews)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#0D3952;\"|\n| 3\n| 69% (32 reviews)\n| 72 (15 reviews)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#A7BA9A;\"|\n| 4\n| 80% (10 reviews)\n| 70 (5 reviews)\n|-\n|}\n\nThe first season of ''Masters of Sex'' received critical acclaim. Based on 58 reviews collected by [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the first season received a 90% approval rating from critics, with a rating average of 8.26 out of 10. The site's consensus states: \"Seductive and nuanced, ''Masters of Sex'' features smart performances, deft direction, and impeccable period decor.\"<ref>{{cite web |url =http://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/masters-of-sex/s01/ |title=Masters of Sex: Season 1 (2013) |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=October 27, 2013}}</ref> [[Metacritic]] gave the first season a score of 86 out of 100, based on 32 reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/masters-of-sex/season-1 |title=Masters of Sex \u2013 Season 1 Reviews |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=September 28, 2013}}</ref> The [[American Film Institute]] listed it as one of the top ten television series of 2013.<ref name=\"afi\">{{cite web | url=https://variety.com/2013/film/awards/afi-names-best-movies-and-tv-shows-of-2013-1200937298/ | title=AFI Names Best Movies and TV Shows of 2013 | work=Variety |date=December 9, 2013 |accessdate=December 9, 2013 | first=Tim |last=Gray}}</ref>\n\nMatt Roush of ''[[TV Guide]]'' wrote that \"There is no more fascinating, or entertaining, new series this fall season.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvguide.com/News/Weekend-Playlist-Masters-1071377.aspx |title=Weekend Playlist: ''Masters of Sex'' and ''Homeland'', ''Breaking Bad'' Finale on Jam-Packed Sunday |work=TV Guide |first=Matt |last=Roush |date=September 27, 2013 |accessdate=November 7, 2013}}</ref> Diane Werts of ''[[Newsday]]'' gave it an \"A\" grade, complimenting the series on its use of humor, stating \"its deft balance of epic scope and whimsical humanity\", as well as the strong performances of the actors and creator [[Michelle Ashford]]'s \"scene-setting scripts\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newsday.com/entertainment/tv/masters-of-sex-review-showtime-scores-1.6139803 |title='Masters of Sex' review: Showtime scores |work=Newsday |first=Diane |last=Werts |date=September 25, 2013 |accessdate=November 7, 2013}}</ref> [[David Wiegand]] of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' particularly praised the performances, calling them \"extraordinary\" and \"stunning\", and noting the series' A-list directors, among them [[Michael Apted]] and [[John Madden (director)|John Madden]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sfgate.com/tv/article/Masters-of-Sex-review-Satisfying-look-at-sex-4847308.php |title='Masters of Sex' review: Satisfying look at sex |work=San Francisco Chronicle |first=David |last=Wiegand |date=September 26, 2013 |accessdate=November 7, 2013}}</ref> Hank Stuever of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' wrote that after the first two episodes, \"the characters get better and more complex, the story builds, strange things start to happen and now I can't wait to see how its interweaving plots unfold.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/tv/showtimes-masters-of-sex-starts-off-slow-and-deliberate-and-then-finds-the-right-spot/2013/09/26/19a08e06-263d-11e3-b3e9-d97fb087acd6_story.html |title=Showtime\u2019s \u2018Masters of Sex\u2019 gets better as it goes along |work=The Washington Post |first=Hank |last=Stuever |date=September 26, 2013 |accessdate=November 7, 2013}}</ref> Alan Sepinwall of [[HitFix]] praised lead actors [[Michael Sheen]] and [[Lizzy Caplan]], calling them \"terrific\", and saying that \"''Masters of Sex'' is the best new show of the fall by a very long stretch. It's also a refreshing anomaly: a prestige cable drama that doesn't feel like a recombination of elements from 15 shows that came before it.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hitfix.com/whats-alan-watching/review-michael-sheen-lizzy-caplan-shine-in-showtimes-masters-of-sex |title=Review: Michael Sheen & Lizzy Caplan shine in Showtime's 'Masters of Sex' |publisher=HitFix |first=Alan |last=Sepinwall |date=September 26, 2013 |accessdate= November 7, 2013}}</ref>  According to Robert Lloyd, the ''Los Angeles Times'' television critic, the show is a \"handsome thing, another well-dressed romp through the American mid-century, when things (we imagine) were simpler and (so we like to think) less sophisticated, but also more exciting. And it's true that sexual naivet\u00e9 of that age can seem incredible in a day when pornography is just another thing on your platform of choice. But even in an age when ''Masters of Sex'' is a TV show, the subject remains stubbornly powerful, private and confounding. We have come far, and we are still cavemen.<ref name=\"lat2013\">{{cite web |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2013/sep/28/entertainment/la-et-st-masters-of-sex-review |title=Review: 'Masters of Sex' explores the science of sex |date=September 28, 2013 |first=Robert |last=Lloyd |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=December 1, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe second season also received critical acclaim equal to if not greater than the first season. It received a score of 89 out of 100 on Metacritic based on 17 reviews, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/masters-of-sex/season-2 |title=Masters of Sex \u2013 Season 2 Reviews |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=July 12, 2014}}</ref> On Rotten Tomatoes, it has a 98% approval rating among critics based on 43 reviews, with a rating average of 8.52 out of 10. The consensus reads: \"Boasting an expanded storyline and broader focus, ''Masters of Sex''{{'}}s second season improves on its already outstanding predecessor.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/masters-of-sex/s02/ |title=Masters of Sex: Season 2|publisher=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=September 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe third season received generally positive reviews from critics, although received more mixed reviews than the previous seasons. It has a Metacritic score of 72 out of 100 based on 15 reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/masters-of-sex/season-3 |title=Masters of Sex \u2013 Season 3 Reviews |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref> On Rotten Tomatoes, it has a 69% approval rating among critics based on 32 reviews, with a rating average of 7.61 out of 10. The consensus reads, \"With a six-year leap forward in the timeline, ''Masters of Sex'' takes an intriguing dramatic turn, but may leave a few viewers feeling frustrated.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/masters-of-sex/s03/|title=Masters of Sex: Season 3|publisher=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=July 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe fourth season received generally positive reviews from critics. It has a Metacritic score of 70 out of 100 based on 5 reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/masters-of-sex/season-4 |title=Masters of Sex \u2013 Season 4 Reviews |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=September 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n{{main|List of awards and nominations received by Masters of Sex}}\n{{Anchor|Awards|Accolades}}\nIn June 2013, the series was honored, along with five others, with the [[Critics' Choice Television Award for Most Exciting New Series]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.criticschoice.com/television-awards/the-btja-announces-icon-award-recipient-and-most-exciting-new-series-honorees/ |title=The BTJA Announces Icon Award Recipient and Most Exciting New Series Honorees |publisher=The Broadcast Television Journalists Association |date=June 10, 2013 |accessdate=June 29, 2013}}</ref> The series received two nominations for the 2014 [[Writers Guild of America Award]]s, for Best New Series and Best Episodic Drama for \"Pilot\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2013/12/05/writers-guild-award-nominations-2014-list-wga/ |title=''Breaking Bad'', ''Orange Is the New Black'', ''House of Cards'' Lead 2014 WGA Nominations |publisher=TVLine |first=Michael |last=Ausiello |date=December 5, 2013 |accessdate=December 5, 2013}}</ref>  For the [[71st Golden Globe Awards]], the series was nominated for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Television Series \u2013 Drama|Best Drama Series]], and [[Michael Sheen]] was nominated [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Television Series Drama|Best Drama Actor]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2013/12/12/golden-globe-nominations-2014-globes-awards-nominees/ |title=Golden Globes: ''House of Cards'', ''The Good Wife'', ''Candelabra'' and ''Breaking Bad'' Lead Noms; ''Parks & Rec'', ''Brooklyn'', Spader and Maslany Score Nods |publisher=TVLine |first=Matt Webb |last=Mitovich |date=December 12, 2013 |accessdate=December 12, 2013}}</ref> For the [[66th Primetime Emmy Awards]], [[Lizzy Caplan]] received a nomination for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Drama Series|Outstanding Lead Actress in a Drama Series]], [[Beau Bridges]] received a nomination for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Guest Actor in a Drama Series|Outstanding Guest Actor in a Drama Series]], and [[Allison Janney]] won for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Guest Actress in a Drama Series|Outstanding Guest Actress in a Drama Series]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/emmy-nominations-2014-list-emmys-nominees-1201260236/ |title=2014 Emmy Awards: \u2018Game of Thrones,\u2019 \u2018Fargo\u2019 Lead Nominations |work=Variety |first=Brian |last=Lowry |date=July 10, 2014 |accessdate=July 10, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2014/08/16/emmys-2014-creative-arts-winners-list/ |title=Emmys 2014: ''Scandal'', ''OITNB'' and ''Masters of Sex'' Stars, ''True Detective'', ''Bob's Burgers'' Among Early Winners |publisher=TVLine |first=Michael |last=Ausiello |date=August 16, 2014 |accessdate=August 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==International broadcast==\nIn Canada, the series debuted on September 29, 2013, on [[The Movie Network]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.themovienetwork.ca/series/mastersofsex/ |title=Masters of Sex |publisher=The Movie Network |accessdate=September 28, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002132110/http://www.themovienetwork.ca/series/mastersofsex/ |archive-date=October 2, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In Australia, the series premiered on [[SBS One]] on October 3, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=TV Picks: It's a Date, Masters of Sex and Upper Middle Bogan|url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/television/tv-picks-it8217s-a-date-masters-of-sex-and-upper-middle-bogan/story-e6frfmyi-1226732378805|publisher=News.com.au|first=Dianne|last=Butler|date=October 3, 2013|accessdate=October 7, 2013}}</ref> In Ireland, the series premiered on October 4, 2013, on [[RT\u00c92|RT\u00c9 Two]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://entertainment.ie/tv-highlight/Masters-of-Sex/217603.htm |title=Masters of Sex RTE2: 11.20pm|publisher=entertainment.ie|accessdate=October 10, 2013}}</ref> In the UK, it debuted on [[Channel 4]] on October 8, 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvwise.co.uk/2013/09/channel-4-sets-uk-premiere-date-for-masters-of-sex/ |title=Channel 4 Sets UK Premiere Date For \u2018Masters Of Sex\u2019 |publisher=TVWise |first=Patrick |last=Munn |date=September 25, 2013 |accessdate=September 29, 2013}}</ref> In New Zealand, it debuted on [[SoHo (TV channel)|SoHo]] on October 23, 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/blogs/on-the-box/9320727/Masters-Of-Sex-masters-sex-on-TV |title=Masters Of Sex masters sex on TV|publisher=Stuff.co.nz |first=Chris |last=Philpott|date=October 24, 2013|accessdate=November 7, 2013}}</ref> [[Virgin Media]] acquired the UK rights for ''Masters of Sex'' and it started airing on September 21, 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tvwise.co.uk/2018/09/virgin-media-to-launch-dedicated-4k-channel-picks-up-uk-rights-to-shut-eye-masters-of-sex-more/ |title=Virgin Media To Launch Dedicated 4K Channel; Picks Up UK Rights To \u2018Shut Eye\u2019, \u2018Masters Of Sex\u2019 & More |website=TVWise |first=Patrick |last=Munn |date=September 12, 2018 |accessdate=October 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{IMDb title|2137109}}\n* {{tv.com show|masters-of-sex}}\n\n{{Masters of Sex}}\n{{Showtime Network programming}}\n\n[[Category:2013 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2016 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:2010s American LGBT-related drama television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American medical television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Serial drama television series]]\n[[Category:Lesbian-related television programs]]\n[[Category:Television series about dysfunctional families]]\n[[Category:Television series set in the 1950s]]\n[[Category:Television series set in the 1960s]]\n[[Category:Television series set in the 1970s]]\n[[Category:Showtime (TV network) original programming]]\n[[Category:Television series by CBS Television Studios]]\n[[Category:Television series by Sony Pictures Television]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in St. Louis]]\n[[Category:Erotic television series]]\n[[Category:Erotic drama television series]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n | show_name = Masters of Sex\n | image = Masters of Sex title.png\n | image_size = 250px\n | image_alt =\n | genre = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Historical period drama|Period drama]]\n}}\n | developer = [[Michelle Ashford]]\n | caption = \n | based_on = {{Based on|''[[Masters of Sex (book)|Masters of Sex]]''|[[Thomas Maier]]}}\n | starring = {{Plainlist |\n* [[Michael Sheen]]\n* [[Lizzy Caplan]]\n* [[Caitlin FitzGerald]]\n* [[Teddy Sears]]\n* [[Nicholas D'Agosto]]\n* [[Annaleigh Ashford]]\n}}\n | theme_music_composer = \n | opentheme = \n | endtheme = \n | composer = [[Michael Penn]]\n | country = United States\n | language = English\n | num_seasons = 4\n | num_episodes = 46\n | list_episodes = List of Masters of Sex episodes\n | executive_producer = {{Plainlist |\n* Michelle Ashford\n* Sarah Timberman\n* Carl Beverly\n* [[Amy Lippman]]\n* Judith Verno\n}}\n | producer = Michael Sheen<br />Lizzy Caplan <br />Thomas Maier\n | location = {{Plainlist|\n* [[New York City]]\n* [[Los Angeles]]\n}}\n | cinematography = [[Ben Davis (cinematographer)|Ben Davis]]\n | camera = \n | runtime = 55\u201360 minutes\n | company = {{Plainlist|\n* Round Two Productions\n* Timberman/Beverly Productions\n* [[Sony Pictures Television]]\n* [[Showtime Networks]]\n}}\n | distributor = [[CBS Television Distribution]]\n | channel = [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]]\n | picture_format = \n | audio_format = \n | first_aired = {{Start date|2013|9|29}}\n | last_aired = {{End date|2016|11|13}}\n | preceded_by = \n | followed_by = \n | related = \n | website = \n | website_title = Official website\n | production_website = \n}}\n\n'''''Masters of Sex''''' is an American [[period drama]] television series that premiered on September 29, 2013, on [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]].<ref name=\"premiere\">{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/01/12/showtime-announces-premiere-dates-for-nurse-jackie-dexter-returning-early-ray-donovan-homeland-masters-of-sex-more/165132/|title=Showtime Announces Premiere Dates for 'Nurse Jackie,' 'Dexter' (Returning Early) 'Ray Donovan,' 'Homeland,' 'Masters of Sex' & More|last=Seidman|first=Robert|work=TV by the Numbers|date=January 12, 2013|accessdate=January 12, 2013}}</ref> It was developed by [[Michelle Ashford]] and loosely based on [[Thomas Maier]]'s biography ''[[Masters of Sex (book)|Masters of Sex]]''.<ref name=\"lat2013\"/> Set in the 1950s through the late 1960s, the series tells the story of [[Masters and Johnson]] ([[William Masters|Dr. William Masters]] and [[Virginia E. Johnson|Virginia Johnson]]) who are portrayed by [[Michael Sheen]] and [[Lizzy Caplan]]. The series has received critical acclaim. It was nominated for a [[Golden Globe Award]] for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Television Series \u2013 Drama|Best Drama Series]] in 2013. The series was canceled by Showtime on November 30, 2016, after four seasons.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2016/11/30/masters-of-sex-cancelled-showtime-season-5/ |title=Masters of Sex Is Done at Showtime |publisher=TVLine |first=Vlada |last=Gelman |date=November 30, 2016 |accessdate=November 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Premise==\nThe series explores the research and the relationship between [[William Masters]] ([[Michael Sheen]]) and [[Virginia E. Johnson|Virginia Johnson]] ([[Lizzy Caplan]]), two pioneering researchers of human sexuality at [[Washington University in St. Louis|Washington University]] in [[St. Louis, Missouri]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Maier |first=Thomas |title= Masters Of Sex: The Life and Times of William Masters and Virginia Johnson, The Couple Who Taught America How To Love|year=2009 |publisher= Basic Books |location=New York|isbn=9780465003075|pages=400|asin=B001Y35IZO}}</ref> The series begins in October 1956 and ends in August 1969 with the fourth season.\n\nAs noted by the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' television critic, the series \"hangs on bones of fact\"; \"it's more useful for the viewer to think of it as all made up. Because, mostly, it is, and because to the extent it tells the story of two real people, it also adorns the telling with dramatic practicalities, invented characters and narrative detours. Indeed, it's down these side streets, casting a brief light on a passing character (patients, prostitutes, a provost's wife), that the show finds many of its best moments.\"<ref name=\"lat2013\"/>\n\nOther than principal characters, which are partly fictionalized, adults are significantly fictionalized; however, children are entirely fictionalized. In real life, Masters and Johnson each have two children, however, in the series they have three children each. Episodes featuring the children include a disclaimer where it states that their storylines are \"entirely fictitious\". Series creator Michelle Ashford explained, \"We are telling a non-fiction story and one where there are people who are still alive out there, and those people need to be protected. We were advised to add [the baby] to protect the people that are still alive. It wasn't a storytelling prerogative. It had to do with protecting living people.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/masters-of-sex-fake-baby/ |title=The Kids Aren't Alright: Behind Masters of Sex's Controversial Children's Stories |website=TV Guide |first=Hanh |last=Nguyen |date=August 11, 2015 |accessdate=January 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Cast and characters==\n[[File:Cast of Masters of Sex at PaleyFest 2014.jpg|thumb|The cast and crew at [[PaleyFest]] 2014. From left: [[Michelle Ashford]], [[Michael Sheen]], [[Lizzy Caplan]], Sarah Timberman (executive producer), [[Caitlin FitzGerald]], [[Teddy Sears]] and [[Annaleigh Ashford]]]]\n\n===Main cast===\n* [[Michael Sheen]] as [[William Masters|Dr. William Masters]]\n* [[Lizzy Caplan]] as [[Virginia E. Johnson|Virginia Johnson]]\n* [[Caitlin FitzGerald]] as Libby Masters\n* [[Teddy Sears]] as Dr. Austin Langham (seasons 1\u20132, recurring seasons 3\u20134)\n* [[Nicholas D'Agosto]] as Dr. Ethan Haas (season 1, guest season 2)\n* [[Annaleigh Ashford]] as Betty Dimello (seasons 2\u20134, recurring season 1)\n\n===Recurring cast===\n* [[Beau Bridges]] as Barton Scully, medical school provost and longtime friend of William Masters\n* [[Allison Janney]] as Margaret Scully, Barton's wife (seasons 1\u20133)\n* [[Rose McIver]] as Vivian Scully, Barton and Margaret's daughter<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/showtimes-masters-sex-adds-lovely-419826 |title=Showtime's 'Masters of Sex' Adds 'Lovely Bones' Actress |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=February 8, 2013 |accessdate=February 11, 2013 |first=Lesley |last=Goldberg}}</ref> (seasons 1\u20132)\n* [[Hel\u00e9ne Yorke]] as Jane Martin, a hospital secretary and participant in the sex study\n* Kevin Christy as Lester Linden, the archivist of Masters and Johnson's work\n* [[Julianne Nicholson]] as Dr. Lillian DePaul, a doctor working in the Obstetrics Department of Washington University Hospital (seasons 1\u20132)\n* [[Ann Dowd]] as Estabrooks 'Essie' Masters, William's mother<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/02/linda-lavin-to-co-star-in-nbcs-sean-hayes-pilot-ann-dowd-recurs-on-masters-of-sex/ |title=Linda Lavin To Co-Star In NBC\u2019s Sean Hayes Pilot, Ann Dowd Recurs On \u2018Masters Of Sex\u2019 |publisher=Deadline.com |first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |date=February 4, 2013 |accessdate=September 28, 2013}}</ref> (seasons 1\u20132)\n* [[Mather Zickel]] as George Johnson, Virginia's ex-husband and father of her children\n* [[Cole Sand]] (seasons 1\u20132) and [[Noah Robbins]] (season 3) as Henry Johnson, Virginia's son\n* Kayla Madison (seasons 1\u20132) and [[Isabelle Fuhrman]] (seasons 3\u20134) as Tessa Johnson, Virginia's daughter\n* [[Greg Grunberg]] as Gene Moretti, Betty's husband (seasons 1\u20132)\n* [[Finn Wittrock]] as Dale, a male [[Male prostitution|prostitute]] whom Barton Scully patronizes (season 1)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thebacklot.com/masters-of-sex-gay-story/11/2013/ |title=The Compelling Gay Story in \"Masters Of Sex\" |publisher=The Backlot |date=November 19, 2013 |accessdate=November 19, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Betsy Brandt]] as Barbara Sanderson, Masters' new secretary, and later a patient of his clinic (season 2)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/breaking-bads-betsy-brandt-joins-689335 |title=Breaking Bad's' Betsy Brandt Joins Showtime's 'Masters of Sex' |work=The Hollywood Reporter |first=Lesley |last=Goldberg |date=March 18, 2014 |accessdate=May 28, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Christian Borle]] as Francis 'Frank' Masters, Jr., the younger brother of William Masters (season 2)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.ca/ustv/news/a573109/masters-of-sex-casts-smash-actor-christian-borle.html#~oFzDp7PqIGbiu8 |title=Masters of Sex casts Smash actor Christian Borle |publisher=Digital Spy |first=Tom |last=Eames |date=May 23, 2014 |accessdate=May 28, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Keke Palmer]] as Coral, the Masters' African-American nanny (season 2)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/keke-palmer-joins-showtimes-masters-of-sex-1201130050/# |title=Keke Palmer Joins Showtime\u2019s \u2018Masters of Sex' |work=Variety |first=Francesca |last=Bacardi |date=March 12, 2014 |accessdate=May 28, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Jocko Sims]] as Robert Franklin, Coral's brother and a civil rights activist (season 2)\n* [[Sarah Silverman]] as Helen, Betty's lover (seasons 2\u20134)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/sarah-silverman-masters-of-sex-1201165873/ |title=Sarah Silverman Joins \u2018Masters of Sex\u2019 Cast |work=Variety |first=Whitney |last=Friedlander |date=April 28, 2014 |accessdate=May 28, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Courtney B. Vance]] as Dr. Charles Hendricks, the head of an African-American St. Louis hospital who seeks integration (season 2)<ref name=\"Auberjonois and Vance\">{{cite web |url=http://www.deadline.com/2014/05/courtney-b-vance-rene-auberjonois-set-for-season-2-of-masters-of-sex/ |title=Courtney B. Vance & Rene Auberjonois Set For Season 2 Of \u2018Masters Of Sex\u2019 |publisher=Deadline.com |first=Erik |last=Pedersen |date=May 19, 2014 |accessdate=May 28, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Danny Huston]] as Dr. Douglas Greathouse, the head of a hospital's Obstetrics Department (season 2)\n* [[Artemis Pebdani]] as Flo Packer, the owner of a diet pill company (season 2)\n* [[Adam Arkin]] as Shep Tally, a [[Public relations|PR]] expert hired by Masters and Johnson to help them present their work (season 2)\n* [[Josh Charles]] as Dan Logan (season 3)\n* [[Emily Kinney]] as Nora Everett, a woman fascinated with Bill and Virginia's work who later becomes part of Bill's surrogacy program (season 3)\n* [[Ben Koldyke]] as Paul Edley (season 3)\n* Colin Woodell as Ronald Sturgis (season 3)\n* [[Jaeden Lieberher]] as Johnny Masters, Bill and Libby's son (seasons 3\u20134)\n* [[Jeremy Strong (actor)|Jeremy Strong]] as Dr. Art Dreesen, a psychologist who is brought in to help lessen Bill and Virginia's workload (season 4)\n* [[Betty Gilpin]] as Dr. Nancy Leveau, Art's wife and a doctor who is brought in to help lessen Bill and Virginia's workload (season 4)\n* [[Niecy Nash]] as Louise Bell, the head of Alcoholics Anonymous (season 4)\n* [[Kelli O'Hara]] as Dody Oliver, Bill's first love who did not answer his marriage proposal (season 4)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Development and production==\nShowtime ordered the pilot for ''Masters of Sex'' in August 2011,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.deadline.com/2011/08/showtime-picks-up-pilots-from-andrew-gurland-michelle-ashford-ann-biderman/ |title=Showtime Picks Up Pilots From Andrew Gurland, Michelle Ashford & Ann Biderman |publisher=Deadline.com |first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |date=August 21, 2011 |accessdate=September 30, 2013}}</ref> and greenlit it for series in June 2012, with the first season consisting of twelve episodes.<ref name=\"variety\">{{cite news |url=https://variety.com/2012/tv/news/showtime-gives-series-orders-to-donovan-sex-1118055335/ |title=Showtime gives series orders to 'Donovan,' 'Sex' |last=Littleton |first=Cynthia |date=June 11, 2012 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=July 15, 2012}}</ref>\n\nWriter/producer [[Michelle Ashford]] serves as [[showrunner]] for ''Masters of Sex''. She assembled a majority-female writing staff, although she says this was unintentional.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nymag.com/thecut/2013/09/dirty-talk-with-the-woman-behind-masters-of-sex.html |title=Q&A: Dirty Talk With the Woman Behind ''Masters of Sex'' |work=New York Magazine |first=Allison P. |last=Davis |date=September 30, 2013 |accessdate=September 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAshford created the character of Barton Scully out of a combination of several men whom Masters knew. One of them was gay, but was not the man serving as provost during Masters' initial study.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thebacklot.com/masters-of-sex-creator-on-the-shows-gay-storyline/11/2013/ |title=\"Masters Of Sex\" Creator On The Show\u2019s \"Exciting\" Gay Storyline |publisher=The Backlot |first=Jim |last=Halterman |date=November 25, 2013 |accessdate=November 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\nProp master Jeffrey Johnson noted the difficulty of obtaining accurate information about [[sex toy|sexual devices]] from the time period. \"They were so taboo it was hard to find research drawings. People didn\u2019t even put them in writing.\" He obtained some vintage vibrators and [[dildo]]s for use in the series along with acquiring [[condom]]s manufactured in the era (which did not have the reservoir tips of modern condoms). He designed \"Ulysses\", a transparent dildo with attached camera first seen in the pilot episode, from scratch, along with a diaphragm sizing kit seen in later episodes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vulture.com/2013/09/masters-of-sex-prop-master-glass-dildos.html |title=Talking to ''Masters of Sex''{{'}}s Prop Master About Glass Dildos and Old Condoms |work=Vulture |first=Molly |last=Langmuir |date=September 30, 2013 |accessdate=September 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[Annaleigh Ashford]], who has a recurring role in the first season as Betty Dimello, was promoted to series regular in season two.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/12/annaleigh-ashford-regular-on-masters-of-sex-departs-kinky-boots/ |title=Annaleigh Ashford Upped To Regular On \u2018Masters Of Sex\u2019, Will Depart \u2018Kinky Boots\u2019 |publisher=Deadline.com |first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |date=December 3, 2013 |accessdate=December 8, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe [[opening credits]] sequence was created by design studio Elastic. The sequence, which includes suggestive, tongue-in-cheek sex metaphors and symbols, received a mixed response from critics; it placed on both best and worst lists for opening credit sequences. It was also nominated for the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Main Title Design]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://time.com/2980158/masters-of-sex-season-2-premier-opening-credits/ |title=Behind the Unusual Opening Credits to Masters of Sex |work=Time |first=Feeney |last=Nolan |date=July 14, 2014 |accessdate=February 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Series overview ==\n{{Main|List of Masters of Sex episodes}}\n{{:List of Masters of Sex episodes}}\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Critical response===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"float: right;text-align:center; width:%70;margin:10px\"\n|-\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" | Season\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" colspan=\"2\" | Critical response\n|-\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | [[Rotten Tomatoes]]\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | [[Metacritic]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#BDD6D3;\"|\n| 1\n| 90% (58 reviews)\n| 86 (32 reviews)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#B30027;\"|\n| 2\n| 98% (43 reviews)\n| 89 (17 reviews)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#0D3952;\"|\n| 3\n| 69% (32 reviews)\n| 72 (15 reviews)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#A7BA9A;\"|\n| 4\n| 80% (10 reviews)\n| 70 (5 reviews)\n|-\n|}\n\nThe first season of ''Masters of Sex'' received critical acclaim. Based on 58 reviews collected by [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the first season received a 90% approval rating from critics, with a rating average of 8.26 out of 10. The site's consensus states: \"Seductive and nuanced, ''Masters of Sex'' features smart performances, deft direction, and impeccable period decor.\"<ref>{{cite web |url =http://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/masters-of-sex/s01/ |title=Masters of Sex: Season 1 (2013) |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=October 27, 2013}}</ref> [[Metacritic]] gave the first season a score of 86 out of 100, based on 32 reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/masters-of-sex/season-1 |title=Masters of Sex \u2013 Season 1 Reviews |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=September 28, 2013}}</ref> The [[American Film Institute]] listed it as one of the top ten television series of 2013.<ref name=\"afi\">{{cite web | url=https://variety.com/2013/film/awards/afi-names-best-movies-and-tv-shows-of-2013-1200937298/ | title=AFI Names Best Movies and TV Shows of 2013 | work=Variety |date=December 9, 2013 |accessdate=December 9, 2013 | first=Tim |last=Gray}}</ref>\n\nMatt Roush of ''[[TV Guide]]'' wrote that \"There is no more fascinating, or entertaining, new series this fall season.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvguide.com/News/Weekend-Playlist-Masters-1071377.aspx |title=Weekend Playlist: ''Masters of Sex'' and ''Homeland'', ''Breaking Bad'' Finale on Jam-Packed Sunday |work=TV Guide |first=Matt |last=Roush |date=September 27, 2013 |accessdate=November 7, 2013}}</ref> Diane Werts of ''[[Newsday]]'' gave it an \"A\" grade, complimenting the series on its use of humor, stating \"its deft balance of epic scope and whimsical humanity\", as well as the strong performances of the actors and creator [[Michelle Ashford]]'s \"scene-setting scripts\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newsday.com/entertainment/tv/masters-of-sex-review-showtime-scores-1.6139803 |title='Masters of Sex' review: Showtime scores |work=Newsday |first=Diane |last=Werts |date=September 25, 2013 |accessdate=November 7, 2013}}</ref> [[David Wiegand]] of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' particularly praised the performances, calling them \"extraordinary\" and \"stunning\", and noting the series' A-list directors, among them [[Michael Apted]] and [[John Madden (director)|John Madden]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sfgate.com/tv/article/Masters-of-Sex-review-Satisfying-look-at-sex-4847308.php |title='Masters of Sex' review: Satisfying look at sex |work=San Francisco Chronicle |first=David |last=Wiegand |date=September 26, 2013 |accessdate=November 7, 2013}}</ref> Hank Stuever of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' wrote that after the first two episodes, \"the characters get better and more complex, the story builds, strange things start to happen and now I can't wait to see how its interweaving plots unfold.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/tv/showtimes-masters-of-sex-starts-off-slow-and-deliberate-and-then-finds-the-right-spot/2013/09/26/19a08e06-263d-11e3-b3e9-d97fb087acd6_story.html |title=Showtime\u2019s \u2018Masters of Sex\u2019 gets better as it goes along |work=The Washington Post |first=Hank |last=Stuever |date=September 26, 2013 |accessdate=November 7, 2013}}</ref> Alan Sepinwall of [[HitFix]] praised lead actors [[Michael Sheen]] and [[Lizzy Caplan]], calling them \"terrific\", and saying that \"''Masters of Sex'' is the best new show of the fall by a very long stretch. It's also a refreshing anomaly: a prestige cable drama that doesn't feel like a recombination of elements from 15 shows that came before it.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hitfix.com/whats-alan-watching/review-michael-sheen-lizzy-caplan-shine-in-showtimes-masters-of-sex |title=Review: Michael Sheen & Lizzy Caplan shine in Showtime's 'Masters of Sex' |publisher=HitFix |first=Alan |last=Sepinwall |date=September 26, 2013 |accessdate= November 7, 2013}}</ref>  According to Robert Lloyd, the ''Los Angeles Times'' television critic, the show is a \"handsome thing, another well-dressed romp through the American mid-century, when things (we imagine) were simpler and (so we like to think) less sophisticated, but also more exciting. And it's true that sexual naivet\u00e9 of that age can seem incredible in a day when pornography is just another thing on your platform of choice. But even in an age when ''Masters of Sex'' is a TV show, the subject remains stubbornly powerful, private and confounding. We have come far, and we are still cavemen.<ref name=\"lat2013\">{{cite web |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2013/sep/28/entertainment/la-et-st-masters-of-sex-review |title=Review: 'Masters of Sex' explores the science of sex |date=September 28, 2013 |first=Robert |last=Lloyd |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=December 1, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe second season also received critical acclaim equal to if not greater than the first season. It received a score of 89 out of 100 on Metacritic based on 17 reviews, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/masters-of-sex/season-2 |title=Masters of Sex \u2013 Season 2 Reviews |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=July 12, 2014}}</ref> On Rotten Tomatoes, it has a 98% approval rating among critics based on 43 reviews, with a rating average of 8.52 out of 10. The consensus reads: \"Boasting an expanded storyline and broader focus, ''Masters of Sex''{{'}}s second season improves on its already outstanding predecessor.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/masters-of-sex/s02/ |title=Masters of Sex: Season 2|publisher=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=September 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe third season received generally positive reviews from critics, although received more mixed reviews than the previous seasons. It has a Metacritic score of 72 out of 100 based on 15 reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/masters-of-sex/season-3 |title=Masters of Sex \u2013 Season 3 Reviews |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref> On Rotten Tomatoes, it has a 69% approval rating among critics based on 32 reviews, with a rating average of 7.61 out of 10. The consensus reads, \"With a six-year leap forward in the timeline, ''Masters of Sex'' takes an intriguing dramatic turn, but may leave a few viewers feeling frustrated.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/masters-of-sex/s03/|title=Masters of Sex: Season 3|publisher=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=July 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe fourth season received generally positive reviews from critics. It has a Metacritic score of 70 out of 100 based on 5 reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/masters-of-sex/season-4 |title=Masters of Sex \u2013 Season 4 Reviews |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=September 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n{{main|List of awards and nominations received by Masters of Sex}}\n{{Anchor|Awards|Accolades}}\nIn June 2013, the series was honored, along with five others, with the [[Critics' Choice Television Award for Most Exciting New Series]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.criticschoice.com/television-awards/the-btja-announces-icon-award-recipient-and-most-exciting-new-series-honorees/ |title=The BTJA Announces Icon Award Recipient and Most Exciting New Series Honorees |publisher=The Broadcast Television Journalists Association |date=June 10, 2013 |accessdate=June 29, 2013}}</ref> The series received two nominations for the 2014 [[Writers Guild of America Award]]s, for Best New Series and Best Episodic Drama for \"Pilot\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2013/12/05/writers-guild-award-nominations-2014-list-wga/ |title=''Breaking Bad'', ''Orange Is the New Black'', ''House of Cards'' Lead 2014 WGA Nominations |publisher=TVLine |first=Michael |last=Ausiello |date=December 5, 2013 |accessdate=December 5, 2013}}</ref>  For the [[71st Golden Globe Awards]], the series was nominated for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Television Series \u2013 Drama|Best Drama Series]], and [[Michael Sheen]] was nominated [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Television Series Drama|Best Drama Actor]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2013/12/12/golden-globe-nominations-2014-globes-awards-nominees/ |title=Golden Globes: ''House of Cards'', ''The Good Wife'', ''Candelabra'' and ''Breaking Bad'' Lead Noms; ''Parks & Rec'', ''Brooklyn'', Spader and Maslany Score Nods |publisher=TVLine |first=Matt Webb |last=Mitovich |date=December 12, 2013 |accessdate=December 12, 2013}}</ref> For the [[66th Primetime Emmy Awards]], [[Lizzy Caplan]] received a nomination for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Drama Series|Outstanding Lead Actress in a Drama Series]], [[Beau Bridges]] received a nomination for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Guest Actor in a Drama Series|Outstanding Guest Actor in a Drama Series]], and [[Allison Janney]] won for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Guest Actress in a Drama Series|Outstanding Guest Actress in a Drama Series]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/emmy-nominations-2014-list-emmys-nominees-1201260236/ |title=2014 Emmy Awards: \u2018Game of Thrones,\u2019 \u2018Fargo\u2019 Lead Nominations |work=Variety |first=Brian |last=Lowry |date=July 10, 2014 |accessdate=July 10, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2014/08/16/emmys-2014-creative-arts-winners-list/ |title=Emmys 2014: ''Scandal'', ''OITNB'' and ''Masters of Sex'' Stars, ''True Detective'', ''Bob's Burgers'' Among Early Winners |publisher=TVLine |first=Michael |last=Ausiello |date=August 16, 2014 |accessdate=August 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==International broadcast==\nIn Canada, the series debuted on September 29, 2013, on [[The Movie Network]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.themovienetwork.ca/series/mastersofsex/ |title=Masters of Sex |publisher=The Movie Network |accessdate=September 28, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002132110/http://www.themovienetwork.ca/series/mastersofsex/ |archive-date=October 2, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In Australia, the series premiered on [[SBS One]] on October 3, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=TV Picks: It's a Date, Masters of Sex and Upper Middle Bogan|url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/television/tv-picks-it8217s-a-date-masters-of-sex-and-upper-middle-bogan/story-e6frfmyi-1226732378805|publisher=News.com.au|first=Dianne|last=Butler|date=October 3, 2013|accessdate=October 7, 2013}}</ref> In Ireland, the series premiered on October 4, 2013, on [[RT\u00c92|RT\u00c9 Two]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://entertainment.ie/tv-highlight/Masters-of-Sex/217603.htm |title=Masters of Sex RTE2: 11.20pm|publisher=entertainment.ie|accessdate=October 10, 2013}}</ref> In the UK, it debuted on [[Channel 4]] on October 8, 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvwise.co.uk/2013/09/channel-4-sets-uk-premiere-date-for-masters-of-sex/ |title=Channel 4 Sets UK Premiere Date For \u2018Masters Of Sex\u2019 |publisher=TVWise |first=Patrick |last=Munn |date=September 25, 2013 |accessdate=September 29, 2013}}</ref> In New Zealand, it debuted on [[SoHo (TV channel)|SoHo]] on October 23, 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/blogs/on-the-box/9320727/Masters-Of-Sex-masters-sex-on-TV |title=Masters Of Sex masters sex on TV|publisher=Stuff.co.nz |first=Chris |last=Philpott|date=October 24, 2013|accessdate=November 7, 2013}}</ref> [[Virgin Media]] acquired the UK rights for ''Masters of Sex'' and it started airing on September 21, 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tvwise.co.uk/2018/09/virgin-media-to-launch-dedicated-4k-channel-picks-up-uk-rights-to-shut-eye-masters-of-sex-more/ |title=Virgin Media To Launch Dedicated 4K Channel; Picks Up UK Rights To \u2018Shut Eye\u2019, \u2018Masters Of Sex\u2019 & More |website=TVWise |first=Patrick |last=Munn |date=September 12, 2018 |accessdate=October 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{IMDb title|2137109}}\n* {{tv.com show|masters-of-sex}}\n\n{{Masters of Sex}}\n{{Showtime Network programming}}\n\n[[Category:2013 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2016 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:2010s American LGBT-related drama television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American medical television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Serial drama television series]]\n[[Category:Lesbian-related television programs]]\n[[Category:Television series about dysfunctional families]]\n[[Category:Television series set in the 1950s]]\n[[Category:Television series set in the 1960s]]\n[[Category:Television series set in the 1970s]]\n[[Category:Showtime (TV network) original programming]]\n[[Category:Television series by CBS Television Studios]]\n[[Category:Television series by Sony Pictures Television]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in St. Louis]]\n[[Category:Erotic television series]]\n[[Category:Erotic drama television series]]\n", "name_user": "Kailash29792", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Masters_of_Sex"}
{"title_page": "Colgate (toothpaste)", "text_new": "{{Infobox brand\n| name           = Colgate\n| logo           = Colgate logo red.svg\n| logo_size      = 200px \n| producttype    = Oral hygiene\n| currentowner   = [[Colgate-Palmolive Company]] \n| introduced     = {{Start date and age|1873}} \n| country        = [[United States]]\n| origin         = [[United States]]\n| tagline        = \n| website        = https://www.colgate.com/\n}}\n\n'''Colgate''' is an [[United States|American]] brand principally used for [[oral hygiene]] products such as [[toothpaste]]s, [[toothbrush]]es, [[mouthwash]]es and [[dental floss]]. American manufactured by [[Colgate-Palmolive]], Colgate oral hygiene products were first sold by the company in 1873, sixteen years after the death of the founder, [[William Colgate]]. The company originally sold soap.\n\nAccording to a 2015 report by [[market research]] company [[Kantar Worldpanel]], Colgate is the only brand in the world purchased by more than half of all households.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kantarworldpanel.com/global/News/Colgate-bought-by-over-half-of-the-worlds-households|title=Colgate bought by over half of the world households - Global site - Kantar Worldpanel|website=www.kantarworldpanel.com|access-date=January 12, 2017}}</ref> Colgate has a global [[market penetration]] of 67.7% and a global [[market share]] of 45%.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.colgate.com/us/en/annual-reports/2015/common/pdf/Colgate-Palmolive_2015-Annual-Report.pdf|title=Colgate-Palmolive Company 2015 Annual Report|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=The Colgate-Palmolive Company|access-date=January 12, 2016}}</ref> Despite this, it maintained the highest growth rate of all brands in the survey, with 40 million new households purchasing Colgate-branded products in 2014.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.brandfootprint-ranking.com/#/brands-in-action/global-brands/colgate|title=Brand Footprint|website=www.brandfootprint-ranking.com|access-date=January 12, 2017}}</ref> Its global market penetration is nearly 50%; higher than the second-placed brand in the study, [[Coca-Cola]] with 43.3% penetration.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Colgate ad 1915.jpg|thumb|120px|1915 magazine ad]]\n[[File:Colgate Dental Cream ca 1950s.jpg|thumb|Colgate Dental Cream (Toothpaste) With [[Sodium lauroyl sarcosinate|Gardol]] - ca. 1950s]]\nColgate was the first toothpaste in a collapsible tube, introduced in 1896 in [[New York City]]. It had been sold in glass jars since 1873.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.colgate.com/app/Colgate/US/Corp/History/1806.cvsp|title=Colgate-Palmolive Company History: Creating Bright Smiles for 200 Years|work=colgate.com|access-date=2007-10-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060502094906/http://www.colgate.com/app/Colgate/US/Corp/History/1806.cvsp|archive-date=2006-05-02|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIt has been in [[Malaysia]] since the 1920s. It is in [[Nepal]] and [[India]], with manufacturing units based in [[India]] and exported to [[Nepal]]. While in the [[Philippines]], it was introduced in 1926 under The Palmolive Company Philippines before it changed its name to Colgate-Palmolive Philippines in 1949.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}\n\nIn 1957, Colgate established its first factory in [[India]] to produce toothpaste for the domestic market, and by 1999 became the highest selling brand in the world.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}} Colgate products are marketed in [[China]] under its [[Chinese language|Chinese]]  Brand name \u9ad8\u9732\u6d01 ([[Pinyin]]: G\u0101ol\u00f9ji\u00e9), which means \"high-quality cleaning gel\".{{citation needed|date=January 2015}} As of 2002, Colgate occupied 20% of the market share for toothpastes in [[China]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://baike.baidu.com/view/28156.htm |title=\u9ad8\u9732\u6d01 (Colgate) |publisher=Baidu |date=March 17, 2013}}</ref> {{As of | 2015}}, it also commanded approximately 70% of the oral care market in [[Brazil]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn 2007, the [[Advertising Standards Authority (United Kingdom)|Advertising Standards Authority]] in the [[United Kingdom|UK]] told Colgate that it could no longer make the claim that 4 out of 5 dentists recommended Colgate. Investigation had showed that the study had telephone surveyed dentists to list toothpastes they recommended, and their competitors were recommended at similar rates. The claim was deemed deceptive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1539715/Colgate-gets-the-brush-off-for-misleading-ads.html|title=Colgate gets the brush off for 'misleading' ads|first=David | last=Derbyshire|date=February 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{As of |2015}}, oral care products (principally produced under the Colgate brand) were the [[Colgate-Palmolive]] company's largest source of income, making up around US$7.5 billion, or 47% of net sales globally (with personal care products such as shampoos making up 20%, home care products such as laundry detergents 19% and pet nutrition products making up the remaining 14%).<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Companies|Medicine}}\n*[[List of toothpaste brands]]\n*[[Index of oral health and dental articles]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Colgate-Palmolive}}\n*{{Official}}\n\n{{Colgate-Palmolive}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT: Colgate (Toothpaste)}}\n[[Category: 1873 introductions]]\n[[Category: Brands of toothpaste]]\n[[Category: Colgate-Palmolive brands]]\n[[Category: American brands]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox brand\n| name           = Colgate\n| logo           = Colgate logo red.svg\n| logo_size      = 200px \n| producttype    = Oral hygiene\n| currentowner   = [[Colgate-Palmolive Company]] \n| introduced     = {{Start date and age|1873}} \n| country        = [[United States]]\n| origin         = [[United States]]\n| tagline        = \n| website        = https://www.colgate.com/\n}}\n\n'''Colgate''' is an [[United States|American]] brand principally used for [[oral hygiene]] products such as [[toothpaste]]s, [[toothbrush]]es, [[mouthwash]]es and [[dental floss]]. American manufactured by [[Colgate-Palmolive]], Colgate oral hygiene products were first sold by the company in 1873, sixteen years after the death of the founder, [[William Colgate]]. The company originally sold soap.\n\nAccording to a 2015 report by [[market research]] company [[Kantar Worldpanel]], Colgate is the only brand in the world purchased by more than half of all households.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kantarworldpanel.com/global/News/Colgate-bought-by-over-half-of-the-worlds-households|title=Colgate bought by over half of the world households - Global site - Kantar Worldpanel|website=www.kantarworldpanel.com|access-date=January 12, 2017}}</ref> Colgate has a global [[market penetration]] of 67.7% and a global [[market share]] of 45%.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.colgate.com/us/en/annual-reports/2015/common/pdf/Colgate-Palmolive_2015-Annual-Report.pdf|title=Colgate-Palmolive Company 2015 Annual Report|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=The Colgate-Palmolive Company|access-date=January 12, 2016}}</ref> Despite this, it maintained the highest growth rate of all brands in the survey, with 40 million new households purchasing Colgate-branded products in 2014.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.brandfootprint-ranking.com/#/brands-in-action/global-brands/colgate|title=Brand Footprint|website=www.brandfootprint-ranking.com|access-date=January 12, 2017}}</ref> Its global market penetration is nearly 50%; higher than the second-placed brand in the study, [[Coca-Cola]] with 43.3% penetration.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Colgate ad 1915.jpg|thumb|120px|1915 magazine ad]]\n[[File:Colgate Dental Cream ca 1950s.jpg|thumb|Colgate Dental Cream (Toothpaste) With [[Sodium lauroyl sarcosinate|Gardol]] - ca. 1950s]]\nColgate was the first toothpaste in a collapsible tube, introduced in 1896 in [[New York City]]. It had been sold in glass jars since 1873.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.colgate.com/app/Colgate/US/Corp/History/1806.cvsp|title=Colgate-Palmolive Company History: Creating Bright Smiles for 200 Years|work=colgate.com|access-date=2007-10-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060502094906/http://www.colgate.com/app/Colgate/US/Corp/History/1806.cvsp|archive-date=2006-05-02|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIt has been in [[Malaysia]] since the 1920s. It is in [[Nepal]] and [[India]], with manufacturing units based in [[India]] and exported to [[Nepal]]. While in the [[Philippines]], it was introduced in 1926 under The Palmolive Company Philippines before it changed its name to Colgate-Palmolive Philippines in 1949.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}\n\nIn 1957, Colgate established its first factory in [[India]] to produce toothpaste for the domestic market, and by 1999 became the highest selling brand in the world.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}} Colgate products are marketed in [[China]] under its [[Chinese language|Chinese]]  Brand name \u9ad8\u9732\u6d01 ([[Pinyin]]: G\u0101ol\u00f9ji\u00e9), which means \"high-quality cleaning gel\".{{citation needed|date=January 2015}} As of 2002, Colgate occupied 20% of the market share for toothpastes in [[China]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://baike.baidu.com/view/28156.htm |title=\u9ad8\u9732\u6d01 (Colgate) |publisher=Baidu |date=March 17, 2013}}</ref> {{As of | 2015}}, it also commanded approximately 70% of the oral care market in [[Brazil]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn 2007, the [[Advertising Standards Authority (United Kingdom)|Advertising Standards Authority]] in the [[United Kingdom|UK]] told Colgate that it could no longer make the claim that 4 out of 5 dentists recommended Colgate. Investigation had showed that the study had telephone surveyed dentists to list toothpastes they recommended, and their competitors were recommended at similar rates. The claim was deemed deceptive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1539715/Colgate-gets-the-brush-off-for-misleading-ads.html|title=Colgate gets the brush off for 'misleading' ads|first=David | last=Derbyshire|date=February 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{As of |2015}}, oral care products (principally produced under the Colgate brand) were the [[Colgate-Palmolive]] company's largest source of income, making up around US$7.5 billion, or 47% of net sales globally (with personal care products such as shampoos making up 20%, home care products such as laundry detergents 19% and pet nutrition products making up the remaining 14%).<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Companies|Medicine}}\n*[[List of toothpaste brands]]\n*[[Index of oral health and dental articles]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Colgate-Palmolive}}\n*{{Official}}\n\n{{Colgate-Palmolive}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Colgate (Toothpaste)}}\n[[Category:1873 introductions]]\n[[Category:Brands of toothpaste]]\n[[Category:Colgate-Palmolive brands]]\n[[Category:American brands]]\n", "name_user": "Chirag Varna", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Colgate_(toothpaste)"}
{"title_page": "Patliputra University", "text_new": "{{short description|University in India}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2018}}\n\n{{Infobox university\n| name = Patliputra University\n| native_name = \n| image = Patliputra_University_logo.jpg\n| image_upright = \n| image_alt = \n| caption = \n| latin_name = \n| other_name = <!--or, other_names-->\n| former_name = <!--or, former_names-->\n| motto = \n| motto_lang = \n| mottoeng = \n| top_free_label = \n| top_free = \n| type = [[Public university|Public]]\n| established = {{start date and age|18 March 2018}}\n| closed = <!-- {{end date|YYYY}} -->\n| founder = \n| parent = \n| affiliation = \n| religious_affiliation = \n| academic_affiliation = \n| endowment = \n| budget = \n| officer_in_charge = \n| chairman = \n| chairperson = \n| chancellor = [[Governor of Bihar]]<br />{{small|(At present, [[Fagu Chauhan]])}}\n| president = \n| vice-president = \n| superintendent = \n| provost = \n| vice_chancellor = Gulab Chand Ram Jaiswal<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://governor.bih.nic.in/ORDER/BSU-(VC-PVC%20Patliputra%20Univ.)-44-2017-741.pdf |title=Regarding appointment of Vice Chancellor of newly constituted Patliputra University, Patna |date=2018-03-19 |publisher=GOVERNOR SECRETRIAT BIHAR |location=RAJ BHAWAN PATNA |access-date=2018-06-16 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180620094132/http://governor.bih.nic.in/ORDER/BSU-(VC-PVC%20Patliputra%20Univ.)-44-2017-741.pdf |archivedate=20 June 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n| rector = \n| principal = \n| dean = Prof. Vijaya Lakshmi [Dean Faculty of Social Science] ; Prof. R. K. Sharma [Dean Faculty of Humanities] ; Prof. Mahendra Pratap Singh [ Dean Faculty of Commerce] ; Prof. Md. Quddus [Dean Faculty of Management] ; Dr. Kamal Prasad Bauddha [Dean Faculty of Education] ; Prof. S.K. Sharma [Dean Faculty of Science]\n| director = \n| head_label = \n| head = \n| academic_staff = \n| administrative_staff = \n| students = \n| undergrad = \n| postgrad = \n| doctoral = \n| other = \n| address = Old Bypass Road, Kankarbagh\n| city = [[Patna]]\n| state = [[Bihar]]\n| province = \n| country = India\n| postcode = 800-020\n| coordinates = {{coord|25.602493|N|85.159128|E|type:edu|display=title}}\n| campus = Urban\n| language = \n| free_label = \n| free = \n| free_label2 = \n| free2 = \n| colors = <!--or, colours= -->\n| athletics = \n| sports = \n| athletics_nickname = <!--or,  sports_nickname= -->\n| sporting_affiliations = \n| mascot = <!--or, mascots= -->\n| sports_free_label = \n| sports_free = \n| sports_free_label2 = \n| sports_free2 = \n| website = {{Official website|ppup.ac.in}}\n| logo = \n| logo_size = \n| logo_alt = \n| footnotes = \n| pushpin_map = India Patna\n| pushpin_label_position = \n| pushpin_map_alt = \n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in Patna, India\n}}\n\n'''Patliputra University''' ('''PPU''') is a [[Collegiate university|collegiate]] [[Public university|public]] [[State university (India)|state university]] located in [[Patna]], [[Bihar]], [[India]]. It was established by an act of the state legislature in 2018. As a [[collegiate university]], its main functions are divided between the academic departments of the university and affiliated colleges. The university has 125 affiliated colleges including twenty-five [[constituent college]]s, two engineering colleges and a dozen pharmacy colleges spread over two [[List of districts of Bihar|districts]], viz. [[Patna district|Patna]] and [[Nalanda district|Nalanda]].<ref name=\"telegraph\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/states/bihar/new-atopa-varsity-220356 |title=New \u2018top\u2019 varsity |author=Roshan Kumar |date=2018-04-03 |website=The Telegraph |language=en |access-date=2018-06-16 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180620094132/https://www.telegraphindia.com/states/bihar/new-atopa-varsity-220356 |archivedate=20 June 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==History== \nIn 2015, Bihar's education minister hinted that [[Magadh University]] (MU) may be split into two or three universities due to the difficulties faced in managing the colleges of oversized MU. In the month of July of the same year, then vice-chancellor of MU, Mohammad Ishtiyaque decided to strengthen the university's Patna branch office to reduce the student's necessity to visit the university headquarters situated at [[Bodh Gaya]]. As a part of the strengthening process, a committee was set up to monitor the expansion and growth of the Patna branch office.<ref>{{cite news|title=MU\u2019s Patna office to cater to needs of 1.5L students |url=https://m.timesofindia.com/city/patna/MUs-Patna-office-to-cater-to-needs-of-1-5L-students/articleshow/48163668.cms |author=B K Mishra |newspaper=[[The Times of India]] |location=[[Patna]] |date=22 July 2015 |access-date=20 June 2018 }}</ref>\n\nOn 30 July 2016, Bihar cabinet approved ''Bihar State Universities (Amendment) Bill 2016'' and made way for the creation of Patliputra University by bifurcating the Magadh University.<ref>{{cite news |title=Govt circulates new varsity bill in House |url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/1160802/jsp/bihar/story_100010.jsp |author=Roshan Kumar |newspaper=[[The Telegraph (India)|The Telegraph]] |date=2 August 2016 |access-date=21 June 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621090723/https://www.telegraphindia.com/1160802/jsp/bihar/story_100010.jsp |archivedate=21 June 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |script-title=hi:\u0930\u093e\u091c\u094d\u092f \u092e\u0947\u0902 \u0926\u094b \u0928\u090f \u0935\u093f\u0936\u094d\u0935\u0935\u093f\u0926\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0932\u092f \u092a\u091f\u0928\u093e \u0914\u0930 \u092a\u0942\u0930\u094d\u0923\u093f\u092f\u093e \u092e\u0947\u0902 \u0916\u0941\u0932\u0947\u0902\u0917\u0947 |url=https://m.bhaskar.com/bihar/patna/news/BIH-PAT-HMU-MAT-latest-patna-news-025502-668095-NOR.html |newspaper=[[Dainik Bhaskar]] |language=Hindi |date=31 July 2016 |access-date=21 June 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621090723/https://m.bhaskar.com/bihar/patna/news/BIH-PAT-HMU-MAT-latest-patna-news-025502-668095-NOR.html |archivedate=21 June 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> A notice was issued in October 2017 inviting application from candidates for the posts of vice-chancellor and pro-vice-chancellor.<ref name=t1>{{cite news |title=Chancellor picks VCs for new varsities |url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/states/bihar/chancellor-picks-vcs-for-new-varsities-216925 |author=Roshan Kumar |newspaper=[[The Telegraph (India)|The Telegraph]] |location=[[Patna]] |date=20 March 2018 |access-date=21 March 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180320091524/https://www.telegraphindia.com/states/bihar/chancellor-picks-vcs-for-new-varsities-216925 |archivedate=20 March 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> More than 150 professors applied for the jobs of vice-chancellor and pro-vice-chancellor.<ref>{{cite news|title=171 apply for Pataliputra varsity VC, pro-VC posts |url=https://m.timesofindia.com/city/gaya/171-apply-for-pataliputra-varsity-vc-pro-vc-posts/articleshow/62310480.cms |newspaper=[[The Times of India]] |author=Abdul Qadir |date=31 December 2017 |location=[[Gaya, India|Gaya]]\n|access-date=7 July 2018 }}</ref> On 19 March 2018, Bihar Governor [[Satya Pal Malik]] appointed Girish Kumar Choudhary and Gulab Chand Ram Jaiswal as the pro-vice-chancellor and vice-chancellor of the Patliputra University, respectively, under the ''Bihar State University (Amendment) Act, 1976''.<ref name=it>{{cite news |title=Governor appoints VCs & Pro VCs in 3 new univs of Bihar |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/pti-feed/story/governor-appoints-vcs-andamp-pro-vcs-in-3-new-univs-of-bihar-1192885-2018-03-19 |work=[[Press Trust of India]] |publisher=[[India Today]] |location=[[Patna]] |date=19 March 2018 |access-date=21 June 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621090723/https://www.indiatoday.in/pti-feed/story/governor-appoints-vcs-andamp-pro-vcs-in-3-new-univs-of-bihar-1192885-2018-03-19 |archivedate=21 June 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Administration== \nThe staff of Patliputra University will be created by dividing the staff of Magadh University.<ref>{{cite news |title=Delay clouds varsities \u2013 Employees' protest holds up bifurcation process |url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/1170626/jsp/bihar/story_158687.jsp |author=Roshan Kumar |newspaper=[[The Telegraph (India)|The Telegraph]] |date=26 June 2017 |access-date=21 June 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621090723/https://www.telegraphindia.com/1170626/jsp/bihar/story_158687.jsp |archivedate=21 June 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=t1/> 55 per cent of the non-teaching staff of Magadh University will shift to Patliputra University post bifurcation while the rest 45 per cent will remain with MU.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://m.timesofindia.com/city/patna/pataliputra-university-grapples-with-staff-crunch/articleshow/64653821.cms|title=Pataliputra University grapples with staff crunch \u2013 Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=2018-06-23}}</ref> Gulab Chand Ram Jaiswal of the [[Banaras Hindu University]]\u2019s faculty of commerce is the vice-chancellor of the university whereas Girish Kumar Choudhary from the [[National Institute of Technology, Patna]]'s electrical department is the pro-vice-chancellor.<ref name=\"telegraph\"/> [[List of governors of Bihar|Bihar's governor]], [[Lalji Tandon]] serves as the chancellor of Patliputra University.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/2018/apr/08/jackboots-on-university-campuses-in-bihar-protests-against-government-move-1798611.html |title=Jackboots on university campuses in Bihar, protests against government move |website=The New Indian Express |access-date=2018-06-16 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616204031/http://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/2018/apr/08/jackboots-on-university-campuses-in-bihar-protests-against-government-move-1798611.html |archivedate=16 June 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Dr. Kaushlendra Kumar Singh is the current Registrar of Patliputra University. Manoj Kumar is the university's proctor. Jinendra Kumar is the dean for student welfare and the dean of the university's Faculty of Science, whereas, Mahendra Pratap Singh is the dean of Faculty of Commerce and R.K. Mishra is the dean of Faculty of Arts and CCDC in the university.<ref name=\"ppup.ac.in\">{{Cite web|url=http://ppup.ac.in/contact-us|title=:::  PATLIPUTRA UNIVERSITY, PATNA  :::|website=ppup.ac.in|language=en|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref>.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/states/bihar/armymen-as-registrars-220642|title=Armymen as registrars|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2018-06-23|language=en}}</ref> Ashok Kumar Gupta is the inspector of colleges (science) and Dr. Praveen Kumar, Department of Economics, College of Commerce is the controller of examinations in the university. Dinesh Prasad Singh are assistant controllers of examinations. K.K. Singh is professor-in-charge of sports and Ratna Amrit is the coordinator for the [[National Service Scheme]]. Dr. Dhruv Kumar, Nalanda College Biharsharif is media in-charge Dr. Pradhan Durga Shankar Prasad, Department of Physics R K D College Patna will be incharge of Establishment.<ref name=\"ppup.ac.in\"/>\n\n== Colleges ==\n=== Constituent Colleges ===\n{{columns-list|colwidth=20em|\n*[[Anugrah Narayan College, Patna|A N College, Patna]]\n*[[ANS College, Barh]]\n*[[B.D. College, Patna|B D College, Patna]]\n*[[BS College, Danapur]]\n*[[College of Commerce, Arts and Science, Patna|College Of Commerce, Arts & Science, Patna]]\n*[[G.J. College, Bihta|G J College, Rambagh, Bihta]]\n*[[Ganga Devi Mahila College]]\n*[[J.D. Women's College|J D  Womens College, Patna]]\n* [[Jagat Narain Lal College]]\n* [[MM College, Bikram]]\n* [[Mahila College, Khagaul]]\n* [[Maltidhari College, Naubatpur]]\n* [[RLSY College, Bakhtiyarpur]]\n* [[RPM College, Patna]]\n* [[Ram Krishna Dwarika College, Patna]]\n* [[Ram Ratan Singh College]]\n* [[SMD College, Punpun]]\n* [[Sri Arvind Mahila College, Patna]]\n* [[Sri Guru Gobind Singh College, Patna]]\n* [[TPS College, Patna]]\n* [[Kisan College, Nalanda]]\n*[[Nalanda College, Biharsharif]]\n*[[Nalanda Mahila College]], Biharsharif\n* [[Sardar Patel Memorial College]]\n* [[SU College, Hilsa]]\n}}\n\n=== Affiliated Colleges ===\n{{columns-list|colwidth=20em|\n* B B M B G Kanya College\n* B L P College, Masaurhi\n* Bansropan Ram Bahadur Singh Yadav College, Kanhauli, Patna\n* Chandradeo Prasad Verma College, Simri, Patna \n* D N College, Masaurhi\n* Dr. C P Thakur College, Naubatpur, Patna\n* Dr. Ram Raj Singh Mahila College, Nalanda\n* Jyoti Kunwar College, Fatehpur, Patna\n* Kameshwar Prasad Singh College, Nadwan\n* L P  Shahi College, Patna\n* P L S  College, Masaurhi \n* [[Paras Nath Kushwaha College]]\n* Patna Muslim Science College, Patna\n* R  P College, Datiyana, Bikram\n* R L S Y Collge, Anishabad, Patna\n* R P S College, Bailey Road, Patna\n* R P S Mahila College, Bailey Road, Patna\n* [[RLSY College, Paliganj]]\n* Ram Roop Prasad College,Patna\n* S K M V College, Fatuha\n* S N A Evening College, Barh\n* Sir Ganesh Dutt Memorial College, Patna\n* Sri Bhuwaneshwari Raja  College, Barh, Patna\n* Deo Sharan Women's Evening College, Sohsarai, Nalanda \n* G D M College, Harnaut\n* K S T College, Sohsarai\n* Lal Singh Tyagi Gramin College, Nalanda\n* Magadh Mahavidyalaya, Chandi, Nalanda\n* Mahabodhi Mahavidyalaya, Nalanda\n* Nalanda Sodh Sansthan\n* P M S College, Paharpura\n* R Lal College, Nalanda\n* R LS Y College, Nalanda\n* R P S College, Harnaut\n* S P College, Hilsa\n* Sadanand, College,  Biharsharif, Nalanda \n* Snatak College, Nalanda\n* Vardhman Mahavir College, Pawapuri\n}}\n\n==Academics==\nAdmitted students of Magadh University (MU) will be awarded degrees by the MU.<ref name=toi1/> The university started operating academically from the 2018\u201319 academic year.<ref name=\"newuniv\">{{Cite web |url=http://governor.bih.nic.in/ORDER/BSU-1590-14062018.pdf |title=Clarification on the issues related to the pending ... \u2013 Governor of Bihar |date=2018-06-14 |website=governor.bih.nic.in |access-date=2018-06-18 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180620094151/http://governor.bih.nic.in/ORDER/BSU-1590-14062018.pdf |archivedate=20 June 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The programmes being offered at the university be the same as the ones being offered at Magadh University.<ref name=toi1>{{Cite web |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/patna/parent-universities-to-hold-exams-of-pupils-shifted-to-new-varsities/articleshow/64606643.cms |title=Parent universities to hold exams of pupils shifted to new varsities \u2013 Times of India |website=The Times of India |access-date=2018-06-16 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180620094136/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/patna/parent-universities-to-hold-exams-of-pupils-shifted-to-new-varsities/articleshow/64606643.cms |archivedate=20 June 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe university plans to launch postgraduate departments in science, commerce and arts stream at university level after many of the postgraduate departments went to MU after the bifurcation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Postgrad classes at Patliputra University |url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/states/bihar/postgrad-classes-at-patliputra-university-235148 |newspaper=[[The Telegraph (India)|The Telegraph]] |location=[[Patna]] |date=4 June 2018 |access-date=21 June 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621090723/https://www.telegraphindia.com/states/bihar/postgrad-classes-at-patliputra-university-235148 |archivedate=21 June 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Some of Patna's better institutions come under Patliputra University after its creation.<ref name=\"telegraph\"/>\n\n==Campus== \nThe university is headquartered in Patna and will administratively operate from Magadh University branch office on [[Kankarbagh]] old bypass in the [[Rajendra Nagar, Patna|Rajendra Nagar]] neighbourhood of Patna,<ref name=\"telegraph\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/patna/new-varsities-give-impetus-to-higher-education-in-state/articleshow/58247467.cms |title=New varsities give impetus to higher education in state \u2013 Times of India |date=2018-04-29 |website=The Times of India |access-date=2018-06-18 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180620094132/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/patna/new-varsities-give-impetus-to-higher-education-in-state/articleshow/58247467.cms |archivedate=20 June 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> whilst, its permanent campus will be located at Beur.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/patna/stage-set-for-mu-bifurcation/articleshow/62299950.cms |title=Stage set for Magadh University bifurcation \u2013 Times of India |website=The Times of India |access-date=2018-06-16 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180620094136/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/patna/stage-set-for-mu-bifurcation/articleshow/62299950.cms |archivedate=20 June 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==See also== \n{{Portal|India}}\n* [[Patna University]]\n* [[Purnea University]]\n* [[Munger University]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official|ppup.ac.in}}\n{{Universities in Bihar}}\n{{Portal bar|India|Education}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Patliputra University}}\n[[Category:Universities in Bihar]]\n[[Category:Patliputra University]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2018]]\n[[Category:2018 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:2018 establishments in Bihar]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Patna]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|University in India}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2018}}\n\n{{Infobox unive